{ Hello and welcome to Lifetime Repertoires: Tarrasch Defense!  My name is Jorden van Foreest and I am a Grandmaster from the Netherlands.  I became a GM back in 2015, during the World Junior Championships in Khanty-Mansiysk, Russia, where I scored my final GM norm. My highest FIDE rating so far is 2715 @@StartBracket@@May 2022@@EndBracket@@. My best achievements were winning the European Youth Championship U14, the Dutch Championship in 2016, and Tata Steel Chess in 2021. I like playing dynamic and enterprising chess, although I can also enjoy a slow endgame grind.  The opening is named after the German player Siegbert Tarrasch, who was one of the best of his time. He was sure that it was the best way to meet 1.d4 and never shied away from the opportunity of playing his opening. After that, it’s been played by several World Champions, most famously Kasparov, but even Carlsen has employed it a couple of times recently in faster time controls.  Currently, the ‘traditional Tarrasch’ is not that popular, hopefully, that will change after this course! 😃 Today’s foremost proponents of the opening are Kasimdzjanov, l’Ami, Nihal Sarin, Gukesh, and Abdusattorov.  I wanted to make this course because I have been been very good at analyzing and fully understanding an opening in-depth, and I have always been quite fond of the Tarrasch Defense, yet I was reluctant to employ it in my games. My first Chessable course was a great opportunity to study the opening and share my insights with the students.  What may you expect from this course? Black typically is prepared to play with the Isolated Queen’s Pawn. This causes us to play with an inferior structure right from the get-go. The advantage of having the isolani is that we have more space in the center, and we will have very smooth development, enabling us to play dynamic and enterprising chess. There is a reason why the Tarrasch has been played by Kasparov, Spassky, Keres, and Grischuk: it allows Black to play for the win right from the beginning.   Let me quickly give you an overview of the course:  Chapter 1: Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bg5  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.g3  Nf6  6.Bg2  Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  8.Nc3  O-O  9.Bg5  is the main variation of the Tarrasch, and the variation you will be most likely to face. Here I recommend playing  9...c4  , which, as the current theory stands, gives Black sufficient counterplay. By closing the center, we will not be playing with an isolani as in most other variations, but will be playing on the queenside instead, especially trying to play for ...b7-b5.   Chapter 2: Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5  A big and important chapter where we will be reaching the pure Tarrasch-style positions, where we will be playing with the isolated pawn. Often White will give up the dark-squared bishop with @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2bp4/8/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bg5  followed by Bxf6, to gain some control over the light squares. In return, we will have the bishop pair, and advance the isolani to d4, where it is well-protected. Here some dry endgames may arise at times as well, which are fine for Black. Two other important lines are @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2bp4/8/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.a3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2bp4/8/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Na4  , where I hope to give some new and fresh ideas.   Chapter 3: Fianchetto With Nc3 – Other 9th Moves  In this chapter, we take a quick look at some reasonably harmless alternatives on move 9, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.g3  Nf6  6.Bg2  Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  8.Nc3  O-O  9.h3  , @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2bp4/8/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2bp4/8/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.b3  . As we will see, those moves aren’t popular for good reason.   Chapter 4: Fianchetto Without Nc3 – 8.dxc5 Bxc5 9.a3  This is another important chapter, as this is a highly topical variation nowadays. I have found a completely new way of playing, by sacrificing a pawn with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.g3  Nf6  6.Bg2  Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.a3  Ne4  10.Nfd2  O-O!?  , which will hopefully shock the opponent. Also, I have an alternative in following the old main line @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n5/2bp4/4n3/P5P1/1P1NPPBP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...f5  , for those interested.   Chapter 5: Fianchetto Without Nc3 – 8.dxc5 Bxc5 – Other 9th Moves  Again, the alternatives shouldn’t trouble us, but we will be prepared if our opponents try to surprise us. We mainly study @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.g3  Nf6  6.Bg2  Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Qc2  in this chapter.  Chapter 6: Fianchetto Without Nc3 – Other 8th Moves  White has many alternatives on move 8 and they are all fairly harmless, but we should be aware of all White’s tries. Once we are, however, these plans are easily dealt with. In general, in the Fianchetto variations, White does not have too much room for creativity - there are only a few critical lines.   Chapter 7: 5.Bg5  This is perhaps the most critical chapter in the entire course. Here we really need to know our theory, as White has several alternatives and play can take any direction. Especially the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Nf6  6.Nc3  Be6  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  8.e4  variation needs to be properly understood. The good thing is that we are virtually guaranteed an interesting game in almost every variation.   Chapter 8: 5th Move Sidelines  There are quite many timid ways of tackling the Tarrasch Defense, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.dxc5  . I have tried recommending variations that preserve our typical Tarrasch themes, so we play with the isolani and aim for maximum piece activity.   Chapter 9: 4th Move Sidelines  A very diverse chapter. If White wants to avoid entering the Tarrasch, and they haven’t studied a good alternative like @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bg5  , they may opt for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.e3  .  White avoids the heavy theory that arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.cxd5  , but instead aims for a calmer setup, while still retaining all the pieces on the board.   Chapter 10: London 2.Bf4  This chapter deals with the London, but as it turns out, even here we have some nice tricks up our sleeve, not allowing London players their usual schematic play.   Chapter 11: Jobava London 2.Nc3  This is a funky chapter, where I have decided to recommend something new. As usual, after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  , we are sticking to the  2...c5  play!   Chapter 12: 1.Nf3 & 1.c4  Fortunately, for us Tarrasch players, the English @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  @@EndBracket@@ is an opening that does not bother us, as White's best is almost always to transpose to our favourite opening. The Reti @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  @@EndBracket@@ is a little different. I settled on an idea Praggnanandhaa has recently been employing with success, which is quite sharp as well. My recommendation is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  2.g3  c5  3.Bg2  Nc6  4.d4  e6  5.O-O  cxd4  6.Nxd4  Bc5  . Immediately challenging White's central knight is the point of 5...cxd4.   Chapter 13: Odds & Ends  This chapter features a couple of nice anti-London move orders. As it turns out, it’s not so easy for White to reach the typical London setup after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  c5!  . Other than that, we will, for example, study the Pseudo-Trompovsky  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bg5  , the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.e4  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  c5  3.e3  , which is a typical choice for those who like to play the Colle system.  Finally, I want to mention that playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. Of course, there are many more specific ideas in the variations that will be discussed throughout the course.  Good luck with the Tarrasch Defense! }
