1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. Named after the great German chess player Siegbert Tarrasch @@StartBracket@@1862-1934@@EndBracket@@, who employed it as early as 1888, was the very first player to use this opening regularly in his play. The aim of going 3...c5 is that Black is challenging the white center as early as possible and fighting for the initiative.  Naturally, such early aggressiveness comes with its risks as Black should generally always be prepared to accept an isolated pawn on d5 after an eventual capture on c5 or exchange on d4. This way of playing has attracted many, and perhaps most notably Garry Kasparov used it as a regular weapon in the 1984 World Championship Match versus Anatoly Karpov.  Nowadays, the Tarrasch Defense is not seen at the highest level as often as the consensus seems to be that White's positional trumps outweigh Black's activity. At the same time, due to its lack of popularity in recent years, there has been lots of room for analysing new ways of playing for both colours and finding innovations.  Finally, I have come to the realization that in fact, the Tarrasch is to this day a completely viable opening that can be played at every level. }
4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6
{ One of the advantages of playing the Tarrasch Defense is that in most of the lines we have a smooth way of developing our pieces. The knights develop themselves to f6 and c6 respectively, and the dark-squared bishop develops itself depending on the situation, followed by castling.   There is however a couple of subtle differences when it comes to bringing out the knights. In this segment, I would like to make clear what those differences are and explain why I recommend  5...Nf6  instead of  5...Nc6  .   Traditionally, Tarrasch connoisseurs have been giving the preference over starting with  5...Nc6  .  During my research, effectively all analytical research seems to be advocating the development of the queen's knight as well.  However, in the last decade, the reply  6.dxc5  has gained significant popularity and is now considered a very serious manner of fighting for an advantage. Whilst I do believe Black has decent ways of meeting this variation, the variations often lead to slightly better endgames for White, with little hope of gaining any of our typical Tarrasch-like activity.   After  5...Nf6  White does gain the extra possibility of  6.Bg5  .  This immediately pinning of the knight is the likely reason why the majority have started by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  .  In recent times the trend seems to have shifted, however, with none other than Magnus Carlsen picking up the Tarrasch with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  for a bit. Moreover, highly-talented Indian players have been adding it to their repertoire as well.   I will show you the slightly passive positions arising after  5...Nc6  . White plays  6.dxc5  d4  7.Na4  Bxc5  8.Nxc5  Qa5+  and has two options now:  9.Bd2  is considered the main move, but White can easily grab an endgame where they will be better due to the pair of bishops with  @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/pp3ppp/2n5/q1N5/3p4/5N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qd2  Qxc5  10.e3  dxe3  11.Qxe3+  Qxe3+  12.Bxe3  . White's advantage is minimal, but I do not like the prospect of giving our opponent such an easy route to an advantage. }
6. Bg5
{ Now, this really has to be met with  6...Be6  .   Another point I would like to address is the following position:  6.g3  Nc6  7.Bg2  , in which I will recommend the former main line  7...Be7  .  Recently another move has gained massively in popularity, being  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd4  .  8.Nxd4  Bc5  is the starting position of what can now safely be called the Dubov-Tarrasch. Named after the great theoretician Daniil Dubov @@StartBracket@@with whom I had the pleasure to work@@EndBracket@@, he brought this variation completely back to life with outstanding results.  I would have added it to my course had not my countrymate Erwin l'Ami already made an excellent course on it for Chessable. Besides, we should take into account that this variation only works with the knight already developed on c3, so it is not a full Tarrasch Repertoire, so we would have to learn the variations starting with 7...Be7 anyhow. }
6... Be6
{ This is the starting point of one of the more serious variations in the course.  I believe that compared to both @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/8/2pp4/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.dxc5  , as discussed earlier, our variations lead to more complex play and chances for counterplay.  Finally, I think that being able to virtually always play ...Nf6 first is a good advantage when it comes to remembering your opening lines. }
