{ I made sure our repertoire is bulletproof by comparing it to other sources @@StartBracket@@for example, Chessable courses and opening books@@EndBracket@@. In the Chessable community, this section is often referred to as 'Repertoire Clashes'.  Here are some, but not all, of the Chessable courses I tried to dismantle:  ♟️ Lifetime Repertoires: The Catalan by GM Srinath Narayanan:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.g3  Nf6  6.Bg2  Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.a3  Ne4  10.Nfd2  f5  11.Nc3  Be6  12.Nb3  Bb6  13.Na4  d4  14.Nd2  Nxd2  15.Bxd2  O-O  16.Nxb6  axb6  17.Bf4  Bd5  18.Qd3  Bxg2  19.Kxg2  Qd5+  20.Qf3  Srinath ends his variation here, claiming a slight advantage for White since they have the better pawn structure. I beg to differ, as I feel our space advantage, and control over the light squares compensates for the structural deficit.  20...Qf7  . We should keep the queens on the board for activity.    ♟️ Lifetime Repertoires: Sam Shankland's 1.d4 - Part 3 by GM Sam Shankland:   Shankland's variation ends after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.g3  Nf6  6.Bg2  Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.a3  Ne4  10.Nfd2  f5  11.Nc3  Be6  12.Nb3  Bb6  13.Na4  , concluding that White will soon win the fight for the d4-square. That is not the case after  13...d4!  , when the pawn on d4 is much more of a strength than a weakness, as it restricts the c1-bishop quite a bit.    ♟️ Keep It Simple: 1.d4 by IM Christof Sielecki   After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.g3  Nf6  6.Bg2  Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.a3  Ne4  10.Nfd2  f5  11.Nxe4  dxe4  12.Qxd8+  Nxd8  13.Nc3  , Sielecki only considers  13...Be6  but @@StartFEN@@r1bnk2r/pp4pp/8/2b2p2/4p3/P1N3P1/1P2PPBP/R1B2RK1 b kq - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Ne6  is a stronger move. The knight immediately jumps back to life and fulfils an important role by making it difficult for White to develop the bishop on c1 since both f4 and g5 are now guarded. A complicated endgame with chances for both sides lies ahead. However, my main recommendation is the fascinating pawn sacrifice  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n5/2bp4/4n3/P5P1/1P1NPPBP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...f5!?  .    ♟️ Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Attack by Kamil Plichta   Plichta concludes that White has a small edge after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  2.g3  c5  3.Bg2  Nc6  4.d4  e6  5.O-O  cxd4  6.Nxd4  Bc5  7.Nb3  Bb6  8.c4  Nge7  9.cxd5  exd5  10.Nc3  O-O  11.Na4  d4  12.Bd2  , which remains to be seen, but one thing is for sure: we will play  12...h5!  . The simple plan of advancing the h-pawn down the board is always surprisingly tough to meet for the opposing side.    ♟️ Go for The Throat: Play 1.d4 by FM Kamil Plichta   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Nf6  6.Nc3  Be6  7.e4  is recommended by Kamil Plichta. While he does an excellent job at convincing his readers about the strength of the move, fortunately for us, it is quite easily dealt with.  7...Be7!  Simple development is the way to go here. Plichta only analyses @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/4bn2/2pp2B1/3PP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq e3 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...dxe4  , after which things indeed could get dangerous for Black.   ♟️ 1.d4 for Ambitious Chess Improvers by Angelika Valkova   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Nf6  6.Nc3  Be6  7.Bxf6  Qxf6  8.e4  dxe4  9.Nxe4  Qf4  10.Bb5+  Nc6  11.Qe2  O-O-O  12.Bxc6  bxc6  13.O-O  Bd5  14.Rae1  is Valkova's deep idea.  14...Kb7!  solves all our problems. Although the game remains sharp, Black is doing alright. My main recommendation, however, is @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp3ppp/2n1b3/1Bp5/3PNq2/5N2/PP2QPPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Be7  – the solid choice.   ♟️ The Solid 1.d4 - Part 1 by GM Adrien Demuth   After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Nf6  6.Nc3  Be6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.e3  O-O  9.Be2  h6  10.Bh4  Nc6  11.O-O  Rc8  12.Rc1  , Demuth only considers the passive  12...Be7  , as was played in Vidit-Carlsen, India 2019  (½-½)  . I agree with Demuth's remark 'the World Champion had to work hard to get a draw' and therefore, I recommend the more active @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/pp3pp1/2n1bn1p/2bp4/7B/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Bb6  . We obtain counterplay with  13.Na4  g5  14.Bg3  Ne4  . The knight stands super strong on e4, and we can continue improving our position in several ways such as ...Qf6 or ...Re8, with ...h5-h4 being a good idea to keep in mind as well.    ♟️ The Principled Queen's Gambit - Part 1 by FM Daniel Barrish   Barrish considers @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nf3  Nf6  6.Bg5  Be6  7.e3  c4  8.Be2  Be7  in one trainable, but we play more actively with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/4bn2/3p2B1/2pP4/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bb4  . This is the most active square for our bishop, so we should certainly position it right here. I covered this variation in 5 trainables and we will reach a highly complex middlegame with chances for both sides.    ♟️ Lifetime Repertoires: London System by GM Liem Quang Le   My variation ends after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  c5  3.e3  Nf6  4.dxc5  e6  5.b4  a5  6.c3  axb4  7.cxb4  b6  8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  10.a4  bxc5  11.b5  g5  12.Bb2  Bd6  13.Qe2  g4  14.Nfd2  Qb8  and Liem analysed a bit deeper:  15.f4  gxf3  16.Nxf3  Rg8  17.O-O  Bc7  18.Nbd2  Rg4  19.Qd1∞  , concluding 'White's next moves are Bc3, h3, while Black will play push the c-pawn and move back the rook to g6. White will play for a5, while Black will try to organize a kingside attack. The position is very double-edged with all results possible.', which is a fair evaluation.    ♟️ Lifetime Repertoires: Jobava London by GM Hans Niemann   Niemann analyses @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  c5  3.e4  dxe4  4.d5  Nf6  5.Nge2  e6  6.Nf4  exd5  7.Nfxd5  Nxd5  8.Qxd5  Qxd5  9.Nxd5  Bd6  10.Be3  Nc6  in great depth, but I prefer @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp3ppp/3b4/2pN4/4p3/4B3/PPP2PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bf5  . As it turns out developing the bishop to f5, followed by the knight to d7 is a good response to White's piece activity.    ♟️ The Jobava London System by GM Simon Williams   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  c5  3.e4  dxe4  4.d5  Nf6  5.Bf4  g6  6.Nb5  . In his course, Simon offers this move, which indeed seems tempting. After a couple of accurate moves, White quickly runs out of tricks, though. After  6...Na6  7.d6  Be6  it is unclear how White can create any further threats and the engines already give Black a close-to-winning advantage of -1,20. }
1. -- *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bg5
{ We have reached what could be considered the main line of the Tarrasch. }
9... c4
{ This closing of the center, and thus precluding White's chance of giving us an isolani is an idea we use frequently in the Tarrasch Defense.  Having created a majority on the queenside, our play will often revolve around utilizing it through ...b7-b5. White, on the other hand, will often attempt to break our structure through b2-b3 or create a central play using e2-e4 and/or f2-f4. }
10. b3 Qa5
{ One of the first things I learned is that in chess, just like in life, moves have consequences. In this case, b2-b3 leaves the knight on c3 unprotected and we should make use of this fact. White has a couple of ways of defending the knight, but all of them have their problems. }
11. Bd2
{ The main move, but the bishop retreating from its active post on g5 does not seem very impressive. }
11... Bb4 { Keeping up the pressure. } 12. Qc2 Re8
{ There were other interesting possibilities as well, but I quite like this one. The knight is ready to jump to e4, and things may get quite tricky for White. }
13. a3 { A tricky move, but we have some tricks up our sleeve as well. } 13...
Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Bf5
{ This clever intermezzo allows us to develop the bishop without losing time retreating the queen. }
15. Qxf5 Qxc3 16. bxc4 Rxe2
{ The right pawn to capture, as the rook suddenly stands very actively on the 2nd rank. }
17. cxd5 Ne7
{ A last accurate move, after which we will capture on d5. We can conclude our position is entirely satisfactory. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bg5
{ We have reached what could be considered the main line of the Tarrasch. }
9... c4
{ This closing of the center, and thus precluding White's chance of giving us an isolani is an idea we use frequently in the Tarrasch Defense.  Having created a majority on the queenside, our play will often revolve around utilizing it through ...b7-b5. White, on the other hand, will often attempt to break our structure through b2-b3 or create a central play using e2-e4 and/or f2-f4. }
10. Ne5
{ This is by far the main move. The knight occupies an active post in the center of the board, and at the same time vacates the long diagonal, so the bishop pressurizes d5. }
10... Be6
{ Developing the bishop and even more importantly, overprotecting d5. In their fight for the opening advantage, White has tried everything under the sun, yet hits a brick wall every time.  It might help us to know that even though White has several options at their disposal, we often play a quick ...h6, immediately challenging the bishop. }
11. Nxc6
{ Not wishing to venture into the long theoretical lines ensuing after for example,  11.f4  , most players have given preference to playing more strategically, hoping of acquiring a small, yet stable advantage due to their better pawn structure. }
11... bxc6 12. b3
{ This is White's point, chipping away at our structure. If we take on b3, White can pressure our pawns on a7 and c6.  They often give up their dark-squared bishop, followed by a knight transfer via a4 to c5. Instead of allowing that to happen, I prefer active counterplay. }
12... h6 { Forcing White's hand. } 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. bxc4
{ The most ambitious approach, but as the position opens up further, our bishops gain in strength.   14.e3  does not have much additional value compared to 14.bxc4: after  14...c5!  White has nothing better than to transpose to the main variation with  15.bxc4  dxc4  . }
14... dxc4 { The pawn on d4 is under siege. } 15. e3
{ White cannot afford to lose their central pawn without a fight. } 15... c5
{ Forcing the position open at any cost. The bishops must and shall be activated. }
16. Bxa8
{ Usually capturing a rook like this would be considered suicide, but here it works as White is just in time to close the long diagonal. }
16... Qxa8
{ This simple recapture seems easiest to me, although one could make a case for  16...cxd4  as well. }
17. d5 { Closing the diagonal at the cost of giving back all the material. }
17... Bxc3 18. dxe6 Bxa1 19. exf7+ Kxf7
{ A highly unusual, yet intelligent recapture. By activating our king, we are already preparing for the endgame. }
20. Qxa1 Qe4
{ In positions with limited material, it is almost always a good idea to centralize your queen. It is simply dominant in the center of the board. }
21. Qb1
{ Not wishing to tolerate our queen any longer, White decides to propose the exchange of queens. }
21... Qxb1 22. Rxb1 Ke6
{ The king marches in to sustain our passers on the c-file. Now it is clear why we captured on f7 with the king back on move 19. Due to our active king, it is White who must think about maintaining equality. }
*


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bg5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bg5
{ We have reached what could be considered the main line of the Tarrasch. }
9... c4
{ This closing of the center, and thus precluding White's chance of giving us an isolani is an idea we use frequently in the Tarrasch Defense.  Having created a majority on the queenside, our play will often revolve around utilizing it through ...b7-b5. White, on the other hand, will often attempt to break our structure through b2-b3 or create a central play using e2-e4 and/or f2-f4. }
10. Ne5
{ This is by far the main move. The knight occupies an active post in the center of the board, and at the same time vacates the long diagonal, so the bishop pressurizes d5. }
10... Be6
{ Developing the bishop and even more importantly, overprotecting d5. In their fight for the opening advantage, White has tried everything under the sun, yet hits a brick wall every time.  It might help us to know that even though White has several options at their disposal, we often play a quick ...h6, immediately challenging the bishop. }
11. f4
{ First tried by Rubinstein in 1908, this energetic move has since been played in many high-level games. White's aim is to either create a bind involving the strong knight on e5 or undermine our e6-bishop by an eventual f4-f5. }
11... Ng4
{ There is no time to waste, and we should initiate counterplay immediately. }
12. Bxe7
{ The exchange of the bishops has been seen in many games, but it is inaccurate. }
12... Nxe7 13. Qd2 { Dealing with the threat of ...Ne3. } 13... Nh6
{ A lovely move, preparing to kick the white knight away from its outpost, after which we will enjoy the better pawn structure. Our knight on h6 is quite strong as well since it will find a nice place on f5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. dxc5
{ This is the second most played move after  9.Bg5  . By releasing the tension in the center, the opponent gives us the isolani immediately.  Play will now revolve around the question of whether the pawn on d5 is a liability or a strength. While White will try to either block or attack it, we can use our active pieces and space advantage, granted by the isolated pawn, to disturb the opponent's plans. }
9... Bxc5
{ There is an option of gambitting the pawn entirely through  9...d4  , but practice has shown that it is best to restore material balance instead. White is at crossroads here, having several ways of completing development.   As for our ideal piece configuration, it is quite straightforward. For the rooks, the ideal positions are generally e8 and c8 or d8, standing useful on the @@StartBracket@@semi-@@EndBracket@@open files. The real question remains for our light-squared bishop, as it might stand well on either e6, f5 or g4 depending on the situation.  As usual, when playing with the isolani we should always be on the lookout for opportunities of pushing it forward at an opportune moment, as the further it advances the more of a menace it becomes to the opponent. }
10. Bg5
{ The old main line and the most direct attempt as it creates a pin and immediate pressure on the isolani.  It is also known as the Timman variation, although players such as Lasker, Capablanca and Euwe all tried it earlier!  In recent years, this variation has faded into the background, however. With some accurate play, Black has been able to neutralize White's pressure fairly easily. }
10... d4
{ Addressing the pressure in the most active way possible by pushing forward, and at the same time forcing the knight to move from c3.  White is now faced with a choice of either moving the knight immediately or capturing on f6 first. }
11. Ne4
{ This is not as popular and not as testing as  11.Bxf6  . Yet, more than 500 people have given it a try so we ought to be ready. }
11... Be7 { Breaking the pin and returning the bishop to safety. } 12. Bxf6
{ The most flexible option by White, as they can still decide whether to capture on f6 later with the knight or not. }
12... Bxf6 13. b4
{ Basically an invitation of exchanging the b-pawn for our d-pawn. } 13... Nxb4
{ Never decline an invitation. } 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15. Qxd4 Qe7
{ An important move, as the endgame after  15...Qxd4  16.Nxd4  would be quite unpleasant.  After the text move, we are ready to bring our knight back home with ...Nc6. The position is highly drawish, but in the long run, our queenside majority might offer some prospects. }
16. Qe5
{ Insisting on the exchange of queens, but things are a little bit different now.   16.Qb2  is the main line in Kotronias's book Fight 1.d4 with the Tarrasch, but modern engines don't see a glimpse of an issue for Black after  16...Nc6  , retreating the knight back to greener pastures.  17.Rfd1  Be6  Black's development has been really smooth, and with the queenside majority the balance can easily swing in our favour. In general, exchanging pieces is not undesirable as endgames will be good for us. }
16... Qxe5 17. Nxe5 Re8
{ Here's the difference, as the pawn on e2 will be hanging whenever the knight moves. }
18. Rfd1 { White has to resort to some tactics to keep the game balanced. }
18... g6
{ A novelty, but quite a logical one at that. Eliminating any back-rank checkmates and reinforcing the threat to the knight. }
19. Nc4 Be6
{ The correct approach, developing the bishop.   Instead,  19...Rxe2  20.Rd8  would still have been rather awkward to meet. }
20. Nd6
{ The knight keeps on jumping, but a lone knight can not do that much damage. }
20... Re7 21. Nxb7 Bxa2
{ Material is equal and already very limited as well - the draw is not far away. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. dxc5
{ This is the second most played move after  9.Bg5  . By releasing the tension in the center, the opponent gives us the isolani immediately.  Play will now revolve around the question of whether the pawn on d5 is a liability or a strength. While White will try to either block or attack it, we can use our active pieces and space advantage, granted by the isolated pawn, to disturb the opponent's plans. }
9... Bxc5
{ There is an option of gambitting the pawn entirely through  9...d4  , but practice has shown that it is best to restore material balance instead. White is at crossroads here, having several ways of completing development.   As for our ideal piece configuration, it is quite straightforward. For the rooks, the ideal positions are generally e8 and c8 or d8, standing useful on the @@StartBracket@@semi-@@EndBracket@@open files. The real question remains for our light-squared bishop, as it might stand well on either e6, f5 or g4 depending on the situation.  As usual, when playing with the isolani we should always be on the lookout for opportunities of pushing it forward at an opportune moment, as the further it advances the more of a menace it becomes to the opponent. }
10. Bg5
{ The old main line and the most direct attempt as it creates a pin and immediate pressure on the isolani.  It is also known as the Timman variation, although players such as Lasker, Capablanca and Euwe all tried it earlier!  In recent years, this variation has faded into the background, however. With some accurate play, Black has been able to neutralize White's pressure fairly easily. }
10... d4
{ Addressing the pressure in the most active way possible by pushing forward, and at the same time forcing the knight to move from c3.  White is now faced with a choice of either moving the knight immediately or capturing on f6 first. }
11. Bxf6
{ In general, one does not want to exchange the bishop for a knight unprovoked, but White does gain a couple of tempi on our queen after the c3-knight jumps to either e4 or d5. }
11... Qxf6
{ Once again White is faced with a choice. They could either simplify the position more through  12.Ne4  Qe7  13.Nxc5  , or be more adventurous with  @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp3ppp/2n2q2/2b5/3p4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nd5  . }
12. Ne4
{ I feel this gives Black a reasonably smooth game.   If White wants to put some pressure,  12.Nd5  is better  . }
12... Qe7 13. Nxc5 { The only logical follow-up. } 13... Qxc5
{ After a bunch of exchanges, we have reached a very typical position for the Tarrasch Defence. Although exchanges are generally good for the side playing against the isolani @@StartBracket@@White@@EndBracket@@, as it reduces the amount of piece play, I do not think this is the case here.  The pawn on d4 is securely protected and cramps White's position quite a bit. Moreover, our pieces will easily find active positions. White generally either transfers the knight from f3 to d3 via e1 or centralizes the rooks.   In either case, our approach remains the same regardless: we play the subtle but highly useful move ...h6, develop our bishop, bring the rooks to the center and take it from there. }
14. Rc1 { A logical move, gaining a tempo on our queen. } 14... Qb6
{ The best square for our queen, attacking the pawn on b2 and keeping d4 protected at all times. }
15. Qc2 { Creating an idea of Ng5, but this is easily dealt with. } 15... h6
{ Stopping any funny business with Ng5. This move is always going to be useful anyhow, as it takes any future back-rank checkmates out of the equation as well. }
16. Rfd1 Be6
{ Developing the bishop with a tempo, as we surely would like to take on a2 if given the opportunity. }
17. b3 Rfe8
{ There are many ways of approaching the position for Black. In fact, most players have given preference to  17...Rfd8  instead, but I quite like the position of the rook here, as the pawn on e2 may become a target in the future. }
18. Qc5
{ Offering the exchange of queens, but we will nevertheless maintain an active position. }
18... Qxc5
{ So we are happily accepting the offer. We obviously want to deny White the opportunity of damaging our structure with Qxb6. }
19. Rxc5 Rac8
{ The final inactive piece joins the game and our army is now fully mobilized. Ideas like ...Nb4 or ...a5-a4, are very much on the agenda, keeping White busy. There is actually one more cute idea, that is well worth remembering. }
20. Rc2 { Intending to play Rcd2 and win our pawn at long last. } 20... d3
{ Quite the surprise! The isolated pawn suddenly sacrifices itself.   We are relying on some clever tactics to afford this. The main point is that the positionally desirable  21.Rxd3  runs into  21...Bf5  , winning material. }
21. exd3
{ The only capture remaining, but the white pieces have lost coordination for just a moment, and we can take advantage of that with another blow. }
21... Bg4
{ Through our pawn sacrifice we have made White lose control over the d4-square entirely and suddenly a strong threat of ...Nd4 is created. }
22. h3 { Perhaps White's safest choice, forcing the game into a rook endgame. }
22... Bxf3 23. Bxf3 Nd4
{ The knight stands beautifully on d4, but unfortunately, just for one moment. }
24. Rxc8 Nxf3+ 25. Kg2 Nh4+
{ An astute intermediate move, ruining the white pawn structure altogether. }
26. gxh4 Rxc8
{ Even though White is up a pawn in this rook endgame, they cannot hope for any advantage since both our rook and our pawn structure are far superior. }
*


