14. Rc1 { Attacking the bishop and forcing us to make a decision. } 14... Bf8
{ Historically,  14...Bb6  has been the most popular move, and although it certainly has its merits, I prefer the text. We are making sure that the bishop is safe and secure for a long time to come.  At the same time, I find our position very aesthetically pleasing! Even though all our pieces except the knight are on the back rank, everything is well coordinated and the bishops are ready to spring into action at any time. }
15. Nb3
{ Creating immediate threats to the d4-pawn is certainly challenging, and we must know how to deal with it. }
15... Be6 { The knight is forced to retreat through a counterattack. } 16. Nf4
Qb6
{ An important move to remember, as it is somewhat counterintuitive. Generally, we do not want to part with our light-squared bishop so easily, as the bishop on g2 can become extremely strong.  In this case, however, we can afford to do so, since our pieces will occupy excellent positions and the knight on b3 will be very awkward after the exchange. }
17. Nxe6 Rxe6
{ The arrows indicate a great number of plans available to us. White finds it hard to move. Rerouting the b3-knight to greener pastures is impossible because it would leave the b2-pawn hanging. }
18. Rc2
{ White's best chance, securing the second rank and intending to bring the rook to d2.   A small trick to note is that  18.Bxc6?!  bxc6  19.Nxd4??  loses to  19...Rd8!  20.e3  c5  , winning a piece. }
18... Rae8
{ There are many ways of playing the position, but I like Stockfish's very concrete suggestion. }
19. Rd2 Bb4
{ Forcing White to go down a tactical skirmish, since otherwise the previous play would be rendered useless. }
20. Nxd4 Bxd2 21. Nxe6 Bh6 { Suddenly the knight on e6 is somewhat trapped. }
22. Bxc6
{ Forcing us to be precise.   22.Nf4  Bxf4  23.gxf4  Qxb2  leads to full equality. }
22... bxc6
{ The only correct recapture, as  23.Nd4  now loses a piece after  23...Rd8  24.e3  c5  . }
23. Qd7
{ A cute intermezzo, but it does not change the situation as the knight remains in peril after we simply move our rook. }
23... Rb8 24. Nf4 Bxf4
{ Eliminating the knight and destroying the white pawn structure at the same time. }
25. gxf4 Qxb2
{ The game is completely balanced. The vulnerable white king offers Black plenty of counterplay. }
