[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Fianchetto Without Nc3 – 8.dxc5 Bxc5 9.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. dxc5
{ White releases the tension as soon as we have played ...Be7, forcing us to spend another tempo recapturing. Moreover, it should be noted that White has delayed the development of the b1-knight. By doing so, White gets access to a couple of new setups that need to be investigated. }
8... Bxc5 9. Bg5
{ It is possible to start with this move, but the likelihood of play soon transposing to variations we are familiar with is high.   9.Nc3  is a direct transposition to the chapter Fianchetto with Nc3 – 9.dxc5 Bxc5. }
9... O-O 10. Qc1 { An interesting way to try and confuse us. } 10... Be7
{ In the Qc2 lines, we could keep the bishop on the active diagonal due to some ...Bf5 tactics down the line. With the queen on c1, however, these tactics do not work and we should retreat the bishop back the other way. }
11. Nc3 Be6
{ It is easy to be tempted by  11...d4  , but  12.Rd1!  is a venomous reply. Therefore, it is better to keep the pawn on d5 for the moment. }
12. Rd1 h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. e4
{ An exciting move to make, but it will quickly dry up the board. In any case, with the bishop pair, we should be doing fine after alternative moves as well. }
14... d4 { Forcing matters. } 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Qxd5 17. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ Other moves are possible, but this is the most effective way of killing the game. }
18. Bxd5 Ne2+ 19. Kg2 Nxc1 20. Raxc1 Rac8
{ Lots of trades later we have reached a dead-drawn endgame. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Fianchetto Without Nc3 – 8.dxc5 Bxc5 9.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. dxc5
{ White releases the tension as soon as we have played ...Be7, forcing us to spend another tempo recapturing. Moreover, it should be noted that White has delayed the development of the b1-knight. By doing so, White gets access to a couple of new setups that need to be investigated. }
8... Bxc5 9. Qc2
{ A crafty move, asking where the bishop would like to go. Depending on our next move, White will make up their mind about where to develop the pieces. On the flip side, the queen on c2 can be awkwardly placed, as it might come under attack by one of our minor pieces early on.   9.Nc3  is a direct transposition to the chapter Fianchetto with Nc3 – 9.dxc5 Bxc5. }
9... Bb6
{ The only correct choice, keeping the bishop as active as possible on the diagonal. }
10. Nc3 O-O
{ Unless you're playing Kramnik chess, castling is almost always a good idea!   Don't get coaxed into playing  10...d4  , since after  11.Na4  the isolani might quickly fall prey to the enemy pieces. }
11. Bg5
{ The main line of the variation. The opponent intends to exert great pressure on our isolani before it becomes a force to be reckoned with. Since the white queen is already on c2, the rooks are free to occupy the d-file, mounting the pressure even further. }
11... d4
{ In 70 out of the 73 games in my database,  11...Be6  was played. Although there is not much wrong with the move, it does seem a little bit passive.  The text move gives a much more active impression, which is why I chose to recommend it instead. In fact, the position is of great similarity to the 9.dxc5 Bxc5 10.Bg5 variation, with the only difference being White's queen on c2 and our bishop standing on b6 instead of c5. }
12. Ne4
{ This looks like a nasty pin, but we have a creative way of solving our problems. }
12... Bf5
{ A clever solution, highlighting the drawback of White's queen on c2. } 13.
Nh4
{ The only critical move, as the tactics work out nicely for us in case of  13.Nxf6+  Qxf6!  14.Bxf6  Bxc2  .   Also  13.Bxf6  gxf6  is no problem since our light-squared bishop can easily drop back to g6, securing our king. }
13... Bxe4 { The start of a small series of trades. } 14. Bxe4 h6
{ Forcing White to give up one of the bishops as well. } 15. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ We have arrived at a very interesting position. Due to the presence of opposite-coloured bishops, White is reigning over the light squares, while we have strong control over the dark squares.  We should try to take as much control over the squares dominated by the opponent as possible. A good start is placing as many pawns on the light squares, through ...g6 and ...h5. After doing so, our king will find a nice place on g7 as well. }
16. Nf3 Rfe8 17. a3
{ So far we have been following the game Andreikin-Shipov, 2021. Albeit, only being an internet blitz game, both are strong GMs who have been playing the opening stage excellently so far. }
17... g6
{ Improving upon the aforementioned game, by initiating the plan of controlling the light squares.  After we bring our a8-rook into the game and improve our king to g7 we have a very solid position. We can consider offering the trade of knights with a timely ...Ne5 as well, steering the game towards drawish positions. }
