[Black "Fianchetto Without Nc3 – 8.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Be3
{ Korchnoi employed this rare sideline no less than four times in his tournament games, including one versus Kasparov, so I think it's fair to dub it the Korchnoi Variation. }
8... c4
{ The most principled reaction, as the bishop on e3 suddenly looks like a big pawn in an awkward position. }
9. Ne5 O-O 10. b3
{ A typical idea, chipping away at our structure.   10.Nc3  transposes to the 9.Be3 move from the Fianchetto with Nc3 – 9th Move Alternatives chapter. }
10... cxb3 11. Qxb3
{ We have arrived at a critical moment, where many players have not found the most accurate continuation, one of them being Garry Kasparov. }
11... Bd6
{ Challenging White's central knight solves our problems comfortably.   Instead, after  11...Qb6  12.Rc1!  , Korchnoi managed to get the upper hand in Korchnoi-Kasparov, London 1983, even though Kasparov eventually went on to win the game. }
12. f4
{ A serious positional concession, but there was no good alternative method of maintaining the advanced position of the knight. }
12... Ne7
{ One of many satisfactory solutions. The knight is heading to the weakened light squares and overprotecting on d5. With all the positional trumps being in our favour, Black already takes over the initiative. }
