1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5
{ A vicious variation that should be studied carefully. As I have not been able to find a name for this variation yet, I will call it the Korchnoi Variation. He was one of the first players to employ it regularly at a high level. }
5... Nf6
{ As explained in the intro, this is our choice at all times.   5...Be7  is the most popular choice but the exchange of bishops leads to somewhat worse and passive positions for us, with no hope for more than a draw. }
6. Nc3 Be6
{ This position signifies a major component in our repertoire. White is at crossroads and it is our task to carefully examine their options. To clarify things, White has about 3 ways to approach the position:  1. They can either prepare for a quick assault going e2-e4, creating a sharp mess in the process.  2. Most people give preference to playing a slower game through e2-e3, intending to simply develop the bishop and castle.  3. Last, but certainly, not least is the ever-existing option of a fianchetto by going g2-g3. There are a few other sidelines, but they are no reason for concern. }
7. e4
{ This is recommended by Kamil Plichta in his course: Go for the throat - Play 1.d4. While he does an excellent job at convincing his readers about the strength of the move, fortunately for us, it is quite easily dealt with.   If White does wish to play aggressive with e2-e4, it is more dangerous to play with  7.Bxf6  first. }
7... Be7
{ Simple development is the way to go here.   Plichta only analyses  7...dxe4  , after which things indeed could get dangerous for Black. }
8. Bb5+
{ The most popular move and the logical follow-up after 7.e4.   8.Bxf6  is highly likely to transpose after an eventual Bb5+:  8...Bxf6  9.Bb5+  Nc6  is covered here and  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/pp3ppp/4bb2/2pp4/3PP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.exd5  Bxd5  10.Bb5+  Nc6  also transposes. }
8... Nc6
{ There is no reason to be worried about the pin since we will have an excellent position as soon we manage to castle. As a consequence, White has to act immediately. }
9. Bxf6
{ The only capture where White can hope for a tiny bit of pressure.   9.e5  Nd7  10.Bxe7  Qxe7  transposes. }
9... Bxf6 10. O-O
{ White does best to castle, as releasing the tension in the center does not lead anywhere. }
10... dxe4
{ The alternative  10...O-O  would be alright too, but here it is best to go down a forced variation and equalize on the spot. }
11. d5
{ That was White's pawn, but we should not be feared and just continue capturing stuff. }
11... exf3 12. dxc6 O-O { Finally the time to castle has come! } 13. cxb7 Rb8
14. Qxf3 Bxc3 { Using a little tactic to get rid of the passed pawn on b7. }
15. bxc3 Bd5 16. Qf4 Rxb7
{ We have reached an almost symmetrical position, and a draw is likely. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "5.Bg5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5
{ A vicious variation that should be studied carefully. As I have not been able to find a name for this variation yet, I will call it the Korchnoi Variation. He was one of the first players to employ it regularly at a high level. }
5... Nf6
{ As explained in the intro, this is our choice at all times.   5...Be7  is the most popular choice but the exchange of bishops leads to somewhat worse and passive positions for us, with no hope for more than a draw. }
6. Nc3 Be6
{ This position signifies a major component in our repertoire. White is at crossroads and it is our task to carefully examine their options. To clarify things, White has about 3 ways to approach the position:  1. They can either prepare for a quick assault going e2-e4, creating a sharp mess in the process.  2. Most people give preference to playing a slower game through e2-e3, intending to simply develop the bishop and castle.  3. Last, but certainly, not least is the ever-existing option of a fianchetto by going g2-g3. There are a few other sidelines, but they are no reason for concern. }
7. e3
{ Since direct attempts can be met in a good way, most people have preferred the text, wishing to play a slower game and complete development through means of Be2 and castling before committing to action. }
7... c4
{ As in many other variations in the Tarrasch, we use this idea of gaining space on the queenside. At the same time enlarging the scope of our bishop on f8, and diminishing that of the bishop on f1.  White, on the other hand, will usually attempt to break our structure by e3-e4 or b2-b3, or at times attempt to put pressure on the d5-pawn. }
8. Be2
{ The logical follow-up after the last move, and the one that is by far the most popular as well. }
8... Bb4
{ The most active square for our bishop, so we should certainly position it right here.   9.Qa4+  is no worry to us as  9...Nc6  easily deals with that. }
9. O-O Nbd7
{ An uncommon move in the Tarrasch defence, and less popular than  9...O-O  . Yet, I have chosen to recommend this move in favour of the alternative. Although both moves are highly likely to transpose into one another, I found that  10.e4  is not particularly easy to meet if we start by castling.  As it transpires, we will be better prepared to meet the push of White's e-pawn after 9...Nbd7, while not giving up much else. The other reason for developing the knight to d7 instead of the traditional c6, is the overprotection of its colleague on f6, making it easier for our queen to remove itself from the pin. }
10. Ne5
{ If White wants to fight for the advantage, this active move has to be played. At times f2-f4 may be an idea, and it also frees f3 for the bishop. }
10... O-O 11. Nxd7
{ Seemingly the most tempting choice, ruining our pawn structure on the kingside for good. }
11... Qxd7
{ The only right recapture, as  11...Bxd7  would run into  12.Nxd5!  . } 12.
Bxf6 gxf6
{ Thus, our pawn structure on the kingside is not the prettiest in the history of the game of chess. But by now this should be a familiar sight and we should be aware of the advantages our position has as well.  The bishop pair in combination with our majority over on the queenside will generate good counterplay. Moreover, our doubled pawns are no easy target whatsoever, and we can easily make them a strength playing ...f5 and stopping e3-e4 forever. }
13. Bf3 Kh8
{ There were a wealth of different options at our disposal, but I quite like this move. Tucking away our king is always going to be beneficial, and who knows, in the distant future we might use the g-file for an attack. }
14. a3 Bxc3
{ It is good to be aware that if provoked by a2-a3 this often is a good exchange for us. Even though we lose the bishop pair, there is no more pressure on d5, and we get to improve our light-squared bishop. }
15. bxc3 Bf5
{ Our bishop stands excellently here and by now, we are ready to advance on the queenside. If needed, we can stop e3-e4 by ...Rfe8. }
