[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5
{ 4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.cxd5  exd5  5.dxc5  Bxc5  . }
4... exd5 5. dxc5
{ This allows us to develop our bishop to c5 in one go, which should be quite a good achievement for us. Back in the old days, people often used to play ...Be7-xc5 in many lines.   5.e3  Nf6  transposes to 4th Move Sidelines. }
5... Bxc5 6. Qc2
{ This has virtually never been seen, but it is the computer's top choice and therefore must be considered. }
6... Qb6
{ Not only defending the bishop but also attacking f2.   It is useful to realize that  6...Bb6  would be a good move if not for  7.Bg5  , which is uncomfortable to meet. }
7. e3 Nf6 8. Be2 Nc6 9. a3
{ A clever way for White to continue the game. By preparing b2-b4, it is not immediately possible for us to break free through ...d5-d4. }
9... Bd6
{ A smart pre-emptive move in reply. By withdrawing the bishop, we ensure that we can always meet b2-b4 with ...a7-a5. It is also useful to realize that generally, it would be preferable to play ...Bb6, since from there it supports the ...d5-d4 push. In this case, however, our queen occupies that very square. }
10. b4 a5 { Forcing White to compromise their pawn structure in some way. } 11.
b5
{ The most ambitious move.   After  11.bxa5  Nxa5  we have lots of activity on the queenside. }
11... Ne5 12. Nbd2 Be6
{ Slightly more accurate than castling immediately as now we are ready to bother White utilizing ...Rc8. }
13. Bb2 Rc8 14. Qa4 Ned7
{ In general, when playing with the isolani, we should try to keep minor pieces on the board to compensate for our small structural deficit by piece activity. This last move does just that and intends to bring the knight over to c5. The position is dynamically balanced. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4th Move Sidelines – 4.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With  3.Nc3  , White could intend to play  3...c5  4.cxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.dxc5  . However, reaching the fianchetto main lines @@StartBracket@@with Nc3@@EndBracket@@ is still the most likely scenario. }
3... c5
{ Once in a while, you might face an adventurous opponent or simply someone that is scared to enter the frightening Tarrasch Defense main lines and then it is good to be prepared for such scenarios by checking out the sidelines. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing the knight before securing the center is a very provocative approach. We'll be able to make the white knights dance all over the board. }
4... cxd4
{ Since this is a Tarrasch course, we could play  4...Nf6  with a clear conscience, since White has no better than to transpose to the Tarrasch main lines.  However, we shouldn't let White off the hook so easily and try to punish them whenever possible. }
5. Nxd4
{ In case of  5.Qxd4  Nc6  followed by ...d4, White is already close to losing, just 5 moves in. }
5... e5 { Time to make the knights dance. } 6. Nf3
{ Retreating the knight is the most popular move, yet also a severe mistake since it allows us to grab even more space with tempo. }
6... d4 { Now the second knight has to move. } 7. Nxe5
{ Perhaps White thinks they have tricked us, since after the impulsive  7...dxc3  , White ends up winning material after  8.Qxd8  Kxd8  9.Nxf7+  and Nxh8. But, we are not forced to capture the knight immediately. }
7... f6
{ Attacking the second knight, after which White has run out of tricks and a knight will be lost. }
