[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4th Move Sidelines – 4.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. g3
{ A logical choice for those who prefer to play the Catalan. However, things are vastly different from the regular Catalan, since there is already a lot of tension in the center.   4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to the main line of the 5th Move Sidelines chapter. }
4... cxd4
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move.   Another interesting and more solid option is  4...dxc4  5.Bg2  Nc6  , since White has nothing better than  6.Qa4  which leads to an equal position after  6...cxd4  7.Nxd4  Qxd4  8.Bxc6  Bd7  9.Be3!?  Bxc6  10.Qxc6  Qd7  11.Qxc4  .  After the text, there are no easy simplifications available to White. }
5. Bg2
{ In typical Catalan style, it is probably best to develop instead of trying to regain the lost pawn. }
5... Bb4+
{ This smart check ensures that White won't regain the pawn so easily. } 6. Bd2
Bc5
{ Securely protecting the d4-pawn. Now that the d-file is blocked, White cannot play Nxd4 and has to prove compensation. }
7. b4
{ Trying to regain the pawn before it's too late. On the other hand, the b4-pawn might weaken White's position in some cases.   7.cxd5  is a sensible alternative, especially as we should not recapture with the queen here.  7...exd5!  The typical Tarrasch recapture serves us well.   7...Qxd5  should be avoided since after  8.O-O  White's initiative is surprisingly venomous.  8.b4  Bb6   It would also be possible to play  8...Be7  instead, transposing to my note to the 8th move in the 7.b4 variation. The text is an extra option we might as well use, keeping the d4-pawn protected.  9.O-O  Nf6  followed by castling, while White should still spend some tempi in order to regain the pawn. Black can continue in typical Tarrasch fashion, e.g. occupying the e-file with the rook, developing the knight to c6 and the bishop to g4. }
7... Be7 { The safest square.   7...Bb6  is worse because of  8.c5  . } 8. cxd5
Qxd5
{ Funnily enough,  8...exd5  would give us a decent Tarrasch since the b4-pawn creates a lot of light-squared weaknesses in White's position.  The text move is even more ambitious since we are hanging on to the pawn. We can continue developing, with the burden still on White to prove enough compensation. }
