[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "London 2.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ I never considered the London as a serious opening until Carlsen started having great success with it back in 2015. I even picked it up myself and scored some nice wins with it in the process. Nowadays, the London is considered a mainstream opening, and it is popular at all levels. }
2... c5
{ The most aggressive way of tackling the London system, and also nicely in the spirit of the Tarrasch Defense. This early combative approach may take London players aback, as they usually strive for a slower game. }
3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 cxd4
{ With this exchange we're heading for a Carlsbad structure. } 5. exd4 Bf5
{ So, we have reached the typical Carlsbad structure, where White has the c- and d- pawns against our e- and d-pawns. Typically, we should use the minority attack later on with ...b7-b5-b4. While that way of playing is certainly decent, I tried to find a new way of approaching the position and to cast some surprise value upon the opponent. }
6. c3 e6 7. Nbd2 { White simply develops in rudimentary London fashion. } 7...
h5
{ If this doesn't surprise your opponent, I do not know what will. Besides the shock effect, the idea behind the move is to gain some space on the kingside, usually by following it up with ...f6 and ...g5 and therefore discourage the opponent from castling.   A similar version of this idea is  7...f6  , which has been seen in some games, but in that case,  8.Nh4  is slightly awkward to meet. }
8. Be2
{ Since our last move is still a novelty, we can't be exactly sure how White will respond, this one seems the most logical to me. }
8... f6 { Intending to gain further space on the kingside. } 9. h4
{ If  9.O-O  we would play  9...g5  with a fantastic kingside initiative. }
9... Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. O-O Nh6
{ The knight jumps to g4, where it will be a constant menace to White. The destiny of our king isn't clear yet. Ideally, we want to play as ambitiously as possible by castling queenside, with a fun game ahead. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Jobava London 2.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3
{ The Jobava London has become increasingly popular recently. Besides the creative genius of Baadur Jobava, both Simon Williams and Hans Niemann have created successful Chessable courses on the opening that have boosted the popularity even further.  Conventional wisdom holds that one should not place the knight on c3 before pushing the c-pawn to c4, but proponents of this variation have found ways to justify this way of playing. White will often aim to play for an early e2-e4, or start expanding on the kingside through f2-f3 and g2-g4. }
2... c5
{ 2...Nf6  is the main move, but besides the Jobava London with  3.Bf4  , there also exists the possibility of playing the Veresov Attack with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bg5  .  As I have stressed, our idea is to meet virtually every line except for 2.c4 with 2...c5. This is no exception. By immediately striking in the center, we severely limit White in their options. }
3. e4
{ The only principled way of playing. White must strike back in the center. }
3... dxe4
{ The pawn must be captured! At the same time, the d4-pawn is now hanging, so White must continue energetically. }
4. d5
{ The only way to keep the game complicated. The advanced pawn takes control over a number of important squares. }
4... Nf6 { Sometimes, chess speaks for itself. } 5. Nge2
{ The knight is heading to either g3 or f4 depending on circumstances. } 5...
e6
{ There are a number of ways to approach the position but I prefer this one the most. The d5-pawn is a serious asset which is preferably eliminated as soon as possible. }
6. Nf4 { The knight leaps forward to join in the fight for the d5-square. }
6... exd5
{ Deviating from the game Niemann-Duda in which  6...a6  was played, leading to fascinating positions.  The text entails some exchanges after which the position will enter the endgame. }
7. Nfxd5 Nxd5 8. Qxd5
{ The exchange of queens is forced since  8.Nxd5  Be6  is bad news for White. }
8... Qxd5 9. Nxd5
{ Due to the exchange of queens, Nc7+ is threatened, which must be addressed. }
9... Bd6
{ The only reasonable way of covering the c7-square. Although the d5-knight is standing mightily, we are still up one pawn for which White needs to prove compensation. }
10. Be3
{ Developing the bishop, and ensuring that White can castle queenside on the next turn. }
10... Bf5
{ As it turns out developing the bishop to f5, followed by the knight to d7 is a good response to White's piece activity. }
11. O-O-O Nd7
{ The computer suggests that  11...Nc6  is completely fine as well but after  12.Nf6+  a lot of tactics arise in the position and we must be careful.  The text is a more practical way of developing, ensuring that everything is well protected and getting ready to castle queenside ourselves.   In this case, @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1n1ppp/3b4/2pN1b2/4p3/4B3/PPP2PPP/2KR1B1R w kq - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nf6+  Nxf6  13.Rxd6  b6  14.Bb5+  Ke7  is completely fine for us. If anyone is better, it's Black with the extra pawn. To keep enough compensation, White must keep pieces on the board. }
