[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5
{ One of the great benefits of playing the Tarrasch is that virtually any other move than 2.c4 can be met by 2...c5. Especially after 2.Nf3, this is a great shortcut, avoiding loads of sidelines.  For example, many London players may wish to play 2.Nf3 and then 3.Bf4, but now they no longer have such an option.   Objectively, White's best move is  3.c4  , but after  3...e6  we transpose back to the main body of the course. I recently was able to use this in my own practice when facing GM Tabatabaei from Iran in the 2022 Olympiad. }
3. dxc5
{ If White does not wish to transpose to theoretical variations at all costs, this may be the best try, at least gaining a pawn for the moment. }
3... Nf6 { Natural development is best. } 4. c4
{ It would have been more critical to make this move on the previous or second move, but then again better late than never as the saying goes.   4.e3  e6  5.b4  a5  6.c3  transposes to 2.Nf3 c5 3.e3 #2. }
4... e6 5. Be3
{ A quirky idea which has once been tried by Chinese GM Li Chao.   5.cxd5  Bxc5  6.Qc2  transposes to a position that is normally reached through the 5.Qc2 move order. }
5... Nbd7
{ There are other possibilities, but this one appears to be the most enticing of all. For now, we simply intend to capture on c5, so White better comes up with something good. }
6. cxd5 { This is where the fun is at. } 6... Nxd5 7. Bd4 Bxc5
{ We happily offer the g7-pawn, as White will need to move the bishop for a fourth@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ time in eight moves, to capture it. }
8. Bxg7 Rg8 9. Bd4 e5
{ Another cool pawn sacrifice, which can not be accepted. } 10. Bxc5
{ White is forced to make this exchange, as our initiative after  10.Bxe5  Nxe5  11.Nxe5  Qd6  would be insanely powerful. }
10... Nxc5
{ With two powerful horses in the center of the board, and an open g-file to work with we certainly have good play here for the lost pawn. }
11. Nxe5
{ Capturing another pawn is incredibly risky, but also versus other moves our initiative would have been strong. }
11... Be6 12. Nc3 Qc7
{ A nifty move, as  13.Nxd5  is conveniently met by  13...Qxe5  . At the same time, we are ready to castle queenside on the next turn, with fantastic play. Even objectively, the computers already prefer Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5
{ One of the great benefits of playing the Tarrasch is that virtually any other move than 2.c4 can be met by 2...c5. Especially after 2.Nf3, this is a great shortcut, avoiding loads of sidelines.  For example, many London players may wish to play 2.Nf3 and then 3.Bf4, but now they no longer have such an option.   Objectively, White's best move is  3.c4  , but after  3...e6  we transpose back to the main body of the course. I recently was able to use this in my own practice when facing GM Tabatabaei from Iran in the 2022 Olympiad. }
3. c3
{ A rather timid approach, but possible if White just wishes to get a game of chess without too much theory. }
3... Nf6 4. Bf4
{ The only independent option, hoping to transpose to the London. However, these days this particular move order is not popular, as Black has a couple of attractive extra options at their disposal. }
4... Nc6 5. e3 Nh5
{ Specifically this idea of immediately chasing after White's bishop seems to be rather tough to face for White. }
6. dxc5
{ The most challenging response. In the other variations, White loses the bishop pair with not much to show for it. }
6... Nxf4 7. exf4 e6
{ Intending to regain the pawn, which if managed would give us a significantly better position with the bishop pair and better structure. }
8. b4 a5 9. Bb5
{ The logical way of keeping the pawn. Other moves appear much more cumbersome. }
9... axb4 10. cxb4 g5
{ A beautiful idea, which I certainly haven't seen before, exploiting the weakness of the long diagonal. }
11. fxg5
{ I feel this is the most practical decision since White can't stop our bishop from moving to g7. }
11... Bg7 12. Nbd2 { Hoping to make us accept the exchange sacrifice. } 12...
O-O
{ It is important not to get tempted by capturing on a1. The bishop on g7 is far stronger than the rook on a1. Despite being two pawns down, Black is quite a bit better. Our central pawns have a free path up the board, which backed up by the bishop pair will be a mighty force. }
