[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1a) Fianchetto With Nc3 – Introduction to 9.Bg5"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – Introduction to 9.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O
{ Once again, White can opt to develop the knight first with  7.Nc3  . The development scheme for Black will be the same.  7...Be7!  is my preferred choice.   7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bc5  , as explained in the Introduction of this course, is the starting position of the Dubov Tarrasch which is covered in the course of my Dutch colleague Erwin l'Ami. }
7... Be7
{ The advantage of keeping the knight on b1 is seen in the variation arising after 7...cxd4.   7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bc5?  Since White's queen's knight hasn't been developed yet, this option isn't really feasible for Black. White has a strong reply in store.  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.Qc2!  The bishop is attacked, and a potential retreat would leave the c6-pawn hanging. The defense of the bishop is awkward, so Black has a hard time solving their problems. After  10...Qb6  11.Nc3  , the knight's move to edge with Na4 is a serious threat and Black is in a world of trouble. }
8. Nc3
{ Having avoided the Dubov Tarrasch, clever players only develop the knight now. If White does not wish to do so, there is  8.dxc5  as a serious alternative that will be thoroughly analysed in its respective chapter. }
8... O-O 9. Bg5
{ We have reached what could be considered the main line of the Tarrasch. }
9... c4
{ We will extensively analyse this move in the course.   I did my best to bring  9...cxd4  back with the aid of modern engines, but I didn't succeed. Nevertheless, this line deserves a brief overview of its history.  10.Nxd4  h6  11.Be3  Re8  This move is played with the idea of retreating the bishop back to f8, which facilitates the idea of an exchange sacrifice on e3.  During the World Championship match, Karpov played  12.Qb3  here, with good results. The games were so disastrous, that Kasparov stopped playing the Tarrasch altogether in the match.  While  12.Qb3  continues to be a serious option, I discovered that the subtle  12.a3  is even stronger.  Its main point is that after an eventual Qb3 Na5, the queen can drop back to a2. It turns out that the isolated d5-pawn is too much of a burden and Black doesn't have enough activity to compensate for it.   Therefore, to play this variation one has to accept a passive position. And that's certainly not what we intend to do! Luckily,  9...c4  offers us much better prospects. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bg5"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bg5 c4 10.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bg5
{ We have reached what could be considered the main line of the Tarrasch. }
9... c4
{ This closing of the center, and thus precluding White's chance of giving us an isolani is an idea we use frequently in the Tarrasch Defense.  Having created a majority on the queenside, our play will often revolve around utilizing it through ...b7-b5. White, on the other hand, will often attempt to break our structure through b2-b3 or create a central play using e2-e4 and/or f2-f4. }
10. e3 Be6 11. Nd2
{ Whereas the knight usually jumps forward to e5, there is some sense to this fine retreat as well. From here, the knight does an excellent job of sustaining the b2-b3 advance.   11.Ne5  transposes to our main line  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2n2n2/3p2B1/2pP4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne5  Be6  11.e3  . }
11... Rc8 { The rook stands well here, especially in case of b2-b3. } 12. b3
{ Continuing with the aforementioned plan. } 12... Na5
{ A rare case where the knight ventures to a5 instead of the queen.   12...Qa5  is inadvisable in this case as White has the strong rejoinder  13.bxc4!  Qxc3  14.Bxf6  Bxf6  15.cxd5  .  Bringing the knight to a5 creates the threat of ...cxb3, which must be addressed by White. }
13. Rc1 cxb3
{ It turns out that stopping the threat does not stop us from capturing on b3. }
14. axb3 Nc6
{ The knight had done its duty on a5 of bothering White and now retreats to better squares, as b4 has become a juicy outpost for it. In general, White would be happy to play this structure, but in this specific case, the white pieces are awkwardly placed, especially the knight on d2. }
