[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bg5 c4 10.e3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bg5
{ We have reached what could be considered the main line of the Tarrasch. }
9... c4
{ This closing of the center, and thus precluding White's chance of giving us an isolani is an idea we use frequently in the Tarrasch Defense.  Having created a majority on the queenside, our play will often revolve around utilizing it through ...b7-b5. White, on the other hand, will often attempt to break our structure through b2-b3 or create a central play using e2-e4 and/or f2-f4. }
10. e3 Be6 11. b3
{ This was the choice of the world's #2, Ding Liren, so we must take it seriously.   11.Ne5  transposes to our main line  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2n2n2/3p2B1/2pP4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne5  Be6  11.e3  . }
11... Qa5 { A typical response if White plays b2-b3. } 12. Ne2
{ A sensible retreat, since the knight would like to reinstate itself on the pretty f4-square. }
12... Rac8
{ The rook stands well here, and may well be of great use when our c-pawn will march further down the board. }
13. Nf4 { Completing the transfer of the knight. } 13... Bf5
{ We cannot afford to have our light-squared bishop be captured that easily. Luckily, the bishop has a good outpost on f5. }
14. bxc4 { A direct approach, leading to a bit of a tactical skirmish. } 14...
dxc4 15. Bxf6
{ A wise moment to exchange, as otherwise, our knight may well jump to e4. }
15... Bxf6 16. Nd2 c3
{ Our forces had been preparing this thrust already, so there is no reason to refrain from it now. }
17. Nb3 c2
{ It transpires we can push our pawn even further down the board, as  18.Nxa5  loses a piece. }
18. Qh5 g6
{ Intermezzo after intermezzo. This was forced as otherwise it would be highly awkward to both keep the bishop protected and remove our queen from the attack. }
19. Nxa5 gxh5 20. Nxc6 bxc6
{ After the tactical mess, an interesting endgame has arisen. Our pawn structure is nothing to write home about, but most importantly, the c2-pawn has survived and we are ready to breathe life into our bishop pair by ...c6-c5.   If White wishes to close the diagonal of our f5-bishop through  21.e4  , they will instead open the diagonal of the other bishop, and we can immediately use this with  21...Bxd4  . After  22.Rac1  Bg4  23.Rxc2  c5  the position is relatively balanced, although it looks easier to play for Black with our powerful bishop pair. }
