[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bg5
{ We have reached what could be considered the main line of the Tarrasch. }
9... c4
{ This closing of the center, and thus precluding White's chance of giving us an isolani is an idea we use frequently in the Tarrasch Defense.  Having created a majority on the queenside, our play will often revolve around utilizing it through ...b7-b5. White, on the other hand, will often attempt to break our structure through b2-b3 or create a central play using e2-e4 and/or f2-f4. }
10. b3 Qa5
{ One of the first things I learned is that in chess, just like in life, moves have consequences. In this case, b2-b3 leaves the knight on c3 unprotected and we should make use of this fact. White has a couple of ways of defending the knight, but all of them have their problems. }
11. Bd2
{ The main move, but the bishop retreating from its active post on g5 does not seem very impressive. }
11... Bb4 { Keeping up the pressure. } 12. Qc2 Re8
{ There were other interesting possibilities as well, but I quite like this one. The knight is ready to jump to e4, and things may get quite tricky for White. }
13. bxc4 { A logical capture, after which we should not instantly recapture. }
13... Ne4
{ Chess is not checkers, and we are not always required to instantly recapture. As it turns out jumping in with the knight first is far stronger, as White has to deal with their hanging pieces. }
14. Nxd5
{ Crazy complications can ensue if White were to play in this fashion. } 14...
Nxd2 15. Ng5
{ That is the point, White is aiming for a straight checkmate. Don't worry, we have it all under control! }
15... g6 16. Nf6+ Kf8
{ The only correct square for the king. Things certainly look quite dangerous for the moment but keep calm and remember we are up a piece. }
17. d5
{ The most testing continuation.   In case of  17.Ngxh7  Kg7  18.Nxe8  Kxh7  White has lost their attacking potential. }
17... Ne5
{ A variety of moves were possible, but I feel this is the safest, centralizing the knight. }
18. Nxe8 Kxe8 19. Nxh7
{ Continuing the madness.  White had no time to move the rook, as that would allow us to play 19...Bf5, with tempo, suddenly taking over the initiative. }
19... Nxf1 { We should certainly keep grabbing stuff while we can. } 20. Qe4
Qc7
{ We can't afford to lose the central knight, which is the main protector of our king.   As usual, when analyzing crazy computer variations, the lines eventually end in a draw. After  21.Nf6+  Kf8  22.Qh4  Nd2  23.Qh8+  Ke7  24.d6+  Qxd6  25.Nd5+  Kd7  Nf6+  the game ends in a perpetual. Still, that was quite a fun variation if you ask me! }
