13... Bxe5
{ At first sight, this may seem like a bit of an unusual exchange, but we cannot tolerate the knight on e5 forever. Although White gets to have a strong central mass of pawns, we have concrete plans in mind justifying it.   First of all, White is faced with a tough decision on how to recapture. }
14. dxe5 { The most challenging move. } 14... d4
{ This push forward is why we took on e5 on the previous move. } 15. exd4 Nxd4
{ Our knight has jumped to a beautiful central square. If we are allowed to play ...Qb6 and ...Rad8, our position would be simply great. White must therefore come up with something smart. }
16. Rf2
{ It turns out this move is pretty smart, blocking the g1-a7 diagonal and threatening Rd2. }
16... Qb6 { Moving away from the pin. } 17. Na4
{ In this way, White manages to get rid of our excellent knight. } 17... Qa5
{ As there is no effective way of keeping the knight protected, we create a counterthreat against the knight on a4. }
18. Qxd4 Rad8 { An intelligent zwischenzug, making sure the d-file is ours. }
19. Qc5 Qxa4 20. f5
{ Due to our control over the d-file we are doing excellently in the long run and White should go for the attack. }
20... b6
{ Another strong zwischenzug, forcing the queen away and allowing our bishop access to d5. }
21. Qe3 Bd5 22. f6 { Continuing the attack is White's best bet. } 22... Qc6
{ The queen returns just in time to help fend off the attack. } 23. fxg7 Kxg7
24. Rf6 Qc5 { Forcing the play into an equal endgame. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bg5"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bg5 c4 10.Ne5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bg5
{ We have reached what could be considered the main line of the Tarrasch. }
9... c4
{ This closing of the center, and thus precluding White's chance of giving us an isolani is an idea we use frequently in the Tarrasch Defense.  Having created a majority on the queenside, our play will often revolve around utilizing it through ...b7-b5. White, on the other hand, will often attempt to break our structure through b2-b3 or create a central play using e2-e4 and/or f2-f4. }
10. Ne5
{ This is by far the main move. The knight occupies an active post in the center of the board, and at the same time vacates the long diagonal, so the bishop pressurizes d5. }
10... Be6
{ Developing the bishop and even more importantly, overprotecting d5. In their fight for the opening advantage, White has tried everything under the sun, yet hits a brick wall every time.  It might help us to know that even though White has several options at their disposal, we often play a quick ...h6, immediately challenging the bishop. }
11. Qd2
{ Has been the choice of quite many players but is a move we should embrace. If White wants to put any pressure on us, they can not afford to make slow improving moves. }
11... h6 { The choice we ought to be familiar with by now. } 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13.
Rad1
{ An interesting idea. White makes a preparatory move before deciding on their further actions.   If White wishes to play with  13.f4  , they should do so via the 11.e3 move order. In this case, we have a smooth game after the typical  13...Bxe5  14.fxe5  b5!  . It is important to be fast as otherwise, White gets play on the kingside.  15.e3   15.Nxb5  Qb6  is not to be recommended for White. Instead, they should try to transfer the knight to f4.  15...b4  16.Ne2  Qd7  . The game remains complex, but Black is on the better side of equality. In case of Nf4, we can always defend our kingside through ...Ne7, while we will slowly but surely advance our pawns on the queenside further. }
13... Rb8
{ Throwing back the ball into White's court. While ...Rb8 does not necessarily have any particular idea, the rook stands well here in case of ...b7-b5 and asks the opponent how they wish to continue. }
14. f4 { White lacks other useful moves and must play this sooner or later. }
14... Bxe5 { There is no reason to refrain from this typical exchange. } 15.
dxe5
{ Now, it becomes clear why White played their rook to the d-file, as the d-pawn is under serious pressure. }
15... d4 { The d-pawn could not be defended, but it can be pushed! } 16. Ne4
Qb6
{ The queen stands well here, keeping an eye on the white king. We have arrived at an intriguing position, which is yet to see the light of day in practical games.  Our central pawns are imposing, but so are the opponents. While the computer may evaluate the position as 0.00, we can be sure a complex struggle lies ahead where both sides will have their chances. }
*

