10... Be6
{ Developing the bishop and even more importantly, overprotecting d5. In their fight for the opening advantage, White has tried everything under the sun, yet hits a brick wall every time.  It might help us to know that even though White has several options at their disposal, we often play a quick ...h6, immediately challenging the bishop. }
11. f4
{ First tried by Rubinstein in 1908, this energetic move has since been played in many high-level games. White's aim is to either create a bind involving the strong knight on e5 or undermine our e6-bishop by an eventual f4-f5. }
11... Ng4
{ There is no time to waste, and we should initiate counterplay immediately. }
12. Nxg4
{ The most popular move, and, the one that offers the best chances of an advantage. }
12... Bxg4 13. Bxd5
{ Taking the central pawn is necessary, as otherwise, White's play would be senseless.   It is good to know that the alternative of  13.Nxd5  is much worse after  13...f6!  when the bishop on g5 is in trouble. }
13... Bxg5 14. fxg5 Qxg5
{ Restoring the material balance, as well as hinting at ...Qe3+. The position is not easy to evaluate as there are many imbalances. White has two strong central pawns, and pressure on f7 as well as c4. Our king is a bit safer, however, and our pieces are all standing actively. }
15. Rf4 { A clever way of preventing the check on e3. } 15... Rad8
{ The last piece should join the party as well. } 16. Qd2
{ Using the fact that 16...Rxd5 is not quite a threat, White prepares to bring their second rook to the f-file. We have reached a critical point, where we have to demonstrate some accuracy. }
16... Bh3
{ It would be desirable for us to oppose the bishop on d5 by playing  16...Be6  . However, as of now, this loses immediately to  17.Bxe6  fxe6  18.Rxf8  .  Therefore, we must subtly prepare this idea. Now, the threat of ...Rxd5 has become reality, so White's reply is forced. }
17. e4 Be6
{ Having provoked 17.e4, we can now play this move as the pawn on d4 is no longer defended. }
18. Raf1 { 18.Bxe6  would run into the stunning  18...Nxd4!  . } 18... Qe7
{ Overprotecting our pawn on f7 once more. The game remains complex, but our position is entirely satisfactory. White's central pawns look impressive but are rather weak at the same time. If given the chance, ...Nb4 is often a good idea, increasing the pressure on the d5-bishop. }
