{ This is White's main alternative to  11.Bg5  . While this is not a very serious move without the inclusion of the moves 10.a3 a5, it does make certain sense here: White can play Nb5, targeting the d6-square and threatening Nc7, without having to worry about Black playing ...a6. }
11... h6
{ The most solid approach, not going for any crazy complications but taking control over the g5-square and getting ready to play ...Be6 next.   The immediate  11...Be6  would be slightly inaccurate due to  12.Ng5!  . }
12. Rc1
{ White has to bring the rook into the game sooner or later, so it is best to do it now. }
12... Be6
{ Bringing out the bishop as was the plan.   Take note that  13.Nxd5  is a tactic that only works against White as we have  13...Bxf2+  as an intermediate move. }
13. Ne5
{ Leaping forward with the knight seems like a sensible thing to do. Opening up the bishop on g2 and creating pressure in the center. }
13... Rc8
{ At the moment, White has no direct threats so we can calmly continue developing. }
14. Nd3 { Asking our bishop where it would like to go. } 14... Bb6
{ The best square, as  14...Ba7  would run into  15.Nb5  , which would be quite unpleasant to meet. }
15. Na4 { Continuing to harass our bishop. } 15... Bf5
{ This is quite a sophisticated move. In essence, it is prophylaxis for whenever a white knight jumps to c5, we make sure that our light-squared bishop will not be on e6. At the same time, we do not mind if White takes our dark-squared bishop because our queen would stand excellently on b6. }
16. Ndc5 { White continues jumping, but all the jumping costs time. } 16...
Bxc5 { The time has come to part with one of our bishops. } 17. Nxc5 Qb6
{ We have achieved a very healthy and active position. White should worry about the pawn on b2, and we can continue by bringing the rook on f8 into the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5 Bxc5 10.a3 #4 (Alternative 11...d4)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. dxc5
{ This is the second most played move after  9.Bg5  . By releasing the tension in the center, the opponent gives us the isolani immediately.  Play will now revolve around the question of whether the pawn on d5 is a liability or a strength. While White will try to either block or attack it, we can use our active pieces and space advantage, granted by the isolated pawn, to disturb the opponent's plans. }
9... Bxc5
{ There is an option of gambitting the pawn entirely through  9...d4  , but practice has shown that it is best to restore material balance instead. White is at crossroads here, having several ways of completing development.   As for our ideal piece configuration, it is quite straightforward. For the rooks, the ideal positions are generally e8 and c8 or d8, standing useful on the @@StartBracket@@semi-@@EndBracket@@open files. The real question remains for our light-squared bishop, as it might stand well on either e6, f5 or g4 depending on the situation.  As usual, when playing with the isolani we should always be on the lookout for opportunities of pushing it forward at an opportune moment, as the further it advances the more of a menace it becomes to the opponent. }
10. a3
{ White is not hiding any intentions with this move. The plan is to push b2-b4 and force our bishop away from c5. }
10... a5
{ After some deliberation, I have decided to recommend this simple prophylaxis against the b2-b4 idea. While it is true that we have given up on the b5-square now, this doesn't seem to be a great deal of worry to us.   Instead, Black can sacrifice a pawn with  10...Ne4!?  , but this generally results in an endgame that is a bit too dry for my taste.  The text keeps all the pieces on the board. Moreover, it is not a common move at all, so you are quite likely to surprise your opponent here.   Another bonus is that out of the 97 games in my database, 77 players have decided to play  11.Bg5  here. The ensuing positions are almost identical to the lines that we study in the 10.Bg5 variation. }
11. Bf4
{ This is White's main alternative to  11.Bg5  . While this is not a very serious move without the inclusion of the moves 10.a3 a5, it does make certain sense here: White can play Nb5, targeting the d6-square and threatening Nc7, without having to worry about Black playing ...a6. }
11... d4
{ Who doesn't like some provocative chess? White was intending to play Nb5, so why not force them to do so immediately? There is a clear upside to this move, as the d5-square will now be available to us.  While I do believe this to be slightly dubious for Black, I rate the practical chances highly as White is forced to find several strong moves in order to even fight for an advantage. }
12. Nb5 Nd5
{ The knight occupies the beautiful central square and threatens the bishop on f4 at the same time. }
13. Qc1
{ An extremely strong move and the only one that allows White to fight for an advantage. Not only is the queen ready to recapture on f4, but it is also attacking our bishop on c5.   13.Bg5  was played by the Polish grandmaster Gajewski, but after  13...Qb6  Black is already gaining the upper hand. }
13... Nxf4
{ As it turns out we have no better than to immediately part ways with our strong knight. Still, the white bishop on f4 was no weak piece either. }
14. Qxf4 d3
{ Despite not being the first computer move, I could not resist recommending this move as it leads to fascinating positions where you can easily outplay the opponent.  By pushing our d-pawn one step further the complications will revolve around the question of whether White can win the pawn, or whether we can turn it into a serious asset. After all, the pawn is only two squares away from promotion! }
15. e3
{ Capturing the pawn on d3 would just give us a comfortable position with two bishops and no problems.   At the same time,  15.Rad1  seems tempting until you notice  15...Qb6!  , winning the game for Black. }
15... a4
{ Certainly not the most logical move, but the idea is very pretty as we wish to bring our rook into the game via a5, or even a6 sometimes. Eventually, the square on b3 might come in handy for our pieces as well. }
16. Qc4
{ The queen swings over, attacking our bishop and keeping a close eye on our pawn on d3. }
16... Bb6 17. Rfd1 Be6
{ Making use of some clever tactics, since  18.Qxd3  runs into  18...Qxd3  19.Rxd3  Bc4  , winning the game for Black! }
18. Qe4 Qf6
{ While we cannot hold on to the pawn forever, we can create other means of counterplay instead. Our bishop will stand extremely well on b3, our rooks are ready to swing to the central squares. }
19. Qxd3 Bb3
{ The bishop places itself on the outpost. Be aware that  19...Qxb2  is no good due to  20.Ng5  . }
20. Rd2 Ba5 { The white rook is being chased all over the place. } 21. Re2 Rad8
{ Black has fantastic compensation and is certainly no worse. } *

