10. a3
{ White is not hiding any intentions with this move. The plan is to push b2-b4 and force our bishop away from c5. }
10... a5
{ After some deliberation, I have decided to recommend this simple prophylaxis against the b2-b4 idea. While it is true that we have given up on the b5-square now, this doesn't seem to be a great deal of worry to us.   Instead, Black can sacrifice a pawn with  10...Ne4!?  , but this generally results in an endgame that is a bit too dry for my taste.  The text keeps all the pieces on the board. Moreover, it is not a common move at all, so you are quite likely to surprise your opponent here.   Another bonus is that out of the 97 games in my database, 77 players have decided to play  11.Bg5  here. The ensuing positions are almost identical to the lines that we study in the 10.Bg5 variation. }
11. Bg5
{ As mentioned, you will be by far the most likely to face this move. Although there are some subtle differences, play will be extremely similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2bp4/8/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bg5  . }
11... d4 12. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ As in the 10.Bg5 line, both  13.Nd5  and  13.Ne4  are playable for White. }
13. Nd5 Qd8 14. Nf4
{ I was quite surprised when I noticed the computer being slightly enthusiastic about this move. It took me quite a while to realize why, as in the 10.Bg5 variation, this move is hardly worth any consideration.  I believe the main point is that the knight on f4 securely defends the pawn on e2, freeing the queen to use some of the weakened light squares such as a4 and b5 on the queenside. If our pawn would still be on a7, this would be far less of a worry. }
14... Re8
{ Even though the pawn on e2 is securely protected, it is still a good idea to place our rook on the half-open file. }
15. Rc1 { White does the same. } 15... Bb6
{ I tried to make  15...Bf8  work, but I eventually ran into some deep issues. My line went as follows:  16.h4  h6  17.Qa4!  g5!?  , and stuff gets highly tactical after  18.hxg5  hxg5  19.Nxg5  Qxg5  19.Rxc6!!  Bd7  20.Rg6+  Qxg6  21.Qxd7  , after which I prefer White.  Fortunately, the bishop is standing well on b6 too. Now, if it would be our turn, we would love to play ...a4, getting a good grip on the light squares. }
16. Qa4
{ The only way to stop our idea adequately. Interestingly, the white queen stands quite well here. }
16... h6
{ A small move, but hinting at big plans, since the idea of ...g7-g5 forcing the knight away from f4 is a genuine idea. On the other hand, we can also continue our development with ...Bf5 or ...Bg4. All in all, we definitely have a flexible position with good chances here. }
