[Round "?"]
[White "2) Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5 Bxc5 10.Na4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. dxc5
{ This is the second most played move after  9.Bg5  . By releasing the tension in the center, the opponent gives us the isolani immediately.  Play will now revolve around the question of whether the pawn on d5 is a liability or a strength. While White will try to either block or attack it, we can use our active pieces and space advantage, granted by the isolated pawn, to disturb the opponent's plans. }
9... Bxc5
{ There is an option of gambitting the pawn entirely through  9...d4  , but practice has shown that it is best to restore material balance instead. White is at crossroads here, having several ways of completing development.   As for our ideal piece configuration, it is quite straightforward. For the rooks, the ideal positions are generally e8 and c8 or d8, standing useful on the @@StartBracket@@semi-@@EndBracket@@open files. The real question remains for our light-squared bishop, as it might stand well on either e6, f5 or g4 depending on the situation.  As usual, when playing with the isolani we should always be on the lookout for opportunities of pushing it forward at an opportune moment, as the further it advances the more of a menace it becomes to the opponent. }
10. Na4
{ Voluntarily placing the knight on the edge of the board is generally not a good idea, but here we should take the move very seriously. Our bishop has to move from its powerful position, therefore enabling White to establish better control over the dark squares in the center.  Besides, it is exactly this move which has been recommended by strong opening theoretician Boris Avrukh in his 1.d4 Grandmaster Repertoire series.  On the bright side for us, a knight on the rim remains dim and we will have sufficient means of achieving counterplay. Our main focus of play will be on the kingside, as White will generally be diverting their pieces to the other side of the board. }
10... Be7
{ Albeit slightly passive, the bishop stands best here. Now we needn't be worried about an eventual pin by Bg5, and if needed, the bishop can come back to life via f6, after an eventual ...Ne4. }
11. Nd4
{ A tempting move from White's perspective, as the knight occupies the best square available on the board.   However, even from such a strong outpost, the knight can not control the entirety of the board, and as a consequence, the knight has lost control over some squares as well. I am hinting at the h4-square especially, which while seemingly irrelevant is quite important. }
11... h5
{ Harry the h-pawn starts its journey down the board! Since the knight has left its post on f3, our pawn can easily march down the board, wreaking havoc within the enemy lines.  Moreover, the move is still a novelty, so your opponent is almost certain to be shocked by the sudden aggressive play. }
12. h4
{ A scared opponent might immediately pull the brakes and stop the h-pawn. However, as a consequence, White seriously weakens their kingside and especially the g4-square. }
12... Bg4
{ Immediately taking advantage of White's previous move; our bishop stands very well here as it can no longer be challenged by h2-h3. }
