12. Bg5
{ As there are no longer any games in this position, it is not easy to predict what your opponent would choose. The text appears to be the most logical, stopping the h-pawn in its tracks for the moment and developing the bishop at the same time. }
12... Ne4
{ We shouldn't allow our evil plans to be stopped so easily. By offering the exchange of bishops, the h-pawn is ready to march forward once more. }
13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Rc1
{ Once again, this seems logical to me. White hopes to keep us busy by attacking our knight once more. }
14... h4
{ We shouldn't be fooled or distracted by what White is doing, as pushing the h-pawn is all that matters. }
15. Nxc6
{ The pawn has to be taken as otherwise, the previous moves would have been pointless. }
15... bxc6 16. Rxc6 h3
{ Finally, our soldier reaches his final destination. From h3, it will be like a thorn in the opponent's flesh for the rest of the game, as the white king will be in a constant state of jeopardy. }
17. Bh1 Bg4
{ Developing the bishop to the most active position available, exercising great pressure on the e2-pawn.  18.f3  is of no concern as  18...Bd7  conveniently counterattacks White's rook. }
18. Qxd5
{ White takes another pawn, but this one we will regain in short order. } 18...
Nf6
{ Bringing the knight to safety, simultaneously attacking both White's queen as the pawn on e2 once more. }
19. Qg5 Bxe2 20. Re1 Rae8
{ A last accurate move, as the rook joins the fray. Next, we can move our queen from the e-file so our bishop is ready to move as well. Especially ...Qb4 is a tricky move to keep in mind.  Even though we are still down one pawn, we have long-term compensation as long the pawn on h3 is alive, which will always be a great thorn in White's position.   A final note is that White can not afford to go after the h3-pawn with  21.Qh4?  since  21...Qd7  with the idea of ...Bb5 is completely crushing. }
