{ Sending the bishop to the most active square available. In general, we will try to follow up with ...Qd7, after which eventually ...Bh3 will be an idea as well.  At the same time, we should be aware of the idea to exchange bishop for knight through ...Bxf3, as it will diminish White's control over the center, especially the d4-square. }
12. Rc1
{ Proceeding logically, White now occupies the semi-open file and prepares to play Nc5. }
12... Qd7
{ The queen forms a battery with the bishop, stopping White from playing h2-h3 for the moment. Furthermore, our rooks can easily occupy central squares e8 and d8. }
13. Bc5
{ This move scores extremely well for White in practice, so it is about time we change that.   With  13.Nd4  ,  White occupies a central position with the knight. A move that was seldomly seen but strikes me as rather natural.  13...Rfe8  14.Nxc6  The typical plan for White, slightly weakening our pawn structure.  14...bxc6  15.Nc5  Bxc5  16.Rxc5  A familiar sight, White has the two bishops and better pawn structure, yet has absolutely no advantage after our following move!  16...h5!  As often, the idea of pushing the h-pawn down the board is extremely menacing to the opponent and will be a constant source of good counterplay. }
13... h5
{ A novelty, but an idea typical of this line. While the pawn may not directly rush down the board, it is ready to do so whenever an opportunity presents itself. }
14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Re1
{ The more straightforward  15.h3  is well met by  15...Bxf3  16.Bxf3  h4!  , forcing White to further weaken their kingside. }
15... Rfe8
{ Back to the standard plan of bringing our rooks to the game. Remember that if White starts entertaining thoughts of playing Nd4, we should be ready to play ...h5-h4. }
