13... Bxc5 { It would be ill-advised to keep the knight on c5 alive. } 14. Bxc5
Rfe8 { This move should be self explanatory. } 15. Re1
{ Defending the pawn on e2, so that White's queen is free to move. In general, I think it is good to think about this kind of position a bit as it is very typical for the Tarrasch Defense, especially this line.  In the past, these types of positions were assessed as quite favourable for White. Indeed, White's bishop pair and play against the isolated pawn should offer them quite promising prospects in the long term.  However, modern chess engines have altered this view. The hypermodern chess school no longer emphasizes positional aspects such as vulnerable pawns and the bishop pair, but rather focuses on precise calculation.  In this case, Black's activity compensates for the positional disadvantages. In particular, the difference in the quality of the rooks is striking. The e2-pawn makes a mockery out of the white rook, while the black rooks are flourishing on an open and semi-open file. Dynamically, the position is about equal. }
15... Rac8
{ The position is not very concrete, so naturally, there are several moves which are reasonable. This is one of them, simply bringing in the rook to the open file.  Typical of the modern school of chess is to push ...h5-h4-h3 in such cases. Neural Network engines have told us, these pawns are quite a menace to the opponent.  However, the more restrained ...h6 is often a decent idea too. Furthermore, improving the knight with ...Ne4, or exchanging some bishops through ....Bh3 are ideas worth contemplating.  In general, in which order we do what mostly depends on how White plays. }
16. Bd4
{ Subtle play, White would like to play Nd4, but for now, it would run into ...b6. While it is also possible to play Be3 immediately, the nature of the position remains the same. }
16... Ne4 { Logical and good, the knight stands well on e4. } 17. Be3
{ Another somewhat strange retreat, but finally, the d4-square is cleared for the knight. }
17... h5
{ Here goes nothing. It was by no means bad to play  17...h6  instead, but the text is more in the spirit of the Tarrasch! }
18. Nd4
{ There are too many options for both sides to extensively investigate each one of them, but the following sample line gives an excellent demonstration of the kind of play we are aiming for. }
18... Bh3
{ Exchanging the prime defender of White's king.   The immediate  18...h4  would not work as well due to  19.Nxc6  bxc6  20.f3!  , therefore we must move our bishop first. }
19. Nxc6 Rxc6 { Sacrificing the pawn, but accepting it is highly dangerous. }
20. Bxh3 Qxh3 21. Qxd5 { White takes up the gauntlet. } 21... Rg6
{ A nice rook lift, and suddenly dark clouds start to appear over the opponent's monarch. }
22. Qxb7 Kh7
{ It turns out we even can afford ourselves the luxury of improving the king, before going over to action. }
23. Qxf7 { White captures a third pawn. } 23... Nxg3
{ The time to sacrifice has come! } 24. fxg3 Rxg3+ 25. hxg3 Qxg3+
{ As usual, when analysing with strong engines, after all the complications the game will end peacefully as a draw by perpetual is imminent. }
