{ Not the most ambitious move, but not entirely pointless either as the idea is to simply develop the bishop on the long diagonal. }
10... Ne4
{ Taking advantage of the fact that White's knight is unprotected for just a moment. }
11. Bb2 { The most logical continuation. } 11... Nxc3 12. Bxc3 d4
{ A desirable move in general, and now we can even make it with the gain of tempo. This also goes to show the main idea behind our last couple of moves, as the exchange of knights means that White no longer has the option of Na4 available to our central push. }
13. Bb2 Bf5
{ Through a transposition of moves, we suddenly find ourselves in a bit of a theoretical position. Developing the bishop here seems reasonable to me and it was Alireza Firouzja's choice as well. }
14. Rc1 Bb6
{ With this move, we deviate from the game Artemiev-Firouzja. In that game,  14...Qd6  was played but after  15.b4!  ,  White developed some small pressure.  I prefer to bring the bishop to a secure square immediately while retaining some flexibility regarding our queen's position. As long as we manage to keep our d-pawn alive, we should have a comfortable position. }
