10. Bg5
{ The old main line and the most direct attempt as it creates a pin and immediate pressure on the isolani.  It is also known as the Timman variation, although players such as Lasker, Capablanca and Euwe all tried it earlier!  In recent years, this variation has faded into the background, however. With some accurate play, Black has been able to neutralize White's pressure fairly easily. }
10... d4
{ Addressing the pressure in the most active way possible by pushing forward, and at the same time forcing the knight to move from c3.  White is now faced with a choice of either moving the knight immediately or capturing on f6 first. }
11. Ne4
{ This is not as popular and not as testing as  11.Bxf6  . Yet, more than 500 people have given it a try so we ought to be ready. }
11... Be7 { Breaking the pin and returning the bishop to safety. } 12. Bxf6
{ The most flexible option by White, as they can still decide whether to capture on f6 later with the knight or not. }
12... Bxf6 13. Qd2
{ A reasonable improving move, intending to bring a rook to the d-file and increase pressure on the d-pawn. }
13... Bf5 { Sometimes just developing the pieces is the best idea. } 14. Nxf6+
{ The knight was running out of good squares, so this exchange is more or less forced. }
14... Qxf6 15. Qf4 { The trickiest move, intending to play Nh4 next. } 15...
Rfe8 { Continuing to improve all of our forces. } 16. Nh4
{ Carrying on with the small operation started on the previous move. } 16...
Be4 { A cute move, making use of some small tactics. } 17. Qxf6
{ Delivering us the doubled pawns, but to do so White has lost some time and our pieces have occupied good positions.   17.Bxe4  did not win a piece as the intermediate  17...Qxf4  18.gxf4  Rxe4  would work in our favour. }
17... gxf6 18. Nf3 d3
{ We can not have too many pawn weaknesses in our position. Through this move, we get rid of the isolated pawn. }
19. exd3 Bxd3 20. Rfd1 Rad8
{ All of our pieces are incredibly active, compensating for our somewhat inferior pawn structure. }
