[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5 Bxc5 10.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. dxc5
{ This is the second most played move after  9.Bg5  . By releasing the tension in the center, the opponent gives us the isolani immediately.  Play will now revolve around the question of whether the pawn on d5 is a liability or a strength. While White will try to either block or attack it, we can use our active pieces and space advantage, granted by the isolated pawn, to disturb the opponent's plans. }
9... Bxc5
{ There is an option of gambitting the pawn entirely through  9...d4  , but practice has shown that it is best to restore material balance instead. White is at crossroads here, having several ways of completing development.   As for our ideal piece configuration, it is quite straightforward. For the rooks, the ideal positions are generally e8 and c8 or d8, standing useful on the @@StartBracket@@semi-@@EndBracket@@open files. The real question remains for our light-squared bishop, as it might stand well on either e6, f5 or g4 depending on the situation.  As usual, when playing with the isolani we should always be on the lookout for opportunities of pushing it forward at an opportune moment, as the further it advances the more of a menace it becomes to the opponent. }
10. Bg5
{ The old main line and the most direct attempt as it creates a pin and immediate pressure on the isolani.  It is also known as the Timman variation, although players such as Lasker, Capablanca and Euwe all tried it earlier!  In recent years, this variation has faded into the background, however. With some accurate play, Black has been able to neutralize White's pressure fairly easily. }
10... d4
{ Addressing the pressure in the most active way possible by pushing forward, and at the same time forcing the knight to move from c3.  White is now faced with a choice of either moving the knight immediately or capturing on f6 first. }
11. Ne4
{ This is not as popular and not as testing as  11.Bxf6  . Yet, more than 500 people have given it a try so we ought to be ready. }
11... Be7 { Breaking the pin and returning the bishop to safety. } 12. Bxf6
{ The most flexible option by White, as they can still decide whether to capture on f6 later with the knight or not. }
12... Bxf6 13. Nxf6+
{ This exchange only helps us as the f6-bishop wasn't going anywhere. } 13...
Qxf6 14. Qd2 Rd8
{ As we are not yet sure whether we would like to develop our bishop to e6, f5 or g4, we improve our rook first. Immediately hinting at ideas of ...d4-d3. }
15. Rfd1
{ This would be a logical continuation, but already, some tactics start to appear. }
15... d3 { It is always a pleasure to play such moves. } 16. exd3 Bg4
{ The pin on the knight is quite nasty, and White better starts worrying about equalizing. }
