{ Addressing the pressure in the most active way possible by pushing forward, and at the same time forcing the knight to move from c3.  White is now faced with a choice of either moving the knight immediately or capturing on f6 first. }
11. Bxf6
{ In general, one does not want to exchange the bishop for a knight unprovoked, but White does gain a couple of tempi on our queen after the c3-knight jumps to either e4 or d5. }
11... Qxf6
{ Once again White is faced with a choice. They could either simplify the position more through  12.Ne4  Qe7  13.Nxc5  , or be more adventurous with  @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp3ppp/2n2q2/2b5/3p4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nd5  . }
12. Ne4
{ I feel this gives Black a reasonably smooth game.   If White wants to put some pressure,  12.Nd5  is better  . }
12... Qe7 13. Nxc5 { The only logical follow-up. } 13... Qxc5
{ After a bunch of exchanges, we have reached a very typical position for the Tarrasch Defence. Although exchanges are generally good for the side playing against the isolani @@StartBracket@@White@@EndBracket@@, as it reduces the amount of piece play, I do not think this is the case here.  The pawn on d4 is securely protected and cramps White's position quite a bit. Moreover, our pieces will easily find active positions. White generally either transfers the knight from f3 to d3 via e1 or centralizes the rooks.   In either case, our approach remains the same regardless: we play the subtle but highly useful move ...h6, develop our bishop, bring the rooks to the center and take it from there. }
14. Qd2
{ A somewhat tricky move, as the computer claims the natural  14...Be6  suddenly runs into  15.b4  . }
14... Be6
{ Generally speaking, I don't like to overrule the computer, but here I dare to do so! }
15. Rfc1
{ A bit of a different move, as normally the a1-rook goes to c1. While the rooks look a bit awkward in this way, at least the pawn on a2 is securely defended. }
15... Qb6 16. Ng5 { This appears to be the point behind White's play. } 16...
Bf5
{ Yet, it is hard to be too impressed as White should sooner or later attempt to bring the rook from a1 back into the game. Meanwhile, we can easily bring our rooks into the game. }
17. Ne4 Bxe4
{ A good trade, as the knight reaching c5 would not be great news for us. } 18.
Bxe4 Rfe8 { Our position is super solid and we have no problems. } *

