{ Stopping any funny business with Ng5. This move is always going to be useful anyhow, as it takes any future back-rank checkmates out of the equation as well. }
16. Rfd1 Be6
{ Developing the bishop with a tempo, as we surely would like to take on a2 if given the opportunity. }
17. b3 Rfe8
{ There are many ways of approaching the position for Black. In fact, most players have given preference to  17...Rfd8  instead, but I quite like the position of the rook here, as the pawn on e2 may become a target in the future. }
18. Qc5
{ Offering the exchange of queens, but we will nevertheless maintain an active position. }
18... Qxc5
{ So we are happily accepting the offer. We obviously want to deny White the opportunity of damaging our structure with Qxb6. }
19. Rxc5 Rac8
{ The final inactive piece joins the game and our army is now fully mobilized. Ideas like ...Nb4 or ...a5-a4, are very much on the agenda, keeping White busy. There is actually one more cute idea, that is well worth remembering. }
20. Rc2 { Intending to play Rcd2 and win our pawn at long last. } 20... d3
{ Quite the surprise! The isolated pawn suddenly sacrifices itself.   We are relying on some clever tactics to afford this. The main point is that the positionally desirable  21.Rxd3  runs into  21...Bf5  , winning material. }
21. exd3
{ The only capture remaining, but the white pieces have lost coordination for just a moment, and we can take advantage of that with another blow. }
21... Bg4
{ Through our pawn sacrifice we have made White lose control over the d4-square entirely and suddenly a strong threat of ...Nd4 is created. }
22. h3 { Perhaps White's safest choice, forcing the game into a rook endgame. }
22... Bxf3 23. Bxf3 Nd4
{ The knight stands beautifully on d4, but unfortunately, just for one moment. }
24. Rxc8 Nxf3+ 25. Kg2 Nh4+
{ An astute intermediate move, ruining the white pawn structure altogether. }
26. gxh4 Rxc8
{ Even though White is up a pawn in this rook endgame, they cannot hope for any advantage since both our rook and our pawn structure are far superior. }
