{ Creating immediate threats to the d4-pawn is certainly challenging, and we must know how to deal with it. }
15... Be6 { The knight is forced to retreat through a counterattack. } 16. Nf4
Qb6
{ An important move to remember, as it is somewhat counterintuitive. Generally, we do not want to part with our light-squared bishop so easily, as the bishop on g2 can become extremely strong.  In this case, however, we can afford to do so, since our pieces will occupy excellent positions and the knight on b3 will be very awkward after the exchange. }
17. Bxc6
{ This is not very dangerous, but it is good to be aware of this move since it appears to win a pawn. }
17... bxc6
{ Somehow most players in the database went for  17...Bxb3  instead, but in fact, it is easier to start with this capture, since we leave White with fewer options. }
18. Qxd4
{ So White has won a pawn for the time being, but the variation does not end here. }
18... Bxb3 { We continue by initiating a long and forcing sequence. } 19. Qxb6
axb6 20. axb3 g5
{ A clever point, forcing the knight to give up protection over the pawn on e2. }
21. Nh5 Rxe2 22. Rxc6 Rxb2 23. Rxb6 Ra3
{ After a long sequence of captures, we have reached a highly simplified endgame. The text is the last accurate move that Black had to find to eliminate White's extra pawn. The ensuing endgame is a dead draw. }
