[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bf4
{ In terms of popularity, this move lags far behind the main moves, but it is certainly not completely pointless.  The bishop occupies a fine square, and White is ready to include the rook with Rc1 next. The downside is that it does not put any direct pressure on our center, thus allowing us to handle the position more freely. }
9... h6
{ According to my database, this is the ninth move in terms of popularity, but that does not mean it is not a good one! By stopping any Ng5 shenanigans, we prepare to play ...Be6 next.   Note that playing  9...c4  here, similar to the 9.Bg5 variation, is feasible too.  Yet, I have chosen the text move since I believe we should embrace the opportunity to play in a pure Tarrasch style, accepting the isolani after an eventual exchange of the d4- and c5-pawns. }
10. Rc1
{ The alternative of  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.Rc1  Be6  transposes to the text move. }
10... Be6 { The correct follow-up after our previous move. } 11. dxc5
{ White has more or less run out of useful waiting moves and is bound to release the central tension sooner rather than later. }
11... Bxc5 12. Na4
{ This appears to be the most testing move, forcing our bishop to lose control over the d4-square.   Instead,  12.Nxd5  would be a severe mistake, since after  12...Bxf2+!  13.Rxf2  Nxd5  Black is clearly better.   A more sensible alternative is  12.Ne5  , but even so, after  12...Rc8  Black has little to fear. }
12... Be7
{ It is wise to retreat all the way back.   Instead, the most popular move  12...Bd6  would be a serious mistake, losing control over the dark squares after  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.Nc5  . }
13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 b6
{ An important novelty, covering the c5-square once and for all. Now the knight on a4 is stuck in no man's land. If it ever decides to return to c3, that opens an opportunity for our bishop to establish itself on c5 once more.  As for our other plans, we can look to contest the c-file with ...Rc8, and improve further with ...Qd7, connecting the rooks. At the same time, the isolated pawn is hard to attack for White, and apart from the isolani there are no other targets in our camp. }
15. Nc3 Bc5 { Black is doing fine. } *


[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Fianchetto With Nc3 – Other 9th Moves"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.h3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. h3
{ This peculiar move has been tried a couple of times by Hikaru Nakamura. Besides that, I don't think we should be too frightened upon facing this move. If anything, the pawn on h3 seems to me to be a slight weakness. You never know if it might be hanging later on in the game. I suppose the idea is to prevent ...Bg4, but our bishop is not obliged to go there in the first place. }
9... Be6 { Another lovely square for the bishop! } 10. Be3 b6
{ Typically we respond to Be3 with ...c4, but h2-h3 has made White lose some valuable time, and we can use that to our advantage by keeping the pawn structure intact. }
11. Ne5
{ This has been played in three out of four games. It allows us to demonstrate some nice tactics. }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 d4
{ As it turns out, all the tactics work in our favour here. } 13. exf6 Bxf6 14.
Bxa8 Qxa8
{ White is up an entire rook for the time being, but two pieces are hanging, and the disadvantage of the pawn being on h3 is demonstrated, as ...Bxh3 is a serious threat too. Stockfish already gives a huge advantage of -1,5 to Black. }
