[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. a3
{ With this move, White hopes to capture on c5 and follow it up with b2-b4 under favourable circumstances. Unfortunately for White, we will not be allowing any of this. }
9... c4
{ Especially with the pawn already committed to a3, this makes a whole lot of sense. The b3-square is seriously weakened and our knight has a direct route to enter via a5. Moreover, the typical idea of playing b2-b3 by White will be much harder to achieve once our knight lands there. }
10. Ne5 Na5 { The knight starts its mission! } 11. Bg5 Nb3
{ Already the rook is in a bit of peril since Ra2 looks awkward but the alternative runs into ...Bf5. }
12. Rb1 { The rook simply looks too dumb on a2. } 12... Bf5 13. e4
{ The exchange sacrifice  13.Bxf6  Bxf6  14.Nxd5  Bxb1  15.Qxb1  Bxe5  can only be better for Black.  The text has been played in a few games, but Black is already slightly better. }
13... dxe4 14. Be3
{ A sad retreat, but White can not afford to lose the d4-pawn. } 14... Qc7
{ Protecting the pawn on c4, as well as clearing the d8-square for one of the rooks. A great outcome of the opening! }
