[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. e3
{ Voluntarily locking in the c1-bishop is ill-advised. } 9... c4
{ A common response, even when the White bishop is on g5, it certainly ought to be good here then as well. }
10. b3 Bf5
{ We needn't fear the capture  11.bxc4  , since after  11...dxc4  , our queenside majority will soon become quite menacing, while White has no way of putting the central pawns in motion.  If White does not take, ...Rc8 next is a good idea, involving the rook in the game. All in all, we can establish that Black already equalized at the minimum. }
