[White "3) Fianchetto With Nc3 – Other 9th Moves"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Be3
{ This move bears great resemblance to the Korchnoi variation, which is seen without the inclusion of the moves Nc3 and ...O-O. Although the bishop makes a strange impression on e3, it forces us to play ...c5-c4. However, little do they know that we would play in exactly this way after the more critical 9.Bg5 as well. }
9... c4 { As mentioned, we are more than happy to play like this. } 10. Ne5 h6
{ This subtle move has been a favourite of Kasparov who played it a couple of times in the late 80s, scoring two wins against Larsen and Hort. With this move, we make sure that the bishop on e3 will never reach the g5-square anymore. At the same time, we wait and see how White will approach the situation.   On another note, it is important not to play  10...Be6  instead, since it runs into  11.Nxc4!  dxc4  12.d5  , giving White a great advantage. }
11. b3 { A typical idea, White wishes to exchange our strong c4-pawn. } 11...
cxb3
{ There is no feasible way of maintaining the c4-pawn, so we must exchange it. On the bright side, the c-file is open which can often be used to our advantage, targeting the loose knight on c3. }
12. Qxb3
{ The best recapture, increasing the pressure to the d5-square.   In case of  12.axb3  , White would have lost permanent control over the b4-square as well, which is a pretty outpost for our c6-knight. }
12... Na5
{ The pressure against d5 was mounting, so it is important to push the queen back. }
13. Qc2
{ Other moves would also be met with ...Be6 with similar consequences. } 13...
Be6
{ Developing the bishop to its best square. From here we have a couple of plans at our disposal. ...Rc8 and expanding on the queenside with ...a6 and ...b5 are logical. Another interesting idea to keep in mind is ...Bb4, followed by ...Bxc3, exchanging White's knight, and enhancing our control over the light squares, especially the e4-square. }
14. Rab1
{ This appears to be the most testing move, stopping ...Bb4.   In case of  14.f4  Rc8  White has mostly weakened their position since  15.f5  is easily met with  15...Bd7  . }
14... a6 { Setting the queenside expansion plan in motion. } 15. a4
{ A clever prophylaxis, but we have enough other resources to generate counterplay. }
15... Rc8 16. Qd3 Rc7
{ Protecting the pawn on b7 and intending to bring the knight to c4, with a fine position. }
*

[Event "?"]
