[Round "?"]
[White "3) Fianchetto With Nc3 – Other 9th Moves"]
[Black "Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.b3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. b3
{ White intends to fianchetto the bishop to b2. As a rule, this setup is quite harmless, however, since we will be able to contest the long diagonal in a suitable way. }
9... Ne4
{ A typical idea, the knight stands well in the center of the board, and more importantly the f6-square is being cleared for our bishop to occupy. }
10. Bb2 Bf6
{ The correct follow-up after our last move. The bishop stands very well here, mounting the pressure on the d4-pawn even further. }
11. Na4
{ A peculiar way of defending the central pawn, but it turns out to be White's best move. A second point is that White's bishop is now defended by the knight, enabling White to entertain ideas of playing dxc5 at an opportune moment. }
11... cxd4
{ I think this is the most practical way of approaching the position. By capturing on d4, we ensure that we do not have to worry about the possibility of White capturing on c5 instead. }
12. Nxd4 Bd7
{ Optically this looks somewhat passive, but the bishop does quite a good job from here. First of all, it makes sure that in case of Nxc6 we can recapture with ...Bxc6. Secondly, it keeps an eye on the knight on a4, which on a good day might come in handy. }
13. Rc1 Qe7
{ Connecting the rooks and covering the c5-square so that the knight on a4 is forced to stay on the rim for a while longer. }
14. e3 Rac8
{ Bringing the rook to the open file is almost always a good idea. } 15. Nc3
{ Finally the knight returns from the edge of the board. } 15... Nxc3
{ Exchanging some pieces, which at the end will give us a fine position. } 16.
Rxc3
{ In case of  16.Bxc3  Nxd4  17.Bxd4  Rxc1!  18.Qxc1  Bxd4  19.exd4  Rc8  the position is entirely symmetrical and drawish. }
16... Bxd4
{ Perhaps a surprising exchange, but the logical  16....Nxd4  17.Rxc8!  Rxc8  18.Bxd4  allows White to keep some pressure. After the text, White is forced to recapture with the e-pawn on d4. }
17. exd4 Qd6
{ Although White has the bishop pair, the bishop on b2 is quite passive. At the same time, our position is harmonious, with all of our pieces occupying excellent squares.  We can continue with ...Rfe8, improving our worst piece. If we ever manage to exchange light-squared bishops for example with ...Bf5-e4, we might easily be better with a good knight versus bad bishop scenario. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Fianchetto w/o Nc3 – 8.dxc5 Bxc5 9.a3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Without Nc3 – 8.dxc5 Bxc5 9.a3 Be7 10.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. a3
{ A highly topical variation that is also popular within the Chessable community, as both Sielecki and Naryanan recommend it in their courses. White's intentions are crystal clear - they wish to play b2-b4 and fianchetto the other bishop as well.  Interestingly, the little pawn move on the edge of the board is the best scoring move in the database. The combination of being easy to play yet very challenging creates the recipe for an attractive variation. It is therefore no wonder that the move is so popular and obtained the stamp of approval from the likes of Smyslov and Kramnik. }
9... Ne4
{ The sweet words about White's previous move should not leave us second-guessing our choice of opening, as the versatility of the Tarrasch Defense is of great magnitude! The dynamic potential and active piece play will always allow us to have resources available.  This energetic jump by our knight is a prime example. Since White has not developed their knight to c3 yet, we use the opportunity to occupy a strong central square. Moreover, the f6-square is vacated for our bishop, from where it can contest White's reign over the a1-h8 diagonal.   Note that this line should not be confused with the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2bp4/8/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc3  O-O  10.a3  variation, in which I recommend going  10...a5  .   In the current position,  9...a5  would be dubious after  10.Bg5  O-O  11.Qc2!  , followed by 12.Rd1. }
10. b4
{ By far the most logical move. White continues the plan that they put in motion on their previous move. }
10... Be7
{ Not a common retreat, but one that highlights another advantage of having played 9...Ne4. The bishop can reroute itself to f6, fighting for the long diagonal. }
11. Nfd2
{ I was about to send my analysis to the Chessable team when I noticed the following move was missing from my analysis. While still being a novelty in OTB @@StartBracket@@Over The Board@@EndBracket@@ games, it's Stockfish's preferred choice. }
11... f5
{ Strangely enough, the logical  11...Bf6  12.Ra2  has a lot of venoms since the rook will get to d2 later on, where it will be well placed.  Therefore, our best option is to secure the position of the knight on e4. }
12. Bb2 Bf6 { Contesting the long diagonal. } 13. Nxe4 fxe4
{ The most fighting option, since  13...dxe4  14.Qxd8+  leads to a slightly better endgame for White. }
14. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ Since the white rook is hanging, we are just in time to consolidate our center. }
15. Nd2 Bf5
{ The best square for the bishop, as it protects the central pawns and cannot come under attack by any of the white pieces. }
16. Nb3 Rd8
{ Protecting the d5-pawn. Finally, we are ready to castle on the next turn and complete development. }
17. b5 Ne5 18. Nd4 O-O
{ Castling is more important than trying to preserve the bishop at all costs. }
19. Nxf5 Qxf5 20. Qd4 b6
{ Securing the queenside pawns as well. Now that everything in our position is well protected, we can start looking for active counterplay. The typical plan of playing ...h5-h4-h3 should be the best way of doing so. }
*

