{ A highly topical variation that is also popular within the Chessable community, as both Sielecki and Naryanan recommend it in their courses. White's intentions are crystal clear - they wish to play b2-b4 and fianchetto the other bishop as well.  Interestingly, the little pawn move on the edge of the board is the best scoring move in the database. The combination of being easy to play yet very challenging creates the recipe for an attractive variation. It is therefore no wonder that the move is so popular and obtained the stamp of approval from the likes of Smyslov and Kramnik. }
9... Ne4
{ The sweet words about White's previous move should not leave us second-guessing our choice of opening, as the versatility of the Tarrasch Defense is of great magnitude! The dynamic potential and active piece play will always allow us to have resources available.  This energetic jump by our knight is a prime example. Since White has not developed their knight to c3 yet, we use the opportunity to occupy a strong central square. Moreover, the f6-square is vacated for our bishop, from where it can contest White's reign over the a1-h8 diagonal.   Note that this line should not be confused with the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2bp4/8/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc3  O-O  10.a3  variation, in which I recommend going  10...a5  .   In the current position,  9...a5  would be dubious after  10.Bg5  O-O  11.Qc2!  , followed by 12.Rd1. }
10. Nbd2
{ Since  10.Nc3  leads to the splintering of the pawn structure, this move is a logical alternative.  In the future, White will contemplate a manoeuvre to d4 via b3. }
10... Bb6
{ 10...O-O  would be entirely viable as well, but  11.Qc2  is just a tad annoying to meet in that case.  With the text move, we are not giving up anything in particular and will just castle on the next move. }
11. Nb3
{ A logical continuation of the previous play, but a dubious one.   11.Qc2  would have maintained the balance, but  11...Bf5  would still require precise play from White. }
11... O-O 12. Nbd4
{ The knight positions itself on a blockading square, but generally, it is better to attack isolated pawns than to blockade them. In this case, the knight sits nicely but the lack of pressure on our d5-pawn gives us an easy game. }
12... Re8
{ Black is already slightly better. There are two famous rules of thumb that White has broken over the last few moves.  The first one is that they have both knights protecting each other. This usually leads to the knights being rather uncoordinated and inflexible. That is exactly what is being the case here, as the knight on d4 is rather vulnerable.  The second rule is that isolated pawns should be attacked, rather than blockaded. Indeed, here our isolated pawn is extremely safe and we can easily place our positions on highly active positions. Our bishop will develop itself to g4, while the queen has an excellent post on f6, further increasing the pressure on the unstable knight on d4. }
