{ A highly topical variation that is also popular within the Chessable community, as both Sielecki and Naryanan recommend it in their courses. White's intentions are crystal clear - they wish to play b2-b4 and fianchetto the other bishop as well.  Interestingly, the little pawn move on the edge of the board is the best scoring move in the database. The combination of being easy to play yet very challenging creates the recipe for an attractive variation. It is therefore no wonder that the move is so popular and obtained the stamp of approval from the likes of Smyslov and Kramnik. }
9... Ne4
{ The sweet words about White's previous move should not leave us second-guessing our choice of opening, as the versatility of the Tarrasch Defense is of great magnitude! The dynamic potential and active piece play will always allow us to have resources available.  This energetic jump by our knight is a prime example. Since White has not developed their knight to c3 yet, we use the opportunity to occupy a strong central square. Moreover, the f6-square is vacated for our bishop, from where it can contest White's reign over the a1-h8 diagonal.   Note that this line should not be confused with the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2bp4/8/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc3  O-O  10.a3  variation, in which I recommend going  10...a5  .   In the current position,  9...a5  would be dubious after  10.Bg5  O-O  11.Qc2!  , followed by 12.Rd1. }
10. Qd3
{ 10.Qd3 has been played only once, but there is a clear objective behind the move, as White desires to play Nc3 without fracturing the pawn structure. }
10... O-O { Just carrying on with our plans and castle is best. } 11. Nc3 Nxc3
{ There is no real choice but to part with our central knight as both Nxe4 and Nxd5 were threatened. }
12. Qxc3
{ White has managed to get rid of our active knight, but the queen looks a bit funny on c3. }
12... Be7
{ Identical to the 10.b4 variation, the bishop transfers itself to f6, this time to harass the white queen. }
13. Be3
{ A rather logical developing move, strengthening White's central control in the process. It does however allow us to follow up with our plan. }
13... Bf6
{ This is definitely the best square on the board for our dark-squared bishop as it exerts great pressure on the center. }
14. Nd4
{ This move leads to variations extremely similar to 13.Nd4.   Moving aside with the queen with  14.Qb3  makes some sense, as White wishes to follow up with Rad1, increasing the pressure on our isolani. Fortunately, it is our turn first.  14...d4!  As often, we should take the opportunity and advance our isolani when presented.  15.Rad1  h6  Quite a subtle move, just creating some air for the king just in case. As it turns out, we also pass the ball back in White's court as it is surprisingly hard for them to make a useful move of their own. Among our next moves, we can look to play either ...Qd6, improving our queen slightly or even look for ...a5-a4 ideas, making White's queen uncomfortable. }
14... Bg4
{ Just like after 13.Nd4, we can counterattack the pawn on e2, instead of passively defending our c6-knight. }
15. Nxc6
{ A clever idea by White, noticing that  15...Bxc3  runs into  16.Nxd8  , losing material for us.  Fortunately, we don't have to be so obedient and can simply recapture the knight. }
15... bxc6 16. Qxc6 Bxe2 17. Rfe1 Bc4
{ The bishop once again returns back just in time. In fact, both of our bishops stand extremely well, exercising significant pressure on the white queenside. Moreover, White's queen is in a somewhat weird spot and can be attacked with ...Rc8 later on. }
