{ The sweet words about White's previous move should not leave us second-guessing our choice of opening, as the versatility of the Tarrasch Defense is of great magnitude! The dynamic potential and active piece play will always allow us to have resources available.  This energetic jump by our knight is a prime example. Since White has not developed their knight to c3 yet, we use the opportunity to occupy a strong central square. Moreover, the f6-square is vacated for our bishop, from where it can contest White's reign over the a1-h8 diagonal.   Note that this line should not be confused with the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/2bp4/8/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nc3  O-O  10.a3  variation, in which I recommend going  10...a5  .   In the current position,  9...a5  would be dubious after  10.Bg5  O-O  11.Qc2!  , followed by 12.Rd1. }
10. Nfd2
{ As in life, chess requires the ability to adjust one's plans according to the situation. Our knight is standing strong and mighty, so White desires to exchange it as soon as possible. This is a very critical variation, but I believe I found some very interesting ideas to combat it.   In most games, people have opted to sustain the knight by playing  10...f5  . I certainly believe this move is playable, but it is a committal one as well since it significantly weakens our pawn structure.   While looking for alternatives, I stumbled upon the bizarre  10...O-O!?  , ignoring White's threat altogether!   10...O-O  is my main recommendation and I covered  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n5/2bp4/4n3/P5P1/1P1NPPBP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...f5  as an alternative. }
10... O-O
{ A novelty that is certain to throw your opponent off their game @@StartBracket@@or chair@@EndBracket@@ immediately. Not addressing the threat of Nxe4 allows us to rapidly develop our pieces and fight for the initiative. }
11. Nxe4
{ White has to pick up the gauntlet, whether they like it or not. Any other move would render the previous play meaningless. }
11... dxe4 12. Qxd8
{ Leaving the queens on the board would be beneficial to us. However, even without the queens, our active pieces provide ample counterplay. }
12... Rxd8 13. Bxe4
{ Once again the only critical move, as otherwise, we will defend our pawn with ...f5. }
13... Bg4 { Developing our last minor piece with tempo is natural and best. }
14. Nc3
{ The safest and human choice, developing the knight and simultaneously defending on e2. }
14... Bd4
{ With the simple intention of ...Bxc3 followed by ...Bxe2. Interestingly, this is surprisingly hard to meet. }
15. Be3 Bxc3
{ A counterintuitive capture.   Note that  15...Bxe3  is no good. We would indeed ruin White's structure, but White would suddenly be quite active and our compensation has faded.  Luckily, there is a satisfactory alternative. }
16. bxc3 Bxe2 17. Rfb1 Rd7
{ White has a lovely pair of bishops, but Black is very solid and we have a sound pawn structure.   In the 15.Bf4 variation @@StartBracket@@the next variation@@EndBracket@@ I recommend @@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/pp3ppp/2n5/8/3bB1b1/P1N3P1/1P2PP1P/R1B2RK1 w - - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Bf4  Bxc3  16.bxc3  Bxe2  17.Rfb1  Ba6!  in a similar position. Although @@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/pp3ppp/2n5/8/4B3/P1P1B1P1/4bP1P/RR4K1 b - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Ba6  would be possible here as well, we can use the subtle difference of White's dark-squared bishop not covering the b8-square in order to start with this. }
18. Rxb7
{ This tactical strike shouldn't bring White much as the presence of opposite-coloured bishops should bring us a comfortable draw.  It is important to understand why our previous move is possible now, and less good with the bishop on f4 instead of e3. }
18... Rxb7 19. Bxc6 Rab8
{ This is the difference: the b8-square is not controlled by White and therefore, we can force an ending with opposite-coloured bishops. }
20. Bxb7 Rxb7 { Black should hold without too many difficulties. } *


