{ As in life, chess requires the ability to adjust one's plans according to the situation. Our knight is standing strong and mighty, so White desires to exchange it as soon as possible. This is a very critical variation, but I believe I found some very interesting ideas to combat it.   In most games, people have opted to sustain the knight by playing  10...f5  . I certainly believe this move is playable, but it is a committal one as well since it significantly weakens our pawn structure.   While looking for alternatives, I stumbled upon the bizarre  10...O-O!?  , ignoring White's threat altogether!   10...O-O  is my main recommendation and I covered  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2n5/2bp4/4n3/P5P1/1P1NPPBP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...f5  as an alternative. }
10... O-O
{ A novelty that is certain to throw your opponent off their game @@StartBracket@@or chair@@EndBracket@@ immediately. Not addressing the threat of Nxe4 allows us to rapidly develop our pieces and fight for the initiative. }
11. Nxe4
{ White has to pick up the gauntlet, whether they like it or not. Any other move would render the previous play meaningless. }
11... dxe4 12. Qxd8
{ Leaving the queens on the board would be beneficial to us. However, even without the queens, our active pieces provide ample counterplay. }
12... Rxd8 13. Bxe4
{ Once again the only critical move, as otherwise, we will defend our pawn with ...f5. }
13... Bg4 { Developing our last minor piece with tempo is natural and best. }
14. e3
{ The top engine move, but it strikes me as a rather inhuman choice. Surely, it is tempting to bring out some pieces as White as well. As always, however, the silicon machine has a point as the pawn on e3 does restrict our dark-squared bishop severely. Therefore, we must continue our piece play along the light squares. }
14... Ne5
{ There is no time to think about the pawn on b7, we must and shall continue to activate our pieces to the maximum. }
15. Bxb7
{ White is not backing down either and takes as many pawns as possible. Slower moves would not suffice and give us ample compensation in various ways. }
15... Rab8 16. Bg2
{ We have arrived at a difficult moment, where there are several possible moves at our disposal. In my assessment, Black's best play is quite ingenious. }
16... Be2 { Attacking the rook leaves White with only one satisfactory reply. }
17. Re1 Bg4
{ A surprising retreat; didn't the bishop just come from g4? As it turns out, White's rook is significantly worse on e1 than on f1. The reason is that any ...Nd3 jump now comes with a direct tempo on the rook. This detail is so important that it justifies spending two tempi to force the rook there. }
18. Nc3 { Developing the knight at last. } 18... a5
{ A wonderful move, as this is prophylaxis against any b2-b4 ideas. The deficit of 2 pawns is hardly felt since White has no clear way of untangling their pieces.   The immediate  18...Nd3  was also possible, but it is even better to keep the knight on e5 for the moment, retaining the idea of ...Nf3+ as well. }
19. Ne4
{ A tempting move, but this allows us to demonstrate the points behind our previous play. }
19... Nd3 20. Rf1 Be2
{ Trapping the rook and thus gaining the exchange, while retaining active pieces. }
*

