[Black "Fianchetto Without Nc3 – 8.dxc5 Bxc5 9.Qc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. dxc5
{ White releases the tension as soon as we have played ...Be7, forcing us to spend another tempo recapturing. Moreover, it should be noted that White has delayed the development of the b1-knight. By doing so, White gets access to a couple of new setups that need to be investigated. }
8... Bxc5 9. Qc2
{ A crafty move, asking where the bishop would like to go. Depending on our next move, White will make up their mind about where to develop the pieces. On the flip side, the queen on c2 can be awkwardly placed, as it might come under attack by one of our minor pieces early on.   9.Nc3  is a direct transposition to the chapter Fianchetto with Nc3 – 9.dxc5 Bxc5. }
9... Bb6
{ The only correct choice, keeping the bishop as active as possible on the diagonal. }
10. Nc3 O-O
{ Unless you're playing Kramnik chess, castling is almost always a good idea!   Don't get coaxed into playing  10...d4  , since after  11.Na4  the isolani might quickly fall prey to the enemy pieces. }
11. Na4 { White keeps on chasing the bishop. } 11... Re8
{ While it would be pleasant to keep the dark-squared bishop, it would allow our opponent to establish a positional bind after  11...Bc7  12.Be3  .  Therefore, simply bringing the rook to the semi-open file is healthy and sound. }
12. Bg5 { A fine move, but White may soon regret not capturing on b6. } 12...
Ba5
{ Not allowing the opponent a second chance.   If White would try to go for the aforementioned strategic idea of  13.Be3  , it would run into the typical yet powerful  13...Rxe3!  . }
13. a3 h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 { We have an active position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Fianchetto w/o Nc3 – 8.dxc5 Bxc5 – Other 9th Moves"]
[Black "Fianchetto Without Nc3 – 8.dxc5 Bxc5 9.Qc2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. dxc5
{ White releases the tension as soon as we have played ...Be7, forcing us to spend another tempo recapturing. Moreover, it should be noted that White has delayed the development of the b1-knight. By doing so, White gets access to a couple of new setups that need to be investigated. }
8... Bxc5 9. Qc2
{ A crafty move, asking where the bishop would like to go. Depending on our next move, White will make up their mind about where to develop the pieces. On the flip side, the queen on c2 can be awkwardly placed, as it might come under attack by one of our minor pieces early on.   9.Nc3  is a direct transposition to the chapter Fianchetto with Nc3 – 9.dxc5 Bxc5. }
9... Bb6
{ The only correct choice, keeping the bishop as active as possible on the diagonal. }
10. Nc3 O-O
{ Unless you're playing Kramnik chess, castling is almost always a good idea!   Don't get coaxed into playing  10...d4  , since after  11.Na4  the isolani might quickly fall prey to the enemy pieces. }
11. Na4 { White keeps on chasing the bishop. } 11... Re8
{ While it would be pleasant to keep the dark-squared bishop, it would allow our opponent to establish a positional bind after  11...Bc7  12.Be3  .  Therefore, simply bringing the rook to the semi-open file is healthy and sound. }
12. Nxb6 Qxb6
{ Although we have lost one of our bishops, our queen has occupied a strong position. As usual, we have a very simple scheme of developing the light-squared bishop, followed by bringing the a8-rook into the game. }
13. Bg5 { The only way to attempt to obstruct our plans. } 13... Ng4
{ This certainly is a highly unusual idea for the Tarrasch, as the knight typically goes to e4.   The reason for this sudden change of direction is quite simple, as  13...Ne4  would run into  14.Be3  .  After the text, the idea is to play ...h6 next, sending the bishop back. Moreover, at times, the g4-knight can spring back into action via e5. }
14. h3 Nge5
{ The knight continues its journey, offering a trade of knights. A trade only beneficial to us, as it would strengthen our control over the d4-square. }
15. Nxe5 Rxe5
{ Not only is White's bishop hanging, but ...Nd4 is another threat hanging in the air. }
16. Qd2 { The only way of conveniently dealing with the threats. } 16... d4
{ The further the isolani advances, the more we strengthen our grip over White's position. }
17. Bf4 Rb5
{ A peculiar idea but by no means a bad one. The rook is well placed on b5 as it attacks the b2-pawn. If we manage to get ...Be6-d5 in under favourable circumstances, we can already start thinking about being better. }
