[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Fianchetto w/o Nc3 – Other 8th Moves"]
[Black "Fianchetto Without Nc3 – 8.b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. b3
{ This has been played by some strong players, including a very young Anish Giri, although he was already rated nearly 2700! However, we should be happy to see this move as it allows us to obtain a pretty comfortable game. }
8... Ne4
{ A typical idea once White fianchettos the second bishop. In several variations in the 9.dxc5 Bxc5 chapter, we are willing to back to e7, to finally go to f6.  In this case, we save two tempi, as our bishop is immediately able to occupy the long diagonal from f6 - saving some tempi should be good news for us.  In general, it is good to strive for the ...Ne4 & ...Bf6 setup once White hints at playing their bishop to b2. The reason is that our f6-bishop will be opposing the b2-bishop and it will be more active than its counterpart since White's bishop is looking at their own d4-pawn.  A secondary reason is that after White has played b2-b3, the c3-square has been weakened and White can not as easily challenge our central knight with Nc3 anymore. }
9. Bb2 Bf6
{ I feel in these scenarios, a standoff between the two bishops is generally beneficial to us. Our bishop is actively exerting pressure, while its counterpart is only keeping the d4-pawn protected, but has no active prospects. }
10. e3
{ A close second after  10.Na3  in the popularity ranking is this move, strengthening the center. }
10... Bg4
{ A drawback of White's last move is that it allows this nasty pin, creating strong pressure on another diagonal. }
11. h3 Bxf3
{ We do not mind parting with the bishop, as it means that White loses an important defender of the d4-pawn. }
12. Bxf3 cxd4
{ It is clever to capture in the center immediately, as  12...O-O  13.Nc3!  might let White escape to a drawish endgame after  13...cxd4  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Bxe4  dxe3  16.Qxd8  exf2+  17.Kxf2  Bxd8  . Although Black is up a pawn here, the two bishops offer White enough compensation.  After the text move, White has no such escapes and will be forced to defend a passive position with little prospects. }
13. exd4 O-O
{ By now it is clear that while our bishop is fantastic, its counterpart on b2 fulfils the sad task of passively defending its pawn. We can continue to add the pressure through ...Qb6 next, with a very pleasant position. }
*

