{ This move contains more venom than you would initially expect. If we impulsively play  8...O-O?  , we would suddenly be much worse after  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.b4  . }
8... c4
{ A clever response, as the a2-a3 move is not beneficial for White in these structures. If anything, we might be able to take some profit as the light squares on the queenside can become vulnerable. }
9. Nc3 O-O 10. Bg5
{ After White makes all the sensible moves we have reached a line from the 9.Bg5 c4 variation, in which White rarely plays a2-a3. }
10... Be6 { Developing the bishop and overprotecting d5. } 11. Ne5 h6
{ Essentially forcing White to give up the bishop pair. } 12. Bxf6 Bxf6
{ We have achieved a great version of the lines arising from the 9.Bg5 c4 chapter. We can continue the game by expanding on the queenside. }
