[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Fianchetto w/o Nc3 – Other 8th Moves"]
[Black "Fianchetto Without Nc3 – 8.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3
{ The fianchetto variation has always stood out as the critical method of combating the Tarrasch. The main reason is that from g2, the bishop will be able to exert great pressure on d5. In addition, the castled king will be highly secure. }
5... Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Be3
{ Korchnoi employed this rare sideline no less than four times in his tournament games, including one versus Kasparov, so I think it's fair to dub it the Korchnoi Variation. }
8... c4
{ The most principled reaction, as the bishop on e3 suddenly looks like a big pawn in an awkward position. }
9. b3 O-O
{ While it's possible to capture on b3 immediately, I prefer keeping the tension for a bit longer. }
10. bxc4
{ The sharpest continuation.   10.Ne5  would be a transposition to the 9.Ne5 variation. }
10... dxc4
{ After the trade of pawns, White has acquired two potentially strong central pawns. For the moment, however, the bishop on e3 stands in the way of the e-pawn and it will take some time before the pawns can be set in motion.   On the other hand, our pieces are already standing in good positions, and we have a queenside majority which can become a force to reckoned with. }
11. Nc3 Qa5
{ The queen swings out, attacking the c3-knight and vacating the d8-square for our rook. }
12. d5 { A clever idea, fighting for the initiative. } 12... Rd8
{ We shouldn't be seduced by the hanging knight on c3 as after  12...Qxc3  13.dxc6  White is the one having all the fun.  By pinning the pawn, suddenly all kinds of things start to hang for White. }
13. Nd2
{ This was played in the game Lobron-Lautier, Baden-Baden 1992. Now, Lautier missed an opportunity to carry out a powerful strong exchange sacrifice. }
13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Rxd5 15. Bxd5 Qxd5
{ With two bishops, threats to the white king and some impressive pawns on the queenside, Black has the upper hand. }
