9. Nxe4 Qf4
{ Our queen finds a nice home here, as it cannot easily be attacked and it attacks the white knight at the same time. }
10. Nfg5
{ A funny way of defending the knight, which has been tried by Russian GM Ponkratov in 2012. White hopes to get in g2-g3 to dislodge our queen. It is our turn first, however. }
10... c4
{ A satisfying dual-purpose move that closes the white bishop’s diagonal and at the same time opens ours. }
11. Qd2
{ White must exchange queen to stop the check, leading to a roughly equal endgame. }
11... Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 Nc6
{ Developing both the knight and getting ready to castle. } 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14.
Bxc4 Nxd4
{ Despite having a slightly weakened pawn structure, there is enough dynamic play for us to compensate. The white king is yet to find a safe place and our next couple of moves will be easy to make. }
