{ I consider this to be one of the most dangerous lines in the entire course. Generally, the exchange of bishop for knight would be good for us, but in this specific case, White has a very concrete idea in mind of opening the position through e2-e4. By first sidetracking our queen this idea gains in strength. However, while being a serious attempt at gaining the advantage, I believe that we will be well-armed to fight it. }
7... Qxf6
{ There is no real choice as recapturing with the pawn would ruin our pawn structure. }
8. e4
{ White continues with their aforementioned idea.   8.e3  c4  transposes. }
8... dxe4
{ Again there is not much choice as we cannot allow White to take on d5 with the pawn. Now, White can either recapture on e4 immediately or interpose a check on b5 first.   In my view  9.Nxe4  is the most testing of both as it retains some more flexibility in White's options. In general, however, both moves likely lead to the same position. }
9. Nxe4 Qf4
{ Our queen finds a nice home here, as it cannot easily be attacked and it attacks the white knight at the same time. }
10. Bb5+ Nc6
{ It is important to always meet the check on b5 in this way as from here the knight exerts pressure on the center and White has no time to pin us with d4-d5. }
11. Qe2
{ A critical position in the variation has been reached. We are at crossroads and have to choose which direction to take. The choice is between castling queenside or castling kingside.  While the former sounds much more enterprising, the variations are extremely sharp and dangerous. My personal preference is therefore to prepare castling kingside. While sometimes having to accept a slightly worse position, we can be sure we do not get blown off the board.   However, for those not faint of heart, I will include the alternative of  11...O-O-O!?  . }
11... Be7
{ The solid choice, as we will simply castle kingside on the next turn and there will be no danger to our king. }
12. O-O O-O { Mission completed. } 13. Nxc5
{ Grabbing the pawn is both the most logical and the best continuation. } 13...
Nxd4 { Using this small tactic we simplify the position. } 14. Nxd4 Bxc5
{ The right knight to capture, as  14...Qxd4  15.Nxe6  fxe6  16.Qxe6  Rf7  17.Bc4  loses material for us. }
15. Nxe6 fxe6
{ After the exchanges we have reached an opposite-coloured bishop position. White is a little bit better as their pawn structure is better. If they wish they can capture our weakness on e6 with check right here.  Yet, I believe the position is decent for us. Our bishop on c5 is exerting serious pressure on f2. Combined with our major pieces this will force us to tie White's pieces to defence and be unable to activate themselves.  Moreover, the presence of the opposite-coloured bishops makes drawing tendencies very high as the exchange of all the major pieces is generally considered an easy draw. }
16. Qxe6+
{ Of the white options this appears to be the most logical choice. White captures a pawn by check. }
16... Kh8 17. Qe2
{ White hurries back to defend on f2, but capturing a pawn that was not too important anyway has cost them a lot of time. }
17... Rad8
{ Bringing the final piece into the game, with some strong ideas as 18...Rd2 is a strong threat. }
18. g3 Qd2
{ If we cannot play the rook to d2 we use that square for the queen. } 19. Rae1
a5
{ Just like in the variation after 16.g3, we play this strengthening move, ensuring our bishop will always be safe and cannot be attacked by a3-b4 in the future. }
