16. g3
{ This move has been the choice of all the correspondence players in this variation. White knows that the pawn on e6 does not run away and hopes to drive our pieces from their strong positions first. }
16... Qf3
{ An improvement over  16...Qd6  which was the choice of correspondence players.  The queen stands very active here, and White is faced with a tough question. The exchange of queens would only bring the game closer to a draw but at the same time, White does not really wish to tolerate the queen on f3 either. }
17. Rae1 { Aiming to exchange queens under favourable circumstances. } 17...
Rad8 { Once again, playing for activity is the right way. } 18. Qxe6+
{ White has to capture the pawn eventually. } 18... Kh8 19. Qe2 a5
{ A useful move in many endgames, as after we play ...b6, we have created a block on the queenside that can hardly be touched. White is still faced with the pressure on the pawn on f2.  If they were to exchange queens by Qxf3 we can continue to keep this pressure by ...Rdf8. A final important idea to keep in mind is the move ...g5, where we reach an endgame. Thereby we seriously hamper any white advances on the kingside even further. }
