{ A critical position in the variation has been reached. We are at crossroads and have to choose which direction to take. The choice is between castling queenside or castling kingside.  While the former sounds much more enterprising, the variations are extremely sharp and dangerous. My personal preference is therefore to prepare castling kingside. While sometimes having to accept a slightly worse position, we can be sure we do not get blown off the board.   However, for those not faint of heart, I will include the alternative of  11...O-O-O!?  . }
11... O-O-O
{ If you have chosen to investigate this move, buckle up and get yourselves ready for a wild ride. }
12. Bxc6
{ Naturally, White has to ruin our pawn structure in front of the king. } 12...
bxc6 13. O-O
{ It is good to take a moment and have a look at the position. Our king is indeed without shelter, and we will have to be on the lookout for several dangerous ideas, the most prominent being the ever-lurking check of Qa6+.  Luckily, we do have quite some positive things working in our favour as well. Our main asset is the pair of bishops in an open position. This means that the bishops can often defend the king and create counterplay at the same time. At the moment, the white king is relatively safe, but things can quickly change in that respect as well. }
13... Bd5
{ Following in the footsteps of the Indian super talent Gukesh. In most variations, this bishop will be our star piece as it serves the dual purpose of defending both our king and assisting in the creation of an attack of our own. }
14. Rfe1 { Simply defending the knight is by far the best move. } 14... cxd4
{ Opening up the way for our second bishop to join the game as well. Especially ...Bb4 is becoming a serious resource to keep in mind. }
15. Nxd4
{ This has not been played yet but is a very logical recapture and it must be considered. }
15... Kb7 { It is time to stop the threat of Qa6+ once and for all. } 16. Rac1
{ Bringing the rook into the attack is dangerous but we have a serious idea up our sleeve as well.   16.g3  Qc7  transposes to the lines starting with 15.g3. }
16... f5
{ Suddenly the knights don't feel so comfortable in the center no longer. } 17.
Rxc6
{ Continuing in the attacking spirit, but we should not back down and accept the material. }
17... Bxc6 18. Nxc6 Kxc6
{ Our king has lost all its shelter, but there is no mate fortunately for us and White should look for ways to force a perpetual check. }
19. Qa6+ Kd7
{ 19...Kc7  would be fine too, just do not go up the board with  19...Kd5  ! }
20. Qb7+ Qc7 { Blocking the check and setting a bit of a trap. } 21. Qd5+
{ The right way to make the game end in a draw.   The tempting  21.Rd1+  would turn out to be a losing mistake as after  21...Ke8  22.Qxc7  Rxd1  the game ends in a win for us. }
21... Kc8 22. Qa8+ Kd7 *

