15... Qc7
{ Just like in other variations, this is the best square for the queen, staying near our king for defensive purposes. }
16. Nxd4 Kb7
{ Preventing Qa6+ and overprotecting the pawn on c6, as well as getting out of the c-file. Talk about multi-purpose moves! If we get a chance we will try to play ...h5-h4 as soon as possible to disturb the white king. }
17. b4
{ Certainly the most dangerous-looking move, not hiding any intentions and coming straight after our king. }
17... Qb6
{ The queen comes around to bother White from the other side of the board. }
18. Nc2
{ This retreat of the knight certainly does not seem too impressive, but there were no easy options as ...Bxb4 was also a threat. From c2 the knight at least protects the pawn on b4. }
18... h5 { There we go! It is time to create an attack of our own. } 19. Nc3
{ White can no longer tolerate our super-strong bishop and has to exchange it. It is a time-consuming plan, however, and our h-pawn will continue inching closer to the white kingside. }
19... h4 20. Nxd5 cxd5
{ White has managed to exchange the bishop, but now the road for our queen has been opened through h6. A super sharp struggle will be ahead, but our position is easier to play as it is now on White to show some accurate defensive moves. }
