{ If you have chosen to investigate this move, buckle up and get yourselves ready for a wild ride. }
12. Bxc6
{ Naturally, White has to ruin our pawn structure in front of the king. } 12...
bxc6 13. O-O
{ It is good to take a moment and have a look at the position. Our king is indeed without shelter, and we will have to be on the lookout for several dangerous ideas, the most prominent being the ever-lurking check of Qa6+.  Luckily, we do have quite some positive things working in our favour as well. Our main asset is the pair of bishops in an open position. This means that the bishops can often defend the king and create counterplay at the same time. At the moment, the white king is relatively safe, but things can quickly change in that respect as well. }
13... Bd5
{ Following in the footsteps of the Indian super talent Gukesh. In most variations, this bishop will be our star piece as it serves the dual purpose of defending both our king and assisting in the creation of an attack of our own. }
14. Rae1
{ This move was recommended in 1.d4 for Ambitious Chess Improvers and definitely deserves attention.  There actually is a deep idea behind the move, which is important to know. After  14.Rfe1  we reply  14...cxd4  , but this no longer works now. After @@StartFEN@@2kr1b1r/p4ppp/2p5/2pb4/3PNq2/5N2/PP2QPPP/4RRK1 b - - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Rae1  cxd4  15.Qa6+  Kb8  16.Nxd4  Bb4  17.Nxc6+  Bxc6  18.Qxc6  Bxe1  19.Nc5  wins for White.  Note that with the rook on a1 we would have mate in 2 with 19...Qxf2. A subtle, but important difference, forcing us to alter our plans somewhat. }
14... Kb7
{ Fortunately, this seems to solve all of our problems, preventing Qa6+, and now White's rooks are rather awkwardly placed. }
15. Qc2
{ The only testing idea.   After  15.Nxc5+  Bxc5  16.dxc5  Rhe8  we are extremely active and have no problems. }
15... cxd4 { Freeing our bishop on f8 to join the game. } 16. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Quite a picturesque position, since both sides have different but excellent minor pieces. }
17. g3
{ Since the queen was occupying an excellent position on f4, White forces it to move. }
17... Qh6
{ A rather strange square for the queen, but it turns out to be best here, escaping from any possible tactical motives. Although the game remains sharp, Black is doing alright. It is especially key to try and involve the h8-rook in the game via e8 as soon as possible. }
