13. e4 { The most direct attempt, but we are well prepared for it. } 13... cxd4
{ It is time to release the tension. } 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. exd5
{ A clever in-between move, netting White the gain of a pawn. } 15... Bd7
{ It is much more important to keep the bishop pair than to hang on to the knight. }
16. Qxd4 Qxd4 17. Rxd4 Bd6
{ Lots of exchanges later we have reached an endgame where White is up a pawn on d5. However, it is mostly obstructing the range of the white pieces. Moreover, our pair of bishops provides enough compensation. }
