7. Qa4+
{ A very uncommon move, and I would not have included it in the course had I not noticed that Capablanca employed it once back in 1920. }
7... Nbd7
{ The correct reply, as the choice of Capablanca's opponent of  7...Nc6  is well met by  8.e3  c4  9.Bxc4!  .   Precisely this devilish trick also occurs via the move order of @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/4bn2/2pp2B1/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e3  c4  8.Qa4+  . Fortunately, we have our resources there too. }
8. e4
{ The principled continuation, but we will be well equipped to meet this push. }
8... Be7
{ Keeping the tension and preferring to finish development instead is important. }
9. Bxf6
{ Grabbing the pawn is tempting and was the choice of the Dutch Grandmaster Zhaoqin Peng.   If White continues to advance by  9.e5  we would reply with  9...Ne4  . }
9... Bxf6 10. exd5 Bg4
{ Since we have a strong pair of bishops, and a serious lead in development to boot, White should be the one taking care not to end up in a worse position. }
*

