1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5
{ A vicious variation that should be studied carefully. As I have not been able to find a name for this variation yet, I will call it the Korchnoi Variation. He was one of the first players to employ it regularly at a high level. }
5... Nf6
{ As explained in the intro, this is our choice at all times.   5...Be7  is the most popular choice but the exchange of bishops leads to somewhat worse and passive positions for us, with no hope for more than a draw. }
6. Nc3 Be6
{ This position signifies a major component in our repertoire. White is at crossroads and it is our task to carefully examine their options. To clarify things, White has about 3 ways to approach the position:  1. They can either prepare for a quick assault going e2-e4, creating a sharp mess in the process.  2. Most people give preference to playing a slower game through e2-e3, intending to simply develop the bishop and castle.  3. Last, but certainly, not least is the ever-existing option of a fianchetto by going g2-g3. There are a few other sidelines, but they are no reason for concern. }
7. e4
{ This is recommended by Kamil Plichta in his course: Go for the throat - Play 1.d4. While he does an excellent job at convincing his readers about the strength of the move, fortunately for us, it is quite easily dealt with.   If White does wish to play aggressive with e2-e4, it is more dangerous to play with  7.Bxf6  first. }
7... Be7
{ Simple development is the way to go here.   Plichta only analyses  7...dxe4  , after which things indeed could get dangerous for Black. }
8. e5
{ In advancing the pawns White merely makes them vulnerable to attack in this case.   8.Bxf6  is highly likely to transpose after an eventual Bb5+:  8...Bxf6  9.Bb5+  Nc6  is covered here and  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/pp3ppp/4bb2/2pp4/3PP3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.exd5  Bxd5  10.Bb5+  Nc6  also transposes. }
8... Nfd7
{ A strong reply, as from here the knight pressurizes the central pawns.   8...Ne4  may look more appealing at first sight, but sometimes it is better to take a small step back. }
9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nb5
{ The only real way to make sense of White's previous play. Nd6+ and Nc7, trapping the rook, seem to be serious threats, should we be worried? }
10... O-O
{ The answer is most definitely no! We happily allow White to take our rook as that time-consuming operation will give us more than enough time to arrange a counterattack. }
11. Nc7 Nxe5
{ Using this cute discovery attack we get to open the e-file towards the opponent's monarch. }
12. Nxa8 Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Nc6
{ 13...Bg4+  would unfortunately not win us the game immediately as it is met by  14.Qe3  .  Therefore, it is best to simply continue our development. Besides having a huge development advantage, we are now also ready to pick up the knight on a8. }
14. dxc5
{ White has to bite the bullet as allowing ...Nxd4 would be disastrous. } 14...
Nb4
{ We should not let White off the hook and continue our initiative.   Had we captured the knight with  14...Rxa8  , White would have been able to get their king out of the danger zone just in time by  15.Bd3  . }
15. Rc1 Nxa2 { Taking the pawn while continuing to bother the opponent. } 16.
Rc2 Bf5+
{ At last we get to use our discovery attack on the king. This time making use of another sweet trick to capture one more pawn. }
17. Re2 Qxc5 { Suddenly mate on c1 is threatened as well. } 18. Rd2
{ Stopping the mate and forcing us to finally make one defensive move. } 18...
g6
{ Giving a check on c1 or e8 may have looked to be quite tempting, but as Nimzowitsch already said: the threat is stronger than its execution.  We should not forget that the white knight is still stranded on a8, and after we capture it, we are doing completely fine materially speaking. }
19. Be2 Qc1+
{ A tad more accurate than capturing the knight. We are already deep in the lines and White has had to find some seriously good moves not to lose. Soon, we will likely reach an endgame that should be balanced. }
20. Bd1 Rxa8 21. Qe3
{ Protecting the rook, and finally getting ready to castle. } 21... Qc4
{ Not just yet! } 22. b3 Qc3 23. O-O Qxe3 24. fxe3 Nb4
{ Having two pawns for the exchange, we are doing completely fine. } *


