[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) 5.Bg5"]
[Black "5.Bg5 Nf6 6.Nc3 Be6 7.dxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5
{ A vicious variation that should be studied carefully. As I have not been able to find a name for this variation yet, I will call it the Korchnoi Variation. He was one of the first players to employ it regularly at a high level. }
5... Nf6
{ As explained in the intro, this is our choice at all times.   5...Be7  is the most popular choice but the exchange of bishops leads to somewhat worse and passive positions for us, with no hope for more than a draw. }
6. Nc3 Be6
{ This position signifies a major component in our repertoire. White is at crossroads and it is our task to carefully examine their options. To clarify things, White has about 3 ways to approach the position:  1. They can either prepare for a quick assault going e2-e4, creating a sharp mess in the process.  2. Most people give preference to playing a slower game through e2-e3, intending to simply develop the bishop and castle.  3. Last, but certainly, not least is the ever-existing option of a fianchetto by going g2-g3. There are a few other sidelines, but they are no reason for concern. }
7. dxc5
{ A mundane approach, making sure that ...c5-c4 will not be played but allowing us to develop our bishop to an excellent square in one go. }
7... Bxc5 8. e3 O-O
{ As often in the Tarrasch Defence, Black’s moves play themselves. } 9. Bd3
{ Whilst being the less popular choice, this more active positioning of the bishop appears a tad more challenging to me. The variations will be almost completely similar to the other bishop move, but there are a couple of subtle differences that are good to be aware of as will be explained soon. }
9... h6 { Playing in the same manner as after 9.Be2 is a good idea for now. }
10. Bh4 Nc6 11. O-O Bb6
{ A small twist compared to 9.Be2, as there we included the moves ...Rc8 and Rc1.  The reason for omitting these moves here is that with the bishop on d3 instead of e2, it may find a nice place for itself on b1 with the rook on c1. However, with the rook still on a1, the idea of Bb1 would be much less good as it leaves the rook locked up. }
12. Na4 g5 13. Bg3 Ne4
{ We have reached the exact same position as in the 9.Be2 line, only without Rc1 and ...Rc8 being played. }
14. Rc1 Qf6
{ The queen stands excellently here, influencing almost the entire board. } 15.
Bb1
{ A typical idea, intending to set up a battery with the queen going to d3. However, as we have not played ...Rc8 yet, we are the first to strike. }
15... Nxg3 16. hxg3 d4
{ If one can play this liberating move without any consequences that is usually a good sign. }
17. Nxb6 axb6 18. Qd3
{ Things look dangerous for a moment, but only for a moment. } 18... Rfd8
{ Creating a square for the king on f8, so Qh7+ is nothing more than a check. Our pieces are active, and we have a very decent position. }
*

