[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) 5.Bg5"]
[Black "5.Bg5 Nf6 6.Nc3 Be6 7.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5
{ A vicious variation that should be studied carefully. As I have not been able to find a name for this variation yet, I will call it the Korchnoi Variation. He was one of the first players to employ it regularly at a high level. }
5... Nf6
{ As explained in the intro, this is our choice at all times.   5...Be7  is the most popular choice but the exchange of bishops leads to somewhat worse and passive positions for us, with no hope for more than a draw. }
6. Nc3 Be6
{ This position signifies a major component in our repertoire. White is at crossroads and it is our task to carefully examine their options. To clarify things, White has about 3 ways to approach the position:  1. They can either prepare for a quick assault going e2-e4, creating a sharp mess in the process.  2. Most people give preference to playing a slower game through e2-e3, intending to simply develop the bishop and castle.  3. Last, but certainly, not least is the ever-existing option of a fianchetto by going g2-g3. There are a few other sidelines, but they are no reason for concern. }
7. e3
{ Since direct attempts can be met in a good way, most people have preferred the text, wishing to play a slower game and complete development through means of Be2 and castling before committing to action. }
7... c4
{ As in many other variations in the Tarrasch, we use this idea of gaining space on the Queenside. At the same time enlarging the scope of our bishop on f8, and diminishing that of the bishop on f1.  White, on the other hand, will usually attempt to break our structure by e3-e4 or b2-b3, or at times attempt to put pressure on the d5-pawn. }
8. Bxf6
{ A speciality of Armenian Grandmaster Haik Martirosyan who employed it three times against Indian prodigy Nihal Sarin. From a strategic standpoint, this exchange is decent for us, but White hopes that the queen will be misplaced on f6 as it loses the protection of the pawn on d5 and the short-term play outweighs the long-term factors. }
8... Qxf6 9. a3 { A typical idea, stopping the possibility of ...Bb4. } 9...
Nc6
{ The saying 'develop your knights before your bishops' holds true here, as our bishop on f8 is not entirely sure yet where it would like to position itself. }
10. g3
{ This is the point of White's setup. Having waited with developing the bishop White has retained the possibility of a fianchetto. }
10... Bd6
{ As b4 is not available we have chosen the second most active square for the bishop. From here it may reroute itself via c7 to a5 at times as well. }
11. Bg2 O-O
{ Our development has been completed and as we have the pair of bishops, White must act quickly in order not to fall into a strategically worse position. }
12. O-O Rfd8
{ The right square for the rook, as it overprotects the pawn on d5 and it will be useful here in case of an opening in the center. If allowed, we would like to play the other rook to b8, sustaining plans of ...b5-b4. }
13. b3
{ The most dangerous by White, intending to compromise our pawn structure. }
13... Na5
{ A knight on the rim is dim is a saying that often applies, but not here. Rather, from here it puts pressure on b3 and covers our pawn on c4 as well. }
14. bxc4 dxc4
{ The first time I saw this move, I had a tough time grasping it. Surely, our knight was destined to c4 and we give up the entire center now. However, a closer look reveals that things are not so simple. Would we had taken back with the knight, our pawn on d5 would have been destined to be a long-time target.  By the somewhat counterintuitive recapture of the pawn, our knight now finds an excellent square on b3, our pawn on c4 is a passed pawn after all, and since our pieces are so well positioned we are in good shape to meet White's central pawn pushes. }
15. e4
{ Swift action by White is the best way.   The only real alternative of  15.Nd2  is well met by  15...Qe7  , and as e3-e4 will be increasingly hard to manufacture our Queenside play will become menacing. }
15... Nb3 { Spicing up the game even further. } 16. e5 Bxe5
{ A strong temporary sacrifice, destroying White's central pawn formation. }
17. Nxe5 Rxd4
{ We have two pawns for the lost piece and White's queen, rook and knight are all undefended. }
18. Qe2 Nxa1 19. Rxa1 Re8
{ After a brief tactical skirmish we have reached a complicated position, with approximate material equality of two pawns and a rook for two minor pieces. The game is around balanced, but it seems easier to me to play for Black as White should still find a way to coordinate their pieces in a good way. }
