[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5
{ A vicious variation that should be studied carefully. As I have not been able to find a name for this variation yet, I will call it the Korchnoi Variation. He was one of the first players to employ it regularly at a high level. }
5... Nf6
{ As explained in the intro, this is our choice at all times.   5...Be7  is the most popular choice but the exchange of bishops leads to somewhat worse and passive positions for us, with no hope for more than a draw. }
6. Nc3 Be6
{ This position signifies a major component in our repertoire. White is at crossroads and it is our task to carefully examine their options. To clarify things, White has about 3 ways to approach the position:  1. They can either prepare for a quick assault going e2-e4, creating a sharp mess in the process.  2. Most people give preference to playing a slower game through e2-e3, intending to simply develop the bishop and castle.  3. Last, but certainly, not least is the ever-existing option of a fianchetto by going g2-g3. There are a few other sidelines, but they are no reason for concern. }
7. e3
{ Since direct attempts can be met in a good way, most people have preferred the text, wishing to play a slower game and complete development through means of Be2 and castling before committing to action. }
7... c4
{ As in many other variations in the Tarrasch, we use this idea of gaining space on the Queenside. At the same time enlarging the scope of our bishop on f8, and diminishing that of the bishop on f1.  White, on the other hand, will usually attempt to break our structure by e3-e4 or b2-b3, or at times attempt to put pressure on the d5-pawn. }
8. Be2
{ The logical follow-up after the last move, and the one that is by far the most popular as well. }
8... Bb4
{ The most active square for our bishop, so we should certainly position it right here.   9.Qa4+  is no worry to us as  9...Nc6  easily deals with that. }
9. O-O Nbd7
{ An uncommon move in the Tarrasch defence, and less popular than  9...O-O  . Yet, I have chosen to recommend this move in favour of the alternative. Although both moves are highly likely to transpose into one another, I found that  10.e4  is not particularly easy to meet if we start by castling.  As it transpires, we will be better prepared to meet the push of White's e-pawn after 9...Nbd7, while not giving up much else. The other reason for developing the knight to d7 instead of the traditional c6, is the overprotection of its colleague on f6, making it easier for our queen to remove itself from the pin. }
10. Ne5
{ If White wants to fight for the advantage, this active move has to be played. At times f2-f4 may be an idea, and it also frees f3 for the bishop. }
10... O-O 11. Bf3
{ If White does not wish to part with their dark-squared bishop this would be the logical alternative. Mounting the pressure on d5 to the absolute maximum. }
11... Qa5
{ Getting out of the pin just in time, while still keeping an eye on d5. } 12.
Nxd7
{ White does best exchanging the knight, as otherwise, we may entertain thoughts of playing ...Nxe5 ourselves. }
12... Nxd7 13. Qc2
{ The right choice by White. Slightly improving the queen as well as making sure ...Bf5 is not played soon. }
13... h6
{ There are several other possibilities, but I like this useful move, as well as gaining a tempo. It is never a bad idea to create some air for the king in the event of an unlikely back-rank checkmate later. }
14. Bh4 Rfe8
{ Another small move, just improving the rook a bit. The game has reached the phase of a slow, yet highly complex middlegame with chances for both sides.  We should attempt to improve our knight next, which can be done via two routes. Either via b6 to c8 and d6, or possibly even to a4 after an eventual exchange on c3. Another viable manoeuvre would be via f8 to g6 bothering the white bishop. Neither should we forget about playing ...b5 at an opportune moment. }
