7. e3
{ Since direct attempts can be met in a good way, most people have preferred the text, wishing to play a slower game and complete development through means of Be2 and castling before committing to action. }
7... c4
{ As in many other variations in the Tarrasch, we use this idea of gaining space on the Queenside. At the same time enlarging the scope of our bishop on f8, and diminishing that of the bishop on f1.  White, on the other hand, will usually attempt to break our structure by e3-e4 or b2-b3, or at times attempt to put pressure on the d5-pawn. }
8. Be2
{ The logical follow-up after the last move, and the one that is by far the most popular as well. }
8... Bb4
{ The most active square for our bishop, so we should certainly position it right here.   9.Qa4+  is no worry to us as  9...Nc6  easily deals with that. }
9. O-O Nbd7
{ An uncommon move in the Tarrasch defence, and less popular than  9...O-O  . Yet, I have chosen to recommend this move in favour of the alternative. Although both moves are highly likely to transpose into one another, I found that  10.e4  is not particularly easy to meet if we start by castling.  As it transpires, we will be better prepared to meet the push of White's e-pawn after 9...Nbd7, while not giving up much else. The other reason for developing the knight to d7 instead of the traditional c6, is the overprotection of its colleague on f6, making it easier for our queen to remove itself from the pin. }
10. Ne5
{ If White wants to fight for the advantage, this active move has to be played. At times f2-f4 may be an idea, and it also frees f3 for the bishop. }
10... O-O 11. Nxd7
{ Seemingly the most tempting choice, ruining our pawn structure on the Kingside for good. }
11... Qxd7
{ The only right recapture, as  11...Bxd7  would run into  12.Nxd5!  . } 12.
Bxf6 gxf6
{ Thus, our pawn structure on the Kingside is not the prettiest in the history of the game of chess. But by now this should be a familiar sight and we should be aware of the advantages our position has as well.  The bishop pair in combination with our majority over on the Queenside will generate good counterplay. Moreover, our doubled pawns are no easy target whatsoever, and we can easily make them a strength playing ...f5 and stopping e3-e4 forever. }
13. Bf3 Kh8
{ There were a wealth of different options at our disposal, but I quite like this move. Tucking away our king is always going to be beneficial, and who knows, in the distant future we might use the g-file for an attack. }
14. a3 Bxc3
{ It is good to be aware that if provoked by a2-a3 this often is a good exchange for us. Even though we lose the bishop pair, there is no more pressure on d5, and we get to improve our light-squared bishop. }
15. bxc3 Bf5
{ Our bishop stands excellently here and by now, we are ready to advance on the Queenside. If needed, we can stop e3-e4 by ...Rfe8. }
