[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 5th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 exd5 5.e4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With  3.Nc3  , White could intend to play  3...c5  4.cxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.dxc5  . However, reaching the fianchetto main lines @@StartBracket@@with Nc3@@EndBracket@@ is still the most likely scenario. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. e4
{ The pet line of Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has employed it frequently in faster time control games. By opening the center, White hopes to gain a quick initiative.   5.e3  Nf6  transposes to the 4th Move Sidelines. }
5... dxe4 6. Bc4
{ A tricky move, but one that does burn all the bridges as it offers us a second pawn to take and another juicy central pawn at that. }
6... cxd4
{ Challenge accepted. This is the right way to capture on d4, as it attacks the knight on c3 as well.   Instead,  6...Qxd4  7.Qb3  would be no good for us. }
7. Qb3
{ Continuing in the attacking spirit, but beware, this is no more than a bluff. Black is already objectively winning, and it is only move 7. }
7... Nf6
{ As it turns out the threat on f7 is not a deadly one and we can simply bring out the knight.   It is important not to go for  7...dxc3  , as after  8.Bxf7  Ke7  9.Bxg8  , White is winning. }
8. Bxf7+ Ke7 { One of those rare cases where the Bongcloud is good! 😀 } 9. Nf3
{ Another flashy move that could be tried. Mainly aiming to confuse us as to which of the knights to capture. }
9... dxc3
{ This is the right capture, as the e4-pawn is important to provide some shield for our king. }
10. Be3 { Threatening Bc5+, but this can be easily parried. } 10... Na6 11. O-O
Qd6
{ A final accurate move after which the white attack vanishes. Since we are already ahead by one piece, we should not fall into the temptation of capturing a second one on f3. Rather, preparing to exchange pieces by either ...Qb4, ...Nc5 or ...Be6 diffuses the attack. }
