1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With  3.Nc3  , White could intend to play  3...c5  4.cxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.dxc5  . However, reaching the fianchetto main lines @@StartBracket@@with Nc3@@EndBracket@@ is still the most likely scenario. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. e4
{ The pet line of Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, who has employed it frequently in faster time control games. By opening the center, White hopes to gain a quick initiative.   5.e3  Nf6  transposes to the 4th Move Sidelines. }
5... dxe4 6. d5
{ The most popular move, but once again nothing disturbs our plans of normal development. }
6... Nf6 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Bb5+
{ Most players have gotten somewhat scared by this check and opted for  8...Kf8  . There is no reason not to simply block the check, however. }
8... Bd7 9. d6
{ This may look like a small worry at first, but a couple of strong moves and it becomes clear that Black is the one who is doing well. }
9... Bxb5 10. Nxb5 Qa5+ { A vital check, forcing the knight backwards. } 11.
Nc3 h6 { A cute in-between move, forcing the bishop to fall back as well. } 12.
Bf4 { 12.dxe7  hxg5  would only leave the pawn on e7 up for grabs. } 12... Bd8
13. Ne2 O-O
{ Our king has been safely castled, and although the white passer on d6 looks somewhat annoying we should not forget we have an extra pawn, and we have some easy developing moves ahead of us. }
