[Round "?"]
[White "8) 5th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With  3.Nc3  , White could intend to play  3...c5  4.cxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.dxc5  . However, reaching the fianchetto main lines @@StartBracket@@with Nc3@@EndBracket@@ is still the most likely scenario. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4
{ This move was featured in the very first game Von Bardeleben-Tarrasch, 1888@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. It does not put all that much pressure on the center and therefore gives us a reasonably smooth game.   As kids, we learned that it's generally better to develop knights before bishops and that holds very much true here, as  5.Nf3  is by far the most testing move.   5.e3  Nf6  transposes to the 4th Move Sidelines. }
5... Nc6 6. Nf3 Nf6
{ Simple play works best. Now, White has a choice to make on how to bring out their Kingside pieces. }
7. g3
{ This just does not combine well with the early Bf4 move played by White. It stands much better on g5 instead, which would be the very main line of the opening. }
7... Bg4
{ After 7.e3, we develop our bishop to b4, here we bring the other bishop all the way out to g4. The threat is rather obvious: we want to take on f3, after which the d4-pawn is loose. However, this is rather awkward for White to meet. }
8. Be3
{ Perhaps the only way of really protecting the pawn but having to move the bishop again is more an admission of defeat than anything else. Black has an easy game in several ways. I like keeping White busy by continuing the initiative. }
8... Qb6
{ The more restrained  8...Be7  is certainly possible as well, as is  8...c4  . }
9. Na4 Qa6 10. dxc5 d4 11. Nxd4 Rd8
{ This position demonstrates the dynamic potential of the Tarrasch Defence. The pin is very nasty, and despite being up two pawns, White is in a world of trouble. }
*

