[Black "3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 exd5 5.dxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With  3.Nc3  , White could intend to play  3...c5  4.cxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.dxc5  . However, reaching the fianchetto main lines @@StartBracket@@with Nc3@@EndBracket@@ is still the most likely scenario. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. dxc5
{ A move that may well hold the title of the longest history of high-level games seen in the Tarrasch Defence. First seen in Burns-Tarrasch in 1889, and it was recently featured in the game Carlsen-Artemiev, 2021.  The move certainly is logical, as not only White captures a pawn, but also do they unleash and attack the d5-pawn. Yet, all of this should not worry us in the slightest as I believe Black is the only one having the fun here!   5.e3  Nf6  transposes to the 4th Move Sidelines. }
5... d4 { The only way is forwards! } 6. Ne4
{ This does seem more attractive than the alternative of going to the rim of the board. However, here it becomes an easy target for attack. }
6... Nf6 { Immediately challenging the knight is the way to go. } 7. Bg5 Bf5
{ The more pressure the better. } 8. Nxf6+
{ In case of  8.Ng3  we would simply retreat with  8...Bg6  after which the pawn on c5 should be up for grabs. }
8... gxf6 9. e4
{ The only way for White to maintain the balance is to go for a direct counterattack. All the bishop's retreats would give us a great game after capturing on c5. }
9... Bxe4
{ We will be going down a short sequence of moves which are more or less forced. }
10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. Qe2 fxg5 12. Qxe4+ Qe7 13. Qxe7+ Bxe7
{ Finally, we have reached an endgame that could be estimated as approximately equal. We should probably castle Queenside, and not forget that White still has not got rid of the weak c5-pawn. }
*

