[Black "3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 exd5 5.dxc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With  3.Nc3  , White could intend to play  3...c5  4.cxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.dxc5  . However, reaching the fianchetto main lines @@StartBracket@@with Nc3@@EndBracket@@ is still the most likely scenario. }
3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. dxc5
{ A move that may well hold the title of the longest history of high-level games seen in the Tarrasch Defence. First seen in Burns-Tarrasch in 1889, and it was recently featured in the game Carlsen-Artemiev, 2021.  The move certainly is logical, as not only White captures a pawn, but also do they unleash and attack the d5-pawn. Yet, all of this should not worry us in the slightest as I believe Black is the only one having the fun here!   5.e3  Nf6  transposes to the 4th Move Sidelines. }
5... d4 { The only way is forwards! } 6. Na4
{ Voluntarily placing the knight on the rim may seem odd, but at least from here, the knight is less prone to attacks than it would be in the center of the board. }
6... b5
{ A superb move. Not at all intending on gaining back the lost pawn but continuing the initiative. }
7. cxb6 axb6
{ The opening of the a-file has brought severe danger upon the knight. } 8. e4
{ The only way to keep the balance. } 8... Bd7
{ Developing with tempo, and thus keeping White busy.   We should keep on pressuring the knight. Instead,  8...Bb4+?!  wins material but loses the initiative as after  9.Bd2  Bxd2+  10.Qxd2  Rxa4  11.Bb5+  Bd7  12.Bxa4  Bxa4  13.Nf3  White is having all the fun. }
9. b3 b5 { Still keeping White busy. } 10. Nb2 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Bc3
{ From here the bishop will be like a thorn in the white position. If necessary, it can always be defended once more after an eventual ...b4. Thus, giving Black more than sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
*

