7. cxb6 axb6
{ The opening of the a-file has brought severe danger upon the knight. } 8. b3
{ This move was the choice of Carlsen and it was also seen in almost all the games. White desperately tries to free up an escape square for the lost knight. It does look rather artificial, however, and computers confirm the advantage is already well with Black. }
8... b5 9. Nb2 Bb4+ 10. Bd2
{ So far, we are still following the Carlsen-Artemiev game, but here I would like to suggest an improvement. }
10... Bc3
{ In that game  10...Bxd2  was played, but this seems much stronger. } 11. Qc2
Nf6
{ Not backing down in the slightest! Giving up one a second pawn but increasing our advantage in development to the maximum. }
12. Bxc3 dxc3 13. Qxc3 O-O
{ We can safely end the analysis here by saying that White is in huge danger, still having to bring out all their Kingside pieces and castle!  As for our ideas, there are many - we can continue our threats with ...Nd5 next, when White should start worrying about ...Qa5+. Besides, we have several ways of easily developing our pieces to great squares. }
