[Black "3.Nf3 c5 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5
{ 4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.cxd5  exd5  5.dxc5  Bxc5  . }
4... exd5 5. Be3
{ A move with one clear-cut idea - to win a pawn with dxc5, but that's about the only useful thing it does.   5.e3  Nf6  transposes to 4th Move Sidelines. }
5... c4
{ Now the bishop looks quite dumb on d4, and eventually, it will be forced to move again. }
6. g3 Nc6 7. Bg2 Bd6
{ One of the rare cases where I suggest a setup where both knights do not develop to c6 and respectively f6. With the bishop on e3, suddenly ...Nge7-f5 becomes an interesting idea. }
8. O-O Nge7 { We should be pleased with the outcome of the opening. } *

