1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5
{ 4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.cxd5  exd5  5.dxc5  Bxc5  . }
4... exd5 5. dxc5
{ This allows us to develop our bishop to c5 in one go, which should be quite a good achievement for us. Back in the old days, people often used to play ...Be7-xc5 in many lines.   5.e3  Nf6  transposes to 4th Move Sidelines. }
5... Bxc5 6. e3 { A lazy approach that does not put any pressure on us. } 6...
Nf6 7. Be2 Nc6
{ It is also perfectly viable to castle instead. It is merely a transposition of moves. }
8. O-O O-O
{ Black has managed to complete all the standard developing moves without any issues. Next, up there is either the plan to play for ...d5-d4 to get rid of our isolated pawn, or we could keep the game sharp by simply continuing to bring out our pieces. }
