1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5
{ 4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/4p3/2pp4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.cxd5  exd5  5.dxc5  Bxc5  . }
4... exd5 5. dxc5
{ This allows us to develop our bishop to c5 in one go, which should be quite a good achievement for us. Back in the old days, people often used to play ...Be7-xc5 in many lines.   5.e3  Nf6  transposes to 4th Move Sidelines. }
5... Bxc5 6. Qc2
{ This has virtually never been seen, but it is the computer's top choice and therefore must be considered. }
6... Qb6
{ Not only defending the bishop but also attacking f2.   It is useful to realize that  6...Bb6  would be a good move if not for  7.Bg5  , which is uncomfortable to meet. }
7. e3 Nf6 8. Be2 Nc6 9. O-O
{ We should not wait and immediately strike in the center! } 9... d4
{ Generally speaking, when the player with the isolated pawn manages to play this move without consequences, they have equalized comfortably. }
10. exd4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxd4
{ With a completely symmetrical pawn structure the position is close to equal. }
12. Nd2
{ The last hope of gaining an advantage for White is to quickly challenge our central bishop. }
12... O-O 13. Nf3 Bg4
{ It is more important to complete development in this case rather than preserve the bishop on d4. }
14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15. Bxg4 Qxg4
{ A couple more exchanges later, we can safely say the position is very drawish. }
