4... exd5 5. dxc5
{ This allows us to develop our bishop to c5 in one go, which should be quite a good achievement for us. Back in the old days, people often used to play ...Be7-xc5 in many lines.   5.e3  Nf6  transposes to 4th Move Sidelines. }
5... Bxc5 6. Qc2
{ This has virtually never been seen, but it is the computer's top choice and therefore must be considered. }
6... Qb6
{ Not only defending the bishop but also attacking f2.   It is useful to realize that  6...Bb6  would be a good move if not for  7.Bg5  , which is uncomfortable to meet. }
7. e3 Nf6 8. Be2 Nc6 9. a3
{ A clever way for White to continue the game. By preparing b2-b4, it is not immediately possible for us to break free through ...d5-d4. }
9... Bd6
{ A smart pre-emptive move in reply. By withdrawing the bishop, we ensure that we can always meet b2-b4 with ...a7-a5. It is also useful to realize that generally, it would be preferable to play ...Bb6, since from there it supports the ...d5-d4 push. In this case, however, our queen occupies that very square. }
10. b4 a5 { Forcing White to compromise their pawn structure in some way. } 11.
b5
{ The most ambitious move.   After  11.bxa5  Nxa5  we have lots of activity on the Queenside. }
11... Ne5 12. Nbd2 Be6
{ Slightly more accurate than castling immediately as now we are ready to bother White utilizing ...Rc8. }
13. Bb2 Rc8 14. Qa4 Ned7
{ In general, when playing with the isolani, we should try to keep minor pieces on the board to compensate for our small structural deficit by piece activity. This last move does just that and intends to bring the knight over to c5. The position is dynamically balanced. }
