1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With  3.Nc3  , White could intend to play  3...c5  4.cxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.dxc5  . However, reaching the fianchetto main lines @@StartBracket@@with Nc3@@EndBracket@@ is still the most likely scenario. }
3... c5
{ Once in a while, you might face an adventurous opponent or simply someone that is scared to enter the frightening Tarrasch Defense main lines and then it is good to be prepared for such scenarios by checking out the sidelines. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing the knight before securing the center is a very provocative approach. We'll be able to make the white knights dance all over the board. }
4... cxd4
{ Since this is a Tarrasch course, we could play  4...Nf6  with a clear conscience, since White has no better than to transpose to the Tarrasch main lines.  However, we shouldn't let White off the hook so easily and try to punish them whenever possible. }
5. Nxd4
{ In case of  5.Qxd4  Nc6  followed by ...d4, White is already close to losing, just 5 moves in. }
5... e5 { Time to make the knights dance. } 6. Nf3
{ Retreating the knight is the most popular move, yet also a severe mistake since it allows us to grab even more space with tempo. }
6... d4 { Now the second knight has to move. } 7. Nd5 Ne7
{ This or  7...Nf6  are more or less interchangeable.   Just make sure not to play the most popular move  7...Nc6  since after  8.e4  White is surprisingly back in business. }
8. e4 { 8.Nxe5  Nxd5  9.cxd5  Qxd5  would be very pleasant for Black as well. }
8... dxe3
{ 8...Nxd5  is also good, but I feel we should take the opportunity to take en passant. }
9. Bxe3 Nxd5 10. Qxd5
{ Trying to keep the queens with  10.cxd5  leads to an immediate disaster after  10...Bb4+  11.Bd2  Qxd5!  since  12.Bxb4  Qe4+  wins the piece back while Black remains a pawn up. }
10... Bb4+ { Developing with tempo. } 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 f6
{ After some exchanges we have arrived at an endgame which can only be considered better for Black due to our strong pawn chain, which is exercising great central influence. We have an easy plan for developing our pieces with ...Be6, ...Nc6 and ...Ke7. Meanwhile, the white Queenside play can easily be brought to halt with ...a7-a5. }
