9. e4
{ This move has been played in a correspondence game. While the position looks absolutely crazy, the game soon ended in a forced repetition of moves. }
9... Bc5 { Developing the other bishop is a good start. } 10. Be3
{ White needs to use some tactics in order to resolve the awkward situation on the Queenside. }
10... Bxe3
{ We have little choice either of going down the rather forced line. } 11. Nd6+
{ That's the point - finally White is able to free the dreaded knight from the pin. }
11... Kf8
{ Our king has to sidestep.   Note that  11...Ke7  12.Qb4  would be disastrous for us, as our king has no way to hide from the discoveries. }
12. Qa3
{ Setting up a bunch of discoveries.   12.Qb4  with the same idea would be a huge error since it allows  12...Qb6  , winning the game on the spot. }
12... Bh6
{ Funnily enough, White has no decisive discoveries and is forced to go for a repetition of moves. Note that this is the only right square for our bishop since we need to protect the g7-pawn after Nf5+. }
13. Nf5+ Ke8
{ If our bishop wasn't on h6, Nxg7 would now be mate. Fortunately, the bishop is taking care of this square, so White has to settle for a draw. }
14. Nd6+ Kf8 { Shake hands! } *

