1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With  3.Nc3  , White could intend to play  3...c5  4.cxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.dxc5  . However, reaching the fianchetto main lines @@StartBracket@@with Nc3@@EndBracket@@ is still the most likely scenario. }
3... c5
{ Once in a while, you might face an adventurous opponent or simply someone that is scared to enter the frightening Tarrasch Defense main lines and then it is good to be prepared for such scenarios by checking out the sidelines. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing the knight before securing the center is a very provocative approach. We'll be able to make the white knights dance all over the board. }
4... cxd4
{ Since this is a Tarrasch course, we could play  4...Nf6  with a clear conscience, since White has no better than to transpose to the Tarrasch main lines.  However, we shouldn't let White off the hook so easily and try to punish them whenever possible. }
5. Nxd4
{ In case of  5.Qxd4  Nc6  followed by ...d4, White is already close to losing, just 5 moves in. }
5... e5 { Time to make the knights dance. } 6. Ndb5
{ White's best bet is to bite the bullet. } 6... a6
{ This already looks crushing, since  7.Na3  cannot be considered an option. However, White has a resource up their sleeve.   Note that  6...d4  would be a serious mistake, as the knight tango suddenly wreaks havoc after  7.Nd5  , threatening Nc7+. }
7. Qa4
{ A typical idea, indirectly defending the knight, since our rook on a8 is unprotected. }
7... Bd7
{ Stopping any discoveries and making sure the knight isn't going anywhere anytime soon. }
8. cxd5 Nf6
{ There is no good way of winning the knight just yet, so we should just develop some pieces for the moment. }
9. d6 { The most popular move, threatening Nc7+, but it is our turn first. }
9... axb5
{ A powerful exchange sacrifice. White's queen is forced to go to the corner of the board, which gives us time to develop a strong initiative. }
10. Qxa8 b4 { Asking the white knight where it would like to go. } 11. Nd1
{ This looks like the most humane choice to me.   In fact,  11.Nb1  is objectively the best move but after  11...Bxd6  it is clear that we are the ones having all the fun, as White will face the enormous task of developing their pieces and bringing the king to safety.   11.Na4  is not great either, for similar reasons after  11...Bxd6  . }
11... Bxd6 12. Qxb7 { White's greediness knows no bounds. } 12... Bc6 13. Qa7
Ne4
{ The knight jumps with great strength, as already ...Bc5 is being threatened, trapping White's queen. }
14. Be3
{ Stopping ...Bc5, or doesn't it?   According to the engines, returning back home with the queen with  14.Qe3  is the best choice. Still, with such a lack of development Black is probably objectively winning. A crazy computer line goes  14...O-O  15.g4  - White has to resort to some very strange moves in order to attempt to bring some pieces out.  15...Nc5  unleashes a discovery attack on the h1-rook. After  16.Rg1  Black has several good moves, but I like  16...e4  best. This pawn will serve as a thorn in White's position. Although being down in material there is no rush as the White king will be permanently weak. Improving our pieces through ...Qc7 and ...Rd8 is a decent idea when sooner or later tactical motives should pop up. }
14... Bc5
{ It doesn't since  15.Bxc5  runs into  15...Qd2#  ! Therefore, White has to give up the queen, and soon the game as well. }
