1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With  3.Nc3  , White could intend to play  3...c5  4.cxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.dxc5  . However, reaching the fianchetto main lines @@StartBracket@@with Nc3@@EndBracket@@ is still the most likely scenario. }
3... c5
{ Once in a while, you might face an adventurous opponent or simply someone that is scared to enter the frightening Tarrasch Defense main lines and then it is good to be prepared for such scenarios by checking out the sidelines. }
4. Be3
{ A terrible move, but it was once played in the famous game Romanishin-Lputian, Kyiv 1984. Its refutation is very cunning. }
4... e5
{ A fascinating move. By moving the e-pawn a second time, Black is creating mayhem in the white camp. It appears that we are breaking all the golden rules of chess: we are foregoing development and moving a pawn twice. Stunningly, Black is on the verge of winning! }
5. Nxd5
{ Any alternative capture allows Black to fork the white pieces by capturing on d4 or pushing ...d5-d4. }
5... cxd4 6. Bd2 Nf6 7. Bg5
{ This was played in the aforementioned game by Romanishin. Black's advanced center already offered us a promising position, but now things go from bad to worse. What is the refutation?   Other moves don't help White either. The engine recommends sacrificing a pawn with  7.Nf3  , but Black is clearly better after simply capturing the pawn with  7...Nxd5  8.cxd5  Qxd5  . }
7... Nxd5 { Another excellent move. We are completely disregarding the pin. }
8. Bxd8 Bb4+
{ The point. Black wins back the material and will obtain an overwhelming positional advantage in the endgame. }
