1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With  3.Nc3  , White could intend to play  3...c5  4.cxd5  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...c5  4.dxc5  . However, reaching the fianchetto main lines @@StartBracket@@with Nc3@@EndBracket@@ is still the most likely scenario. }
3... c5
{ Once in a while, you might face an adventurous opponent or simply someone that is scared to enter the frightening Tarrasch Defense main lines and then it is good to be prepared for such scenarios by checking out the sidelines. }
4. dxc5
{ A greedy move. White wins a pawn but they need to make some awkward moves in order to hold on to it. }
4... d4 5. Na4
{ Chess is sometimes a weird game since you wouldn't immediately expect that placing the knight on the rim would be White's best option. Actually, there is a point here since the knight can at least not be directly chased away from a4. }
5... Bd7 { Attacking the knight and additionally threatening ...Qa5+. } 6. b4
Bxa4 { Forcing White's queen to the edge of the board. } 7. Qxa4+ Nd7
{ Although White is still up a pawn, we'll soon play ...a5, breaking up White's pawn structure and only leaving the opponent with weak pawns. }
8. Nf3
{ Other moves don't stop our evil plans. For example, after  8.e3  dxe3  9.Bxe3  a5  we are allowed to execute our idea anyways. }
8... a5
{ No need to get distracted by the d4-pawn. It is much more important to continue the aforementioned plan of breaking up White's structure. }
9. Nxd4 axb4 10. Qxb4
{ If White were to play  10.Qc2  instead,  10...Bxc5  11.e3  Ngf6  followed by castling is simple and good. }
10... Bxc5 11. Qb2
{ Hanging on to the position for dear life.   Instead,  11.Qd2  Qb6  would already win us the game. }
11... Ngf6
{ While White has managed to remain up a pawn, it is hard to say anything positive about their position. On the other hand, we will complete development after ...O-O, and start pressuring the weak isolated a2- and c4-pawns. Another strategic idea available to us is ...Ba3, eliminating White's bishop pair. }
