1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. g3
{ A logical choice for those who prefer to play the Catalan. However, things are vastly different from the regular Catalan, since there is already a lot of tension in the center.   4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to the main line of the 5th Move Sidelines chapter. }
4... cxd4
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move.   Another interesting and more solid option is  4...dxc4  5.Bg2  Nc6  , since White has nothing better than  6.Qa4  which leads to an equal position after  6...cxd4  7.Nxd4  Qxd4  8.Bxc6  Bd7  9.Be3!?  Bxc6  10.Qxc6  Qd7  11.Qxc4  .  After the text, there are no easy simplifications available to White. }
5. cxd5 Qa5+
{ A clever intermediate check before recapturing on d5, making sure that White has to block the d-file. }
6. Nbd2 Qxd5 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. O-O e5
{ Securing the extra pawn and strengthening the center. Although it looks a bit scary to leave the queen on d5, White has no actual way of taking advantage. }
9. Qa4
{ White must quickly use the lead in development before we manage to consolidate the extra material. }
9... Bd7 10. Ng5 Nd8
{ A funny counterattack on the white queen. The knight looks weird on d8, but it fulfils the important job of protecting both f7 and b7. }
11. Qc2 { White must retain the queens on the board. } 11... Qb5
{ Our queen sidesteps as well while attacking the e2-pawn. However, we probably shouldn't get too distracted by that pawn and aim to finish development instead. Driving back the enemy forces with moves such as ...f6 or ...Rc8 are good ideas to keep in mind. }
12. Nc4
{ Jumping forward with the knight is probably the most testing of ideas. }
12... Rc8
{ Including this move is certainly useful as White has to spend a tempo protecting the knight. }
13. b3 Qa6
{ Creating a sneaky threat of ...b5. The variations get increasingly complex now, with the computer showing the usual 0.00s everywhere. }
14. Qe4
{ Escaping from the threat of ...b5, as well as attacking e5, seems like by far the most logical attempt by White. }
14... f6 { Securing the pawn chain as well as attacking the g5-knight. } 15.
Nxh7
{ White has to bite the bullet and capture this pawn, creating an idea of Qg6+ in the process. Do notice, however, that this knight has no way back anymore and can fall prey to our forces at any time. }
15... Bc5 16. Qg6+
{ This certainly looks menacing, but we are just in time to cover everything. }
16... Nf7
{ Although the position remains incredibly complex, Black is certainly no worse.  It is important to notice that  16.Bd5  is conveniently met by  16...Be6  , while @@StartFEN@@2r1k1nr/pp1b1npN/q4pQ1/2b1p3/2Np4/1P4P1/P3PPBP/R1B2RK1 w k - 3 17@@EndFEN@@  16.Qxg7  actually loses for White after  16...Bf5!  .  Otherwise, moves such as ...Ne7 or ...Qe6, bringing the queen closer to the king, should be on our radar. }
