1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. g3
{ A logical choice for those who prefer to play the Catalan. However, things are vastly different from the regular Catalan, since there is already a lot of tension in the center.   4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to the main line of the 5th Move Sidelines chapter. }
4... cxd4
{ I believe that this is the most challenging move.   Another interesting and more solid option is  4...dxc4  5.Bg2  Nc6  , since White has nothing better than  6.Qa4  which leads to an equal position after  6...cxd4  7.Nxd4  Qxd4  8.Bxc6  Bd7  9.Be3!?  Bxc6  10.Qxc6  Qd7  11.Qxc4  .  After the text, there are no easy simplifications available to White. }
5. Nxd4
{ A dubious recapture, as it allows us to gain some tempi to advance our center. }
5... e5 6. Nf3 d4 7. Bg2 Nc6
{ Our center has made big strides forward, but we aren't finished yet. } 8. O-O
e4 { Continuing to push! } 9. Nfd2 f5
{ Our center surely looks intimidating and severely restricts White's forces.   A possible continuation is  10.Nb3  . The knight moves for the 3rd time in just 10 moves, but it was really doing nothing on d2.  10...Be6!  is the most accurate way of playing, immediately attacking the c-pawn. In case of  11.Na3  we can either play the solid  11...Bxa3  12.bxa3  Bxc4  , or the ambitious  @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/pp4pp/2n1b3/5p2/2Ppp3/NN4P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qd7  12.Nb5  Rd8  , overprotecting the d4-pawn, with an interesting game ahead. }
