[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. e3
{ Although the text move has been around for ages, it's generally considered an innocuous move. However, in the day and age where there are so many lines of computer analysis and the workload is just enormous, people have started to aim for positions where the advantage will be minimal, but the game will remain complex.   White avoids the heavy theory that arises after  4.cxd5  , but instead aims for a calmer setup, while still retaining all the pieces on the board.   4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to the main line of the 5th Move Sidelines chapter. }
4... Nf6
{ I believe there is not much difference between this and  4...Nc6  , but somehow bringing out the g8-knight first feels more natural to me. }
5. cxd5
{ Releasing the tension in the center early on contains a point that becomes apparent soon. }
5... exd5 { Capturing back with the pawn should be a no-brainer. } 6. Bb5+
{ Patzer sees a check, gives a check is the favourite joke of my first coach. However, this seemingly harmless check contains some serious venom and we should tread carefully.   6.Nc3  Nc6  transposes. }
6... Nbd7
{ As it turns out, this unorthodox way of blocking the check is the only correct move. In fact, I faced this line versus Gledura in 2021, and fortunately, I knew this is the correct reply.   If we would have responded with the natural  6...Nc6  , we would have some problems finishing our development after  7.O-O  . For example,  7...Bd6  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.Qc2  already brings us into a tough spot.   We could also play  6...Bd7  , but since we might soon have to play with an isolani, it is better to keep pieces on the board. }
7. dxc5
{ This capture is called for since allowing us to play ...c5-c4 would be unwise. }
7... a6
{ An accurate intermezzo that is important to remember.   In case of  7...Bxc5  , our knight on d7 would not make much sense.  Instead, we aim to recapture on c5 with the knight. }
8. Bxd7+ { A solid decision, but we'll gladly play with the pair of bishops. }
8... Bxd7 9. Nc3
{ It would be unwise to try and hang on to the pawn with  9.b4  , since after  9...a5  the pawn chain is about to fall apart. }
9... Bxc5
{ There's no need to spend any time protecting the pawn on d5, as capturing it would only open diagonals for our bishops. }
10. O-O { 10.Nxd5  would be well met by  10...Bc6  . } 10... O-O
{ The same reasoning of the previous move still applies. We don't have to worry about our pawn on d5 yet. }
11. b3
{ In this case,  11.Nxd5  Bb5  would be strong. Instead, White is looking to develop the bishop on the long diagonal. }
11... Ne4
{ One of several ways of playing, for example, Lc0's preference is  11...Qe7  , followed by bringing the rooks to the center.  The text is more concrete, and a typical Stockfish suggestion: sacrificing a pawn to fight for an initiative. }
12. Qxd5
{ If White has any ambitions, they should take on the challenge.   After the soft  12.Bb2  Nxc3  13.Bxc3  Bg4  there is little going on.   Also,  12.Nxd5  would not be impressive as  12...Bb5  gives us a great game. }
12... Nxc3 13. Qxc5 Rc8
{ In return for the sacrificed pawn, we'll be able to gain some tempi hitting the enemy pieces. Furthermore, our knight is extremely strong on c3. }
14. Qh5
{ The queen seeks safety far away, where it can not easily come under attack. }
14... Bb5 { Another strong tempo move. } 15. Re1 Ne2+
{ One does rarely a knight this deep in the enemy territory so early on in the game. }
16. Kh1 Qf6 { Now, the rook on a1 is taken under fire. } 17. Ba3
{ In case of  17.Bd2  we can infiltrate the second rank with  17...Rc2  , with good pressure.   White may be tempted by  17.Qe5  , offering the exchange of queens. It is important not to shy away from the exchange, as our active piece play will continue in the endgame after  17...Qxe5  18.Nxe5  f6  19.Nf3  Rc2  . }
17... Rfe8
{ We can safely end our analysis here. If White even manages to get here, they have done well, but our initiative is just starting. Our knight gives a funny impression, but it does a great job restricting the opponent's rooks. Next, we can bring our rook to the second rank, where it will be a menace to White. }
