1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. e3
{ Although the text move has been around for ages, it's generally considered an innocuous move. However, in the day and age where there are so many lines of computer analysis and the workload is just enormous, people have started to aim for positions where the advantage will be minimal, but the game will remain complex.   White avoids the heavy theory that arises after  4.cxd5  , but instead aims for a calmer setup, while still retaining all the pieces on the board.   4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to the main line of the 5th Move Sidelines chapter. }
4... Nf6
{ I believe there is not much difference between this and  4...Nc6  , but somehow bringing out the g8-knight first feels more natural to me. }
5. a3
{ This is probably White's most solid try in the entire course. I tried looking for ways to spice it up but to no avail. }
5... dxc4
{ This is one of the rare occasions when our usual developing move  5...Nc6  would be dubious. After  6.dxc5  Bxc5  7.b4  followed by 8.Bb2 is strong.   It appears that our best option available is to transpose to a harmless subvariation of the Queen’s Gambit Accepted.  If you really want to keep pieces on the board,  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Be7  might be your best bet. White might be a tiny bit better but a complicated game lies ahead, with enough room to outplay your opponent. }
6. Bxc4 a6
{ Copying White's play is the best course of action. The text prepares ...b7-b5. }
7. O-O
{ If White is completely desperate to dry the game up,  7.dxc5  might occur, resulting in an equal endgame after  7...Qxd1  8.Kxd1  Bxc5  . }
7... b5
{ Kicking the white bishop away. Next, we should play ...Bb7 and develop our Kingside. The b8-knight we should develop to d7 later on, so it doesn't obstruct the b7-bishop.  The position is very symmetrical. Since our development is so smooth we should enter the future with confidence.  We have reached a direct transposition to a variation of the QGA @@StartBracket@@Queen's Gambit Accepted@@EndBracket@@, but don't worry - this is a rather harmless sideline. In order to gain some familiarity with these types of positions, it is useful to study some practical games. For example, Halkias-Vallejo Pons, 2007 is a nice game to check out, especially the ...Qd8-b8 manoeuvre being one to remember. }
