{ A tricky line, as many players go slightly wrong here with Black. } 7... cxd4
{ The most accurate way.   Most people have played  7...Bd6  instead, but after  8.dxc5  we must move our bishop again.   I recently played  7...a6  in an online rapid game vs Ding Liren, but after  8.Bxc6+  I soon found myself in  trouble. }
8. exd4
{ By appearances this recapture looks rather harmless. However, don't be deceived as White's small lead in development requires us to react accurately in order not to land in a difficult situation. }
8... Bd6 9. Bg5
{ The ambitious approach, setting up a scary-looking pin, but there is no need for panic. }
9... O-O 10. O-O
{ White needs to castle before even thinking about going pawn hunting. } 10...
Bg4
{ We shouldn't fear any ghosts and just continue to activate our pieces to the most active squares. }
11. Bxf6
{ A injudicious decision, as grabbing the pawn only spells danger upon White's position. }
11... Qxf6 12. Nxd5 Qh6
{ Already things are looking scary for White, with all kinds of threats in the position. }
13. h3 Bxh3 { White's actions need to be punished. } 14. gxh3
{ The principled reply, but perhaps White's last chance would be to bail out with  14.Ne3  , although Black is clearly very comfortable after  14...Bd7  with the pair of bishops and safer king. }
14... Qg6+
{ A highly clever idea. The point will become clear on the next move. } 15. Kh1
Qf5
{ The point, as we not only threaten to take the knight but also to take on h3 with check. }
16. Nc3
{ White's greed knows no bounds.   The best chance might be  16.Kg2  , but after  16...Qxd5  Black is much better. }
16... Qxh3+ 17. Kg1 Rae8
{ White is defenceless against the rook joining the attack with decisive consequences. }
