1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. e3
{ Although the text move has been around for ages, it's generally considered an innocuous move. However, in the day and age where there are so many lines of computer analysis and the workload is just enormous, people have started to aim for positions where the advantage will be minimal, but the game will remain complex.   White avoids the heavy theory that arises after  4.cxd5  , but instead aims for a calmer setup, while still retaining all the pieces on the board.   4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to the main line of the 5th Move Sidelines chapter. }
4... Nf6
{ I believe there is not much difference between this and  4...Nc6  , but somehow bringing out the g8-knight first feels more natural to me. }
5. Nc3
{ Here we are at crossroads with Black. Personally, I have given the move  5...a6  a try when facing Fabiano Caruana with the black pieces in Wijk aan Zee 2021. This move certainly has some merits but here I have decided to recommend the main move  5...Nc6  . It also fits well with our usual Tarrasch game plan of bringing out both knights before doing anything else. }
5... Nc6
{ This position is known as the Symmetrical Tarrasch Defense. The position is indeed completely symmetrical for the moment, yet, the game can quickly turn highly complex when the central tension is released by either side. }
6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5
{ A tricky line, as many players go slightly wrong here with Black. } 7... cxd4
{ The most accurate way.   Most people have played  7...Bd6  instead, but after  8.dxc5  we must move our bishop again.   I recently played  7...a6  in an online rapid game vs Ding Liren, but after  8.Bxc6+  I soon found myself in  trouble. }
8. Nxd4 Bd7 { The knight must be defended. } 9. O-O Bd6
{ As we've seen, this is usually the best square for the bishop in these variations. }
10. Nf3
{ A typical idea, by retreating the knight, our d5-pawn is being attacked. Also, the knight on f3 does a good job protecting White's Kingside. }
10... Bg4
{ Now that our c6-knight no longer needs extra defending we can place our bishop on a more active square. At the same time indirectly defending against the threat to our pawn, since  11.Nxd5  Nxd5  12.Qxd5  Bxh2+  wins the queen. }
11. h3 Bh5 12. Be2
{ The bishop retreats as the pin on White's knight was rather annoying. } 12...
O-O { At last we can castle. } 13. b3
{ Intending to fianchetto the bishop. Now, we have reached a very typical position, which can arise from many openings. For example, the Karpov variation of the Nimzo-Indian reaches the exact same position, only with colours reversed: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Bb4  4.e3  O-O  5.Bd3  d5  6.Nf3  c5  7.O-O  cxd4  8.exd4  dxc4  9.Bxc4  Nc6  10.Bd3  Be7  11.Bg5  h6  12.Bh4  b6  .  Naturally, there are several plans available. Attacking the white monarch by setting up a battery with the queen and bishop on the b8-h2 diagonal is a key idea that we eventually want to implement. }
13... a6
{ A useful move, as the white knight can not reroute itself via b5 anymore. }
14. Bb2 Re8 15. Nh4 { A typical idea. It is very useful to know how to react. }
15... Bg6
{ The classical reply.   15...Bxe2  would be a severe mistake, as after  16.Nxe2  the bishop on b2 is strong and the h4-knight can jump to f5. In these positions, the knight on c3 is misplaced and we should keep it there. }
16. Nxg6 hxg6
{ The loss of our light-squared bishop is of no significance. Our structure has been slightly improved by the trade and most importantly, White has lost control over the d4-square.  Therefore, the standard idea of ...d5-d4 should be seriously considered over the next couple of moves. If we do manage to play ...d5-d4, we would activate our pieces to the maximum and be able to get rid of the isolated pawn. If required, this idea can easily be supported by playing ...Be5. }
