1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. e3
{ Although the text move has been around for ages, it's generally considered an innocuous move. However, in the day and age where there are so many lines of computer analysis and the workload is just enormous, people have started to aim for positions where the advantage will be minimal, but the game will remain complex.   White avoids the heavy theory that arises after  4.cxd5  , but instead aims for a calmer setup, while still retaining all the pieces on the board.   4.dxc5  Bxc5  5.cxd5  exd5  transposes to the main line of the 5th Move Sidelines chapter. }
4... Nf6
{ I believe there is not much difference between this and  4...Nc6  , but somehow bringing out the g8-knight first feels more natural to me. }
5. Nc3
{ Here we are at crossroads with Black. Personally, I have given the move  5...a6  a try when facing Fabiano Caruana with the black pieces in Wijk aan Zee 2021. This move certainly has some merits but here I have decided to recommend the main move  5...Nc6  . It also fits well with our usual Tarrasch game plan of bringing out both knights before doing anything else. }
5... Nc6
{ This position is known as the Symmetrical Tarrasch Defense. The position is indeed completely symmetrical for the moment, yet, the game can quickly turn highly complex when the central tension is released by either side. }
6. a3
{ This is White's most popular try, enabling the idea of b2-b4 after exchanging on c5. }
6... a6
{ Continuing the symmetry. With this move, we give White the option of making us play with an isolani after subsequent exchanges on both d5 and c5.  For this reason, some players have preferred going  6...dxc4  instead, steering the game towards calmer waters. Objectively, both options are roughly equal, but since this is a Tarrasch course, we should not shy away from both the isolani and complicated positions. }
7. dxc5 { The logical follow-up after White's previous move. } 7... Bxc5 8. b4
Bd6
{ I prefer this square over  8...Ba7  . The reason is that after White castles Kingside, our bishop will be in a good attacking position, putting pressure on h2, which on a good day might lead to mate! }
9. Ra2
{ A funky idea which has been tried by Fedoseev. The rook wants to switch over to d2, and only then will the bishop be developed to b2. However, this type of creative play always comes with some drawbacks. In this case, the white Kingside will remain undeveloped for the time being. }
9... O-O 10. Rd2
{ It is not often that one encounters a rook on d2 this early on in the game. }
10... Ne5
{ There are so many fascinating variations here, that you could spend an entire day analysing this position. For example, both  10...Nxb4  and  10...Qe7  are worth consideration.  Finally, I decided to recommend the text move, as I think it makes life the most complicated for White. }
11. cxd5
{ Capturing the pawn is the most ambitious choice, but also a dangerous one since White's king is still in the center. }
11... Nxf3+ 12. gxf3
{ This is by no means the obvious choice, but  12.Qxf3  Be5  would already be very strong for Black. }
12... e5
{ I find this a fascinating idea - it is just so unexpected. With the white king in the center, it would be logical to keep opening files. Instead, we close the entire d-file, making a mockery out of White's rook.  Since White's Kingside is ruined, the king will never find a safe haven. Taking these factors into consideration, I believe the position is much easier to play for Black. Our ideas consist of opening some files on the Queenside with ...a5, or simply developing more pieces with ...Bd7 and ...Rc8. }
