7. dxc5 { The logical follow-up after White's previous move. } 7... Bxc5 8. b4
Bd6
{ I prefer this square over  8...Ba7  . The reason is that after White castles Kingside, our bishop will be in a good attacking position, putting pressure on h2, which on a good day might lead to mate! }
9. Bb2
{ The move  9.cxd5  is interchangeable with 9.Bb2, as both moves lead to the same position.  9...exd5  10.Bb2  O-O  transposes to 3.Nf3 c5 4.e3 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.a3 #7. }
9... O-O 10. cxd5
{ Finally delivering us the isolani, which makes us happy too. } 10... exd5 11.
Be2 Be6 { The best square for the bishop - overprotecting d5. } 12. O-O Rc8
{ It's time to bring the rooks into the game. } 13. Rc1 Re8
{ All of our forces have been mobilized. } 14. Nd4
{ Exchanges are often strategically desirable for White. However, there are concrete factors in play as well... }
14... Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Bg4 { The start of some lovely tactics. } 16. Bxg4 Rc4
{ That's the point, the rook slides in to regain the piece. } 17. Qd2 Bxh2+
{ Black's attacking potential is being unleashed! } 18. Kxh2 Nxg4+ 19. Kg3
{ 19.Kg1  would be deadly after  19...Qh4  . } 19... Qg5
{ Dark clouds have gathered around White's monarch, and it would be lucky if it manages to survive another day with so many discovered attacks pending. }
20. f4 { The only way not to lose on the spot. } 20... Qg6
{ Keeping the discoveries alive. If White manages to defend like a computer, they will escape with a draw after  21.Nxd5  Nxe3  22.Kh2  Qh5+  23.Kg1  Qxd5  24.Qxd5  Rxc1!  25.Qd7  Rxf1  26.Kh2  Rf8  . Any misstep, however, would mean losing the game. }
