{ I believe there is not much difference between this and  4...Nc6  , but somehow bringing out the g8-knight first feels more natural to me. }
5. Nc3
{ Here we are at crossroads with Black. Personally, I have given the move  5...a6  a try when facing Fabiano Caruana with the black pieces in Wijk aan Zee 2021. This move certainly has some merits but here I have decided to recommend the main move  5...Nc6  . It also fits well with our usual Tarrasch game plan of bringing out both knights before doing anything else. }
5... Nc6
{ This position is known as the Symmetrical Tarrasch Defense. The position is indeed completely symmetrical for the moment, yet, the game can quickly turn highly complex when the central tension is released by either side. }
6. a3
{ This is White's most popular try, enabling the idea of b2-b4 after exchanging on c5. }
6... a6
{ Continuing the symmetry. With this move, we give White the option of making us play with an isolani after subsequent exchanges on both d5 and c5.  For this reason, some players have preferred going  6...dxc4  instead, steering the game towards calmer waters. Objectively, both options are roughly equal, but since this is a Tarrasch course, we should not shy away from both the isolani and complicated positions. }
7. dxc5 { The logical follow-up after White's previous move. } 7... Bxc5 8. b4
Bd6
{ I prefer this square over  8...Ba7  . The reason is that after White castles Kingside, our bishop will be in a good attacking position, putting pressure on h2, which on a good day might lead to mate! }
9. Bb2
{ The move  9.cxd5  is interchangeable with 9.Bb2, as both moves lead to the same position.  9...exd5  10.Bb2  O-O  transposes to 3.Nf3 c5 4.e3 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.a3 #7. }
9... O-O 10. cxd5
{ Finally delivering us the isolani, which makes us happy too. } 10... exd5 11.
Be2 Be6 { The best square for the bishop - overprotecting d5. } 12. O-O Rc8
{ It's time to bring the rooks into the game. } 13. Rc1 Re8
{ All of our forces have been mobilized. } 14. Na4
{ The knight on c3 is misplaced, as it obstructs the bishop and can always be hit by an eventual ...d5-d4 breakthrough. Sending the knight to greener pastures definitely makes a lot of sense. Here, White is eyeing the c5-square. }
14... Ne4
{ Not allowing White to carry out their plans so fast, since our knight keeps an eye on c5. }
15. Nd2
{ White clearly wants to play Nc5, but before that, they must exchange our central knight.   The immediate  15.Nc5  would be inadequate after  15...Bxc5  16.bxc5  Na5!  when we plan to play ...Nc4 next, with fantastic control over the light squares and a better pawn structure. The subtle threat of mate in 1 after  17.Qd4  is easily dealt with by  17...f6  . }
15... Qe7
{ If you're feeling adventurous,  15...Qh4  might be for you. I feel the text is a bit more healthy, just keeping everything compact and protected. }
16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Nc5
{ White has finally managed to complete the journey of the knight, but in doing so we have managed to get rid of the isolated pawn. }
17... Red8
{ The rook on e8 wasn't doing overly much, so placing it on the d-file seems like the sensible thing to do. }
18. Qa4 Bxc5
{ Making use of some tactics that have entered the position, as White is forced to recapture with the pawn. }
19. bxc5
{ The positionally desirable  19.Rxc5  runs into the devastating  19...Rd2!  20.Rc2  b5!  . }
19... Qg5
{ Although White has the pair of bishops, we are intending to exchange one of them on the next move. On the other hand, we have the slightly better pawn structure and the idea of ...Rd2 is still hanging in the air. The position is around even. }
