[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) London 2.Bf4"]
[Black "London 2.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ I never considered the London as a serious opening until Carlsen started having great success with it back in 2015. I even picked it up myself and scored some nice wins with it in the process. Nowadays, the London is considered a mainstream opening, and it is popular at all levels. }
2... c5
{ The most aggressive way of tackling the London system, and also nicely in the spirit of the Tarrasch Defense. This early combative approach may take London players aback, as they usually strive for a slower game. }
3. e3 Nc6 4. c3 { A typical London move, completing the central triangle. }
4... Qb6
{ Immediately hitting White where it hurts, as the b2-pawn is often a target in the London system. }
5. Qb3 c4
{ A typical advance, since the endgames arising after  6.Qxb6  are almost always good for Black. }
6. Qc2
{ White's best option is to retreat the queen, hoping that our move ... c5-c4 is a strategic concession. Indeed, if White were to get a couple of tempi, finish development and prepare e3-e4 they would be doing well.   In case of  6.Qxb6  axb6  , we are doing very well since we can easily advance on the Queenside with the typical ...b5-b4. }
6... e5
{ Not allowing White a break! After this pawn sacrifice, the game turns very complicated and tactical, which is usually precisely what London systems wish to avoid.   Note that including ...e5 before playing ...Bf5 is extremely important. In case of  6...Bf5  7.Qxf5  Qxb2  8.Qxd5  Qxa1  9.Qb5!  we would instead be losing the game as we are unable to defend the b7-pawn in a convenient way. }
7. dxe5 Bf5
{ Another typical idea. Using the fact that White can not afford to capture the bishop since  8.Qxf5  runs into  8...Qxb2  , when the rook in the corner will be lost. }
8. Qc1 g5 { Playing with great energy, not giving White a moment of rest. } 9.
Bg3 { The most popular move, but Black is simply doing very well here. } 9...
Bg7 { Intending to regain the pawn. } 10. Nf3 h5
{ With the idea of ...h4, trapping the bishop. White just isn't allowed any free time and has to keep responding to our threats. }
11. h3 h4 12. Bh2 Nh6
{ We'll play ...g4 next, continuing the initiative. In fact, according to the computer, Black is already better. }
*

