[White "11) Jobava London 2.Nc3 "]
[Black "Jobava London 2.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3
{ The Jobava London has become increasingly popular recently. Besides the creative genius of Baadur Jobava, both Simon Williams and Hans Niemann have created successful Chessable courses on the opening that have boosted the popularity even further.  Conventional wisdom holds that one should not place the knight on c3 before pushing the c-pawn to c4, but proponents of this variation have found ways to justify this way of playing. White will often aim to play for an early e2-e4, or start expanding on the Kingside through f2-f3 and g2-g4. }
2... c5
{ 2...Nf6  is the main move, but besides the Jobava London with  3.Bf4  , there also exists the possibility of playing the Veresov Attack with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bg5  .  As I have stressed, our idea is to meet virtually every line except for 2.c4 with 2...c5. This is no exception. By immediately striking in the center, we severely limit White in their options. }
3. Bf4
{ This is not as bad as it looks, and has been played by Jobava London experts Bortnyk and Niemann. }
3... Nc6 { Increasing the pressure to the d4-pawn, which must be addressed. }
4. e4
{ A funky idea, but in essence taking the game down a rather forcing line leading to an endgame. }
4... cxd4 5. exd5 dxc3 6. dxc6
{ I like how both sides are capturing symmetrically. } 6... Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 bxc6
8. Bc7
{ This is the point of White's line, threatening mate in 1! This might work in bullet, but otherwise, it is pretty easily dealt with.   The alternative of  8.bxc3  restores material equality but leaves White with a structurally inferior position. }
8... Bg4 { A clever move, provoking White's next move. } 9. f3 Bd7 10. Ba6
{ This was seen in the only game to end up this far, and it does look threatening. Some accurate moves turn the balance in Black's favour, however.   10.b3  is a decent alternative: White wants to eventually regain the pawn on c3 with a structurally better endgame. However, recapturing this pawn may not be as easy as the opponent might think. We hold on to the pawn with  10...Nf6  11.Ne2  Nd5  while simultaneously attacking the bishop on c7!  12.Ba5  Ne3  Usually I would advise against moving the knight a zillion times in the opening, but I really do like my pawns.  13.Rd3   The natural  13.Rc1  allows us to execute a cute idea:  13...e5  14.Bxc3  Ba3!  , forcing White to give up the protection over c2.  13...Nxc2+  14.Kd1  Na3  The knight has gone on quite the tour, but at the end of the day we do end up a pawn! Note that the knight on a3 is not in any danger of getting caught, since it can always escape via b5. }
10... Nf6
{ There is no time to save the rook, we must look for counterplay instead. }
11. Bb7 Nd5
{ Although the rook on a8 is lost, our knight and the constant threat of ...cxb2 provide ample counterplay. }
12. Bxa8 Nxc7 13. Bb7 cxb2 14. Rb1 e5 15. Rxb2 Nd5
{ Although White is up the exchange, Black is quite a bit better. All the dark squares in the white camp are weak, making our dark-squared bishop extremely strong. Moreover, we have excellent central control, with a dominating knight in the center of the board. }
