[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3
{ The Jobava London has become increasingly popular recently. Besides the creative genius of Baadur Jobava, both Simon Williams and Hans Niemann have created successful Chessable courses on the opening that have boosted the popularity even further.  Conventional wisdom holds that one should not place the knight on c3 before pushing the c-pawn to c4, but proponents of this variation have found ways to justify this way of playing. White will often aim to play for an early e2-e4, or start expanding on the Kingside through f2-f3 and g2-g4. }
2... c5
{ 2...Nf6  is the main move, but besides the Jobava London with  3.Bf4  , there also exists the possibility of playing the Veresov Attack with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bg5  .  As I have stressed, our idea is to meet virtually every line except for 2.c4 with 2...c5. This is no exception. By immediately striking in the center, we severely limit White in their options. }
3. e4
{ The only principled way of playing. White must strike back in the center. }
3... dxe4
{ The pawn must be captured! At the same time, the d4-pawn is now hanging, so White must continue energetically. }
4. Bb5+ { This check is not particularly dangerous. } 4... Bd7 5. dxc5 Nf6
{ The e4-pawn does a good job of restricting White's natural development of the g1-knight whereas the c5-pawn is an easy target once we play ...e6 next. }
6. Be3 e6 7. Nge2 Qc8
{ Forcing White to pay some attention to the pawn on c5. } 8. Qd4
{ The best way of defending the pawn.   After  8.b4  b6!  would have been very strong, since  9.cxb6  Bxb4!  works in our favour. }
8... a6 9. Ba4 Bxa4
{ So far we have been following a game of a young Hans Niemann against Peredun, 2019, which continued  9...Nc6  .  The text is an improvement, making use of a small tactical detail down the road. }
10. Qxa4+ Nbd7
{ The c5-pawn is about to fall, but it appears that White can develop an initiative by castling Queenside. }
11. O-O-O Bxc5 12. Bxc5 b5
{ With this clever intermezzo all of our problems are solved.   The natural  12...Qxc5  13.Nxe4  would be problematic since  13...Nxe4  runs into  14.Qxd7  . }
13. Nxe4
{ White replies with an intermezzo of their own, but it is barely enough to equalize. }
13... Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nxc5
{ Followed by castling short, with a comfortable game ahead. } *

