[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Jobava London 2.Nc3 "]
[Black "Jobava London 2.Nc3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3
{ The Jobava London has become increasingly popular recently. Besides the creative genius of Baadur Jobava, both Simon Williams and Hans Niemann have created successful Chessable courses on the opening that have boosted the popularity even further.  Conventional wisdom holds that one should not place the knight on c3 before pushing the c-pawn to c4, but proponents of this variation have found ways to justify this way of playing. White will often aim to play for an early e2-e4, or start expanding on the Kingside through f2-f3 and g2-g4. }
2... c5
{ 2...Nf6  is the main move, but besides the Jobava London with  3.Bf4  , there also exists the possibility of playing the Veresov Attack with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/2N5/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bg5  .  As I have stressed, our idea is to meet virtually every line except for 2.c4 with 2...c5. This is no exception. By immediately striking in the center, we severely limit White in their options. }
3. e4
{ The only principled way of playing. White must strike back in the center. }
3... dxe4
{ The pawn must be captured! At the same time, the d4-pawn is now hanging, so White must continue energetically. }
4. d5
{ The only way to keep the game complicated. The advanced pawn takes control over a number of important squares. }
4... Nf6 { Sometimes, chess speaks for itself. } 5. Nge2
{ The knight is heading to either g3 or f4 depending on circumstances. } 5...
e6
{ There are a number of ways to approach the position but I prefer this one the most. The d5-pawn is a serious asset which is preferably eliminated as soon as possible. }
6. Nf4 { The knight leaps forward to join in the fight for the d5-square. }
6... exd5
{ Deviating from the game Niemann-Duda in which  6...a6  was played, leading to fascinating positions.  The text entails some exchanges after which the position will enter the endgame. }
7. Nfxd5 Nxd5 8. Qxd5
{ The exchange of queens is forced since  8.Nxd5  Be6  is bad news for White. }
8... Qxd5 9. Nxd5
{ Due to the exchange of queens, Nc7+ is threatened, which must be addressed. }
9... Bd6
{ The only reasonable way of covering the c7-square. Although the d5-knight is standing mightily, we are still up one pawn for which White needs to prove compensation. }
10. Be3
{ Developing the bishop, and ensuring that White can castle Queenside on the next turn. }
10... Bf5
{ As it turns out developing the bishop to f5, followed by the knight to d7 is a good response to White's piece activity. }
11. O-O-O Nd7
{ The computer suggests that  11...Nc6  is completely fine as well, but after  12.Nf6+  a lot of tactics arise in the position and we must be careful.  The text is a more practical way of developing, ensuring that everything is well protected and getting ready to castle Queenside ourselves. }
12. Be2
{ In this case,  12.Nf6+  Nxf6  13.Rxd6  b6  14.Bb5+  Ke7  is completely fine for us. If anyone is better, it's Black with the extra pawn. To keep enough compensation, White must keep pieces on the board. }
12... O-O-O 13. Nc3
{ The knight starts jumping around the board, searching for a target to attack. }
13... Be5 14. Nb5 Kb8 { Keeping everything well protected! } 15. Nd6
{ Those who did not yet know how the knight moves, must surely be familiar by now. }
15... Bg6
{ Removing the bishop from the attack while keeping both f7 and e4 protected. The knight on d6 looks daunting, but do not forget that we are still a pawn up and the White must keep playing energetically to retain compensation. }
16. h4 { White keeps threatening stuff, but all of it is easily diffused. }
16... h5 { Bringing a halt to the aspirations of White's h-pawn. } 17. Rd5 f6
{ An important move, protecting the bishop on e5 and getting ready to drive the white rook away from its post with ...Nb6 next. }
18. Rhd1 Nb6 { Forcing the rook to drop back. } 19. R5d2
{ 19.Rxe5  An exchange truly in the style of the Jobava London. Although not entirely objectively sound, it is not unlikely, since you'll most likely be facing an adventurous player essaying this opening.  19...fxe5  20.Bxc5  Kc7!  A strong idea, pinning White down the d-file.  21.b3  A slow move, but it is not easy to keep threatening stuff.   21.Nb5+  would be well met with  21...Kc6  .  21...Kc6  Not seeing any ghosts, and forcing White to retreat their forces.  22.Ba3  a6  I quite like this practical move, controlling the b5-square. White's compensation has completely disappeared and we are ready to include our h8-rook into the game soon enough. }
19... a6
{ Covering the b5-square, and if we would have one more move we would play ...Kc7, actually trapping the knight. }
20. Nxe4
{ As it turns out White has this trick up their sleeve, ensuring that the knight does not get trapped, as well as restoring the material balance. However, by doing this White is forced to enter a rather passive position and the diagonal of our bishop on g6 is opened as a nice bonus. }
20... Rxd2 21. Nxd2 Nd5
{ Surely we are very deep into the line by now, but actually, the moves from both sides have all been rather forced. The text is the last detail securing that White loses the bishop on e3, since capturing the pawn on c5 is quite a dangerous undertaking. }
22. Bxc5
{ This pawn may be a juicy one, but the capture will leave a sour taste in White's mouth. }
22... Rc8 23. Nb3 Nb4
{ That is the trick! The knight on b4 can not be captured due to  23.Bxb4  Rxc2  winning for Black. At the same time, there are some serious threats to the a2 and c2-pawn, ensuring that White is in a perilous situation. }
