[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 1.Nf3 & 1.c4"]
[Black "1.c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ Fortunately, for us Tarrasch players, the English is an opening that does not bother us, as White's best is almost always to transpose to our favourite opening. }
1... e6
{ Since we can not immediately play  1...d5  , we have to prepare it first. However, the attentive reader will have noticed that in the Tarrasch we always play ...e6 as well, so we do not lose any value starting with this here. }
2. g3
{ Those who play the English and do not wish to enter 1.d4 territory are likely to fianchetto their bishop early on.   2.Nc3  d5  3.d4  is a direct transposition.   2.Nf3  d5  3.e3  is quite a trendy line, but it is no headache for us, as we can make all the routine moves:  3...c5!  4.d4  transposes to the 4th Move Sidelines chapter   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2P5/5N2/PP1PPPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  is also a direct transposition. }
2... d5 3. Bg2
{ White can start with  3.Nf3  too, but the variations are more than likely to transpose to 3.Bg2 after  3...c5  4.Bg2  . }
3... c5
{ The idea should become clear to you right around this point, as we are simply playing the Tarrasch setup as if White has already committed to d4. There will be some key differences down the road though, so keep paying attention! }
4. Nf3 Nc6
{ A small piece of caution is required here, as throughout the main body of the course with 1.d4, I always recommend bringing out the g8-knight first.   Here, things are a little different as starting with  4...Nc6  will allow us to transpose to the 1.Nf3 variation in case White plays  5.d4  now.   Would we have started with  4...Nf6  instead, we would not have that option. After  5.d4  our best choice is to play  5...Nc6  , but after  6.O-O  , we have no better than to play a highly theoretical variation of the Catalan with  6...dxc4  , which we precisely wish to avoid. }
5. O-O
{ The only other sensible move that keeps avoiding the Tarrasch, besides  5.d4  .   5.d4  transposes to my analysis on 1.Nf3  .   5.cxd5  exd5  6.d4  Nf6  is a Tarrasch, as we have seen many times before. }
5... d4
{ Since  5...Nf6  6.d4  is undesirable for the aforementioned reasons, I have decided to recommend a reverse Benoni system. Although you may feel slightly unfamiliar with these structures, I hope to give you some guidance on how to play them. }
6. e3
{ There is very little difference between this and starting with  6.d3  Nf6  7.e3  , as they transpose into each other. }
6... Nf6 7. exd4 cxd4 8. d3
{ This is the starting position of the reverse Benoni, where Black has a wealth of options at their disposal. I have tried looking for the one that is most likely to surprise your opponent, as well as not allowing them their typical play. }
8... h6
{ I very much like this sideline, as it prevents White from carrying out the desired positional plan of Bg5-xf6, which is very typical in the Benoni.  Since Black has more space here, avoiding exchanging pieces will be useful as White will find it harder to arrange their pieces in a good way given that they have less room to do so. }
9. Re1
{ According to my database, this is the most popular move and it has been played by many strong grandmasters too, yet it already gives Black a significant advantage! }
9... Bd6
{ An important move, as it stops White from playing Bf4, and White will find it incredibly hard to develop their pieces in a good way. }
10. Na3 O-O 11. Nc2 a5
{ A final accurate move, firmly establishing that the advantage is in Black's hands. This stops White from playing b2-b4, and prepares  ...e6-e5 on the next move.   Note that White can not capture on d4 due to  12.Ncxd4  Nxd4  13.Nxd4  Bb4!  winning the exchange for Black. }
*

