{ Once again, I feel this is the least pleasant move for White to face, as it prevents Ne5, and will support the ...e6-e5 push in the long run. The plan is now to quickly develop the Kingside. }
10. Re1
{ A logical move, occupying the semi-open file.   Note that  10.Nbd2  would be a terrible blunder due to  10...g5  , winning the bishop!  With the text, White ensures that the bishop will have the e5-square available. }
10... Bb4 { A clever move, causing some disharmony in the white camp. } 11. Re2
{ This has been the most popular move thus far, but the rook is a touch awkward here. }
11... Bc5
{ Having accomplished the little disturbance in the white camp, the bishop retreats, so that a2-a3 will not come with a tempo. }
12. Na3
{ Since developing the knight to d2 still seems rather risky due to the ...g5 business, this is the alternative and has been played in both human games that reached this position. }
12... O-O 13. Nc2 a5
{ A typical idea in the Benoni, stopping b2-b4 once and for all. Slowly Black can start preparing ...e6-e5, with a comfortable position as it is not clear what White should aim for instead.  A nice game here was Grigorian-Kollars, 2020, which Black convincingly managed to win. }
