{ There is very little difference between this and starting with  6.d3  Nf6  7.e3  , as they transpose into each other. }
6... Nf6 7. exd4 cxd4 8. d3
{ This is the starting position of the reverse Benoni, where Black has a wealth of options at their disposal. I have tried looking for the one that is most likely to surprise your opponent, as well as not allowing them their typical play. }
8... h6
{ I very much like this sideline, as it prevents White from carrying out the desired positional plan of Bg5-xf6, which is very typical in the Benoni.  Since Black has more space here, avoiding exchanging pieces will be useful as White will find it harder to arrange their pieces in a good way given that they have less room to do so. }
9. Bf4
{ The only testing move, as any other move would allow ...Bd6, when it is not clear at all where White will develop their dark-squared bishop. }
9... Nd7
{ Once again, I feel this is the least pleasant move for White to face, as it prevents Ne5, and will support the ...e6-e5 push in the long run. The plan is now to quickly develop the Kingside. }
10. Re1
{ A logical move, occupying the semi-open file.   Note that  10.Nbd2  would be a terrible blunder due to  10...g5  , winning the bishop!  With the text, White ensures that the bishop will have the e5-square available. }
10... Bb4 { A clever move, causing some disharmony in the white camp. } 11.
Nbd2
{ Bringing the knight out is probably the most critical, but as we already know ...g7-g5 is a threat that will be constantly looming. }
11... a5
{ A typical idea, stopping White from making any advances on the Queenside with a2-a3 followed by b2-b4.   Instead,  11...g5  would not have won a piece yet due to  12.Be5  , escaping. However, we keep this idea in our pocket as we may well be able to use it at a later stage. }
12. a3 Be7
{ Retreating with the bishop is best, as it is safe and sound here.   Note that  12...Bc5  would be less accurate here due to  13.Ne4  , hitting the bishop.  We simply plan to castle next, and see how White proceeds. }
13. Nb3
{ The only critical idea, as allowing us to comfortably finish development would mean that Black is doing very fine.  Generally, if Black manages to finish development, without losing any material, and without trading any minor pieces, they will be doing well as the space advantage will count in the long run. }
13... g5
{ Shying away from complications is not in the spirit of this course. } 14. Be5
{ White must keep going forward as well, since retreating with  14.Bd2  would allow  14...e5  , when White's pieces are all rather strange. }
14... Rg8
{ Once I noticed this idea, I immediately fell in love with it! Black sacrifices the d4-pawn but ensures that they will have enormous compensation, as will become evident soon. }
15. Bxd4 { The pawn must be captured, but now Black gains a bunch of tempi. }
15... g4 { Tempo number one, forcing the knight back. } 16. Nfd2 a4
{ Attacking the second knight is the whole idea of playing 14...Rg8, as it forces White to part with the strong light-squared bishop. }
17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Nc1 { White must keep retreating! } 18... c5 19. Bc3 Bb7
{ This is the position I was aiming for when recommending the pawn sacrifice. Suddenly Black has acquired a monster bishop on the long diagonal, and White's pieces are rather discombobulated. Imagine Black's queen arriving on c6, and checkmate could soon follow.  In general, I feel that our position plays quite a bit easier than White's. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 1.Nf3 & 1.c4"]
[Black "1.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ Whereas the English allows us to comfortably play our typical Tarrasch moves, the Reti is a little different. Actually, I struggled quite a bit to find a fun variation, which still resembles the Tarrasch.  Eventually, I settled on an idea Praggnanandhaa has recently been employing with success, which is quite sharp as well. }
1... d5 2. g3 c5
{ Of course, this move has to be played if we want to stick true to the Tarrasch. }
3. Bg2 Nc6
{ It is important to bring this knight out first, and not the g8-knight, as we will actually develop it to e7 at times.   If we started with  4...Nf6  , we would most likely be forced into playing a Catalan or reverse-Grunfeld type of position, both of which are playable but not exactly what we are looking for here.  Developing this knight first allows us some extra options, that will funk the game up. }
4. O-O
{ In case you are playing a King's Indian aficionado, you might see this, as we'll be playing a KID with reverse colours. Nothing to be worried about, though, since a reverse KID is still better for Black.  I will not go too in-depth here in terms of analysing the plans, just remember not to castle short too early on as we may want to play on the Kingside ourselves. }
4... e5 5. d3 Be7
{ It is clever to keep delaying the development of the g8-knight, as ideas such as ...g5 or ...h5 are definitely not out of the ordinary. }
6. e4 d4 7. a4 h5
{ The h-pawn rushes down the board, and we are already significantly better. Our king will most likely find safety on the Queenside, and we shall try to attack White on the other side of the board. }
*

