[Black "1.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ Whereas the English allows us to comfortably play our typical Tarrasch moves, the Reti is a little different. Actually, I struggled quite a bit to find a fun variation, which still resembles the Tarrasch.  Eventually, I settled on an idea Praggnanandhaa has recently been employing with success, which is quite sharp as well. }
1... d5 2. g3 c5
{ Of course, this move has to be played if we want to stick true to the Tarrasch. }
3. Bg2 Nc6
{ It is important to bring this knight out first, and not the g8-knight, as we will actually develop it to e7 at times.   If we started with  4...Nf6  , we would most likely be forced into playing a Catalan or reverse-Grunfeld type of position, both of which are playable but not exactly what we are looking for here.  Developing this knight first allows us some extra options, that will funk the game up. }
4. d4 { Really the only critical try. } 4... e6 5. c4
{ A rather dull variation, often leading to early exchanges of many pieces. }
5... dxc4 6. Qa4
{ White must recapture the pawn on c4. Now, a short tactical skirmish ensues, eventually leading to a dry position. }
6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Qxd4 8. Bxc6+ Bd7
{ Don't fall for  8...bxc6  9.Qxc6+  followed by 10.Qxa8!. } 9. Be3
{ Using this intermediate move, White makes sure that they are no worse. } 9...
Bxc6 10. Qxc6+ Qd7
{ Even more accurate than  10...bxc6  11.Bxd4  , where White can hope to play for a slight edge due to their superior pawn structure. }
11. Qxc4 Rc8 12. Qb3 Bc5
{ After already exchanging several pieces, we offer to exchange some more. We'll be finishing the development of our Kingside pieces soon after, leading to a completely symmetrical position, with not much going on. }
13. O-O Bxe3 14. Qxe3 a6
{ Don't forget about that pawn on a7! Next up is ...Nf6 followed by ...O-O, with a dead equal position. }
