{ This is where Pragg's idea starts. } 6. Nxd4 Bc5
{ Immediately challenging White's central knight is the point of capturing on d4 the move before.   Now, White is at crossroads, with both  7.Nb3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2bp4/3N4/6P1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nxc6  being viable options that need to be investigated. }
7. Nb3
{ Retreating with the knight will lead to completely different positions than the sharp variations happening after  7.Nxc6  . The good news is that we will be able to achieve positions which are very similar to the Tarrasch, albeit with a knight on e7 instead of the usual f6. }
7... Bb6 8. c4 { This is the main line by a vast margin. } 8... Nge7
{ This is one of the reasons why we decided to delay developing the knight to f6.   In case of  8...Nf6  ,  9.Bg5  would be rather unpleasant.   Note that capturing with  8...dxc4  would be terrible after  9.Qxd8+  since we lack too much development in the endgame. }
