exd5
{ Of course, we don't play  9...Nxd5  , but happily accept the chance of playing with the isolani.  Compared to the regular Tarrasch the differences are easy to notice, as the white knight on b3 is strangely out of place, and so is our knight on e7.  Probably, all in all, things are slightly in Black's favour as White has already spent 3 tempi moving the knight around, while Black's b6-bishop is slightly more active than on its usual e7-spot. }
10. Nc3 O-O
{ It would be possible to play  10...d4  immediately, but I prefer this flexible move. We needn't worry about White capturing on d5 as we would get an abundance of activity in return.  White has a wealth of options here, so it is good to take a brief look at all of them. }
11. Bg5
{ This was played by Hracek, and it seems natural as well. Fortunately, with our knight being on e7 this pin is much less of a worry. }
11... d4
{ Taking care of the Nxd5 threat by pushing forward. This is all quite similar to the Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5 Bxc5 10.Bg5 variations, where our knight stands on f6 and the bishop on e7. }
12. Na4
{ A handy addition of having the knight on e7 is that  12.Nd5  could be met by  12...f6!  . }
12... Re8
{ Occupying the semi-open file with the rook, so that we can always meet Bxe7 with ...Rxe7. Next, we want to kick the bishop away with ...h6.  If White ever captures on b6 we will happily recapture with ...axb6, which is quite similar to the Tal-Keres game, discussed in the Model Games section, but this is a very favourable version for us. }
