1. Nf3
{ Whereas the English allows us to comfortably play our typical Tarrasch moves, the Reti is a little different. Actually, I struggled quite a bit to find a fun variation, which still resembles the Tarrasch.  Eventually, I settled on an idea Praggnanandhaa has recently been employing with success, which is quite sharp as well. }
1... d5 2. g3 c5
{ Of course, this move has to be played if we want to stick true to the Tarrasch. }
3. Bg2 Nc6
{ It is important to bring this knight out first, and not the g8-knight, as we will actually develop it to e7 at times.   If we started with  4...Nf6  , we would most likely be forced into playing a Catalan or reverse-Grunfeld type of position, both of which are playable but not exactly what we are looking for here.  Developing this knight first allows us some extra options, that will funk the game up. }
4. d4 { Really the only critical try. } 4... e6 5. O-O cxd4
{ This is where Pragg's idea starts. } 6. Nxd4 Bc5
{ Immediately challenging White's central knight is the point of capturing on d4 the move before.   Now, White is at crossroads, with both  7.Nb3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2bp4/3N4/6P1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nxc6  being viable options that need to be investigated. }
7. Nb3
{ Retreating with the knight will lead to completely different positions than the sharp variations happening after  7.Nxc6  . The good news is that we will be able to achieve positions which are very similar to the Tarrasch, albeit with a knight on e7 instead of the usual f6. }
7... Bb6 8. c4 { This is the main line by a vast margin. } 8... Nge7
{ This is one of the reasons why we decided to delay developing the knight to f6.   In case of  8...Nf6  ,  9.Bg5  would be rather unpleasant.   Note that capturing with  8...dxc4  would be terrible after  9.Qxd8+  since we lack too much development in the endgame. }
9. cxd5 { 9.Nc3  transposes to 9.cxd5 after  9...O-O  10.cxd5  exd5  . } 9...
exd5
{ Of course, we don't play  9...Nxd5  , but happily accept the chance of playing with the isolani.  Compared to the regular Tarrasch the differences are easy to notice, as the white knight on b3 is strangely out of place, and so is our knight on e7.  Probably, all in all, things are slightly in Black's favour as White has already spent 3 tempi moving the knight around, while Black's b6-bishop is slightly more active than on its usual e7-spot. }
10. Nc3 O-O
{ It would be possible to play  10...d4  immediately, but I prefer this flexible move. We needn't worry about White capturing on d5 as we would get an abundance of activity in return.  White has a wealth of options here, so it is good to take a brief look at all of them. }
11. Na4
{ The top engine move, so we must explore it a bit more in-depth than the other options. }
11... d4
{ Even without a knight on c3, gaining more space with the d-pawn is desirable. Typical plans such as ...Be6-d5 become readily available. }
12. Bd2
{ 12.Bg5  would transpose to the 11.Bg5 variation.  The text is more subtle, ensuring that the bishop is safe and secure and preparing Rc1 as well. }
12... h5
{ I could never resist recommending this move! The simple plan of advancing the h-pawn down the board is always surprisingly tough to meet for the opposing side. }
13. Bg5
{ Actually, altogether attempting to stop the h-pawn may be best, but the story doesn't end here.   In case of  13.h4  , we would acquire a fantastic square on g4 for our bishop and should immediately use it with  13...Bg4  . }
13... Re8
{ Improving the rook.  It is interesting to compare this position to the 11.Bg5 variation, as we reached nearly the same position, with the difference being that the h-pawn is on h5 instead of h7.  It is hard to say who this benefits exactly, as there is no more ...h6 to kick the bishop away, but on the other hand, the idea of playing ...h4 is still alive, even with the bishop on g5 as we shall see. }
14. Rc1 h4
{ Boom! The tactical justification is that  15.Bxh4  suddenly runs into  15...f6  , with the idea of ...g5 capturing the bishop. On the other hand, 15.gxh4  is not enticing either. All in all, we are doing well here. }
15. gxh4 { Perhaps this is White's best, but it looks super dangerous. } 15...
Bc7
{ The bishop switches diagonals and the simple idea of ...Qd6 lining up the bishop and queen is extremely dangerous. }
