{ The top engine move, so we must explore it a bit more in-depth than the other options. }
11... d4
{ Even without a knight on c3, gaining more space with the d-pawn is desirable. Typical plans such as ...Be6-d5 become readily available. }
12. Bd2
{ 12.Bg5  would transpose to the 11.Bg5 variation.  The text is more subtle, ensuring that the bishop is safe and secure and preparing Rc1 as well. }
12... h5
{ I could never resist recommending this move! The simple plan of advancing the h-pawn down the board is always surprisingly tough to meet for the opposing side. }
13. Bg5
{ Actually, altogether attempting to stop the h-pawn may be best, but the story doesn't end here.   In case of  13.h4  , we would acquire a fantastic square on g4 for our bishop and should immediately use it with  13...Bg4  . }
13... Re8
{ Improving the rook.  It is interesting to compare this position to the 11.Bg5 variation, as we reached nearly the same position, with the difference being that the h-pawn is on h5 instead of h7.  It is hard to say who this benefits exactly, as there is no more ...h6 to kick the bishop away, but on the other hand, the idea of playing ...h4 is still alive, even with the bishop on g5 as we shall see. }
14. Nbc5
{ White needs to play fast - a superficial move would allow us to get ...h4 in. }
14... Qc7
{ Unfortunately,  14...h4  does not quite work out since White will have resources with Qb3+ after an eventual ...f6.  The text unpins the knight and prepares ...Ng6, which will once again enable us to play ...h4 later on. It is up to White to find a satisfactory remedy against our plan.   Note that in case of @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/ppq1npp1/1bn5/2N3Bp/N2p4/6P1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 4 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Bf4  we can simply return with  15...Qd8  as once again ...h4 is a serious idea that White needs to deal with. }
