1. Nf3
{ Whereas the English allows us to comfortably play our typical Tarrasch moves, the Reti is a little different. Actually, I struggled quite a bit to find a fun variation, which still resembles the Tarrasch.  Eventually, I settled on an idea Praggnanandhaa has recently been employing with success, which is quite sharp as well. }
1... d5 2. g3 c5
{ Of course, this move has to be played if we want to stick true to the Tarrasch. }
3. Bg2 Nc6
{ It is important to bring this knight out first, and not the g8-knight, as we will actually develop it to e7 at times.   If we started with  4...Nf6  , we would most likely be forced into playing a Catalan or reverse-Grunfeld type of position, both of which are playable but not exactly what we are looking for here.  Developing this knight first allows us some extra options, that will funk the game up. }
4. d4 { Really the only critical try. } 4... e6 5. O-O cxd4
{ This is where Pragg's idea starts. } 6. Nxd4 Bc5
{ Immediately challenging White's central knight is the point of capturing on d4 the move before.   Now, White is at crossroads, with both  7.Nb3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/2bp4/3N4/6P1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nxc6  being viable options that need to be investigated. }
7. Nxc6
{ Not only is this the sharpest line of the two, it was also Carlsen's choice. }
7... bxc6 8. c4
{ White hopes to quickly put pressure on our position before we manage to safely castle and enjoy a healthy position. }
8... Nf6 9. Qc2
{ The only way to continue posing problems.   The most popular  9.Nc3  brings White nothing as it allows us to finish development with  9...O-O  , with Black already scoring more than 50% according to the database. }
9... Qe7
{ This move is key to Pragg's idea. In fact, it involves an exchange sacrifice. }
10. cxd5
{ This is the most critical move but strangely enough, it has only been played in practice once before. }
10... cxd5 11. Be3
{ While this is already a complete novelty! With the text, White lures our bishop away from the c-file, thus enabling the idea of Qc6+, capturing the rook. Fortunately, this is only the start of the complications.   Note that in case of  11.b4  Bd4!  the counterattack on the a1-rook makes sure that we don't lose any material. }
11... Bxe3 { There is no way back. } 12. Qc6+ Qd7
{ The check must be blocked in this way. } 13. Qxa8 O-O
{ There is no time to retreat the bishop, as after  13...Bb6  14.Qb8  the white queen escapes unscathed and at the end, we will be down a full exchange.  The text threatens the sneaky ...Ba6, trapping the queen, so that White has no time to capture on e3. }
14. Qb8 { The only way to escape with the queen from the corner. } 14... Bb7
{ Cutting off the b-file, so the queen has once again only one square to escape to. }
15. Qe5 Ng4 { Once again, the queen is being hit and has to move. } 16. Qh5
{ Besides  16.Qc3  , this is the only other available square.  For the moment, things look bad for Black: the knight and bishop are simultaneously attacked. Fortunately, there still are resources in the position. }
16... Nxf2 { Adding more fuel to the fire. } 17. Rxf2 Qb5
{ White is up a full rook, but the simple threat of ...Qxb2 is surprisingly hard to meet as White's pieces are extremely uncoordinated. }
18. Na3
{ White must desperately try to get some pieces out.   18.Qf3  was also possible but after  18...Bxf2  19.Kxf2  Qxb2  20.Qc3  Qb6  , the black attack rages on as the rook will come to the c-file next. }
18... Qxb2 19. Rb1 Qxa2
{ Capturing here first is super important!   Can you spot why  19...Qxa3  20.Rxb7  Qxa2  would be disastrous? }
20. Rxb7 Qxa3
{ Indeed, now  21.Qxf7+  Rxf7  22.Rb8+  no longer is mate due to  22...Qf8  ! It's important to be alert at all times when playing a chess game.  Black will most likely capture the f2-rook on the next turn, or very soon after which the dust has more or less settled. White is up a piece, but Black has an extremely solid pawn structure as well as three pawns for the piece. All in all, giving sufficient compensation. A fascinating line! }
