[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "Tarrasch With 7.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3
Nf6 6. g3 Nc6 7. a3
{ This subtle move has recently started gaining popularity after it was seen in Vitiugov-Giri, Belgrade 2022. The main idea seems to be to avoid the Dubov Tarrasch which occurs after  7.Bg2  cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bc5  . }
7... Be7
{ This fits well within our repertoire.   Giri chose  7...cxd4  instead, after which  8.Nxd4  Bc5  9.Be3  Bb6  leads to an interesting position as well. }
8. dxc5 d4
{ Interestingly enough, the automatic recapture  8...Bxc5  runs into  9.b4  , causing some serious problems. Fortunately, the text is very strong, giving us a powerful initiative. }
9. Na4 b5 { Almost trapping the knight. } 10. cxb6
{ Luckily, for now, White still has en passant available. } 10... axb6
{ The second pawn is coming, and the knight remains in grave danger. White struggles to maintain equality. }
*

