[Black "Tarrasch With 7.a3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3
Nf6 6. g3 Nc6 7. a3
{ This subtle move has recently started gaining popularity after it was seen in Vitiugov-Giri, Belgrade 2022. The main idea seems to be to avoid the Dubov Tarrasch which occurs after  7.Bg2  cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bc5  . }
7... Be7
{ This fits well within our repertoire.   Giri chose  7...cxd4  instead, after which  8.Nxd4  Bc5  9.Be3  Bb6  leads to an interesting position as well. }
8. Bg2 c4
{ The usual idea, which is especially good now that White has played a2-a3, weakening the b3-square. }
9. Bg5
{ There is some point to delaying castling.   Instead,  9.O-O  would transpose to the 8.a3 line from the Fianchetto Without Nc3 – Other 8th Moves chapter. }
9... O-O 10. e3 Be6
{ Just playing all of our regular developing moves, waiting for White to clarify their intentions. }
11. Bxf6 { The start of an ingenious plan. } 11... Bxf6 12. Ng1
{ Yes, this move is not a mouseslip! White intends to reroute the knight via e2 to f4. Since White hasn't castled yet this idea is playable. }
12... Qd7 13. Nge2 Bg5
{ Disfiguring  14.Nf4  , since after  14...Bxf4  15.gxf4  b5  , White has no more play in the center while our pawns on the Queenside are coming down like a steamroll. If White does not play 14.Nf4 we anyway aim to play for ...b5, possibly preparing it with ...Rab8 first.   Note that in case of  14.h4  we can fall back to h6 with the bishop:  14...Bh6  . }
