[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "Tarrasch With 8.Bg5 (White Delays O-O) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5
{ This is the starting position of the Tarrasch Defense. } 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3
Nf6 6. g3 Nc6 7. Bg2 Be7
{ Now, although White has some alternatives to going  8.O-O  here, most of them will transpose to the other chapters later on since White can't delay castling forever. }
8. Bg5
{ Sooner or later White has to castle, taking us to the Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.dxc5 chapter. }
8... cxd4
{ There is nothing wrong with playing  8...c4  either, since after  9.O-O  O-O  we return to the chapter Fianchetto With Nc3 – 9.Bg5.  I believe the text to be an interesting additional option, which might be a shortcut towards solving our problems. }
9. Nxd4 Qb6
{ Suddenly creating a double attack on the d4-knight as well as the b2-pawn. }
10. Bxf6
{ White is forced to exchange our knight, since the immediate  10.Nb3  runs into  10...Ng4!  . }
10... Bxf6 11. Nxd5
{ This has been played by three players, thinking to have tricked us. Surely they did not expect to enter a losing variation instead. }
11... Qxd4 12. Nc7+ Ke7 13. Nxa8
{ White has won the exchange, but the knight has been cornered.   Also  13.Qxd4  would be of no help after  13...Nxd4  14.Nxa8  Nc2+  followed by ...Nxa1. }
13... Qb4+ 14. Kf1 Rd8
{ The a8-knight is stuck forever, while our incredibly strong initiative gives us a winning advantage. }
