[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "Blackmar-Diemer Gambit 2.e4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4
{ Perhaps the Blackmar-Diemar Gambit is the only exception where we do not play 2...c5 in response to a sideline. The pawn is too juicy not to be captured! }
2... dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ This is White's idea behind the pawn sacrifice - they hope to obtain a lead in development in return for the lost pawn. }
4... exf3
{ There are other good ways of playing, but simple chess often works best. } 5.
Nxf3 g6
{ I quite like to fianchetto the bishop here. White aims to attack our Kingside, but this configuration guarantees that our king will be very secure. }
6. Bf4 Bg7 7. Qd2
{ White should castle Queenside to at least keep some illusion of compensation. }
7... O-O 8. O-O-O c6
{ An all-purpose move, covering some squares and intending to start a pawn march down the Queenside. }
9. Bh6 Bg4
{ The bishop stands well here, being able to capture on f3 at any moment, thus reducing White's attacking potential. We can follow up by ...Nbd7, and start our pawn storm with ...b5 soon as well. At the same time, it is hard to find any real compensation for White's pawn deficit.  For those worried about a pawn storm involving h2-h4-h5, don't be! We can comfortably take that pawn with our bishop once it reaches h5. }
