[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "Pseudo-Trompowsky 2.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ As I learned when writing the course, this move bears the cool name of the Levitsky Attack. It is also likely to be played by proponents of the Trompowsky, who desire to develop their bishop to g5 upon facing 1...Nf6 as well. }
2... c5
{ We have no reason to stray away from the formula of playing 2...c5 when allowed. }
3. dxc5
{ The most popular continuation, but capturing this pawn on c5 combined with the bishop on g5 makes a weird impression, and indeed it is not very good!   If White wishes to strengthen the pawn chain through  3.c3  ,  3...Qb6  is already tough to meet. }
3... h6
{ Not an exclamation for the strength, but more so for the rarity of the move. Most players have opted for  3...Qa5+  instead, immediately regaining the pawn, but making two queen moves in the process.  With the text move, we drive the bishop away from g5 and intend to regain the c5-pawn under favourable conditions. }
4. Bh4 { Not allowing us to play ...e6, but now the bishop gets hit again. }
4... g5 5. Bg3 Bg7
{ Occupying the long diagonal and forcing White to spend a tempo on covering the b2-pawn. }
6. c3 Nf6
{ Although we are still down a pawn, we have already established a serious lead in development. The c5-pawn is easily targeted by ...Nbd7, while simply castling is a good idea as well. The engines already give us a significant advantage.  If you dislike the idea of being down a pawn, it might be useful to think of this position as a Catalan on steroids. Any time White tries to hang on to the c5-pawn by b2-b4, they will only add fuel to the fire due to ...Ne4 striking down upon White's position.   A sample line is  7.e3  Nbd7  8.b4  Ne4!  , when  9.Qxd5?  Nxc3  10.Qc4  Na4  wins for Black. }
