[Black "Pseudo-Trompowsky 2.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ As I learned when writing the course, this move bears the cool name of the Levitsky Attack. It is also likely to be played by proponents of the Trompowsky, who desire to develop their bishop to g5 upon facing 1...Nf6 as well. }
2... c5
{ We have no reason to stray away from the formula of playing 2...c5 when allowed. }
3. e3
{ Probably this timid move is White's best.   If White wishes to strengthen the pawn chain through  3.c3  ,  3...Qb6  is already tough to meet. }
3... Nc6 4. Nf3
{ White should develop some pieces.   The most popular move is  4.c3  , which is already very unfavourable for White after  4...f6!  5.Bh4  Nh6!  intending to follow up with ...Nf5, targeting the bishop. }
4... f6
{ A somewhat unorthodox move, but for those who have read the chapter on the London system, this makes perfect sense. There we aim to play with ...f6 as well, but here we even have the benefit of gaining an extra tempo on those variations. }
5. Bf4
{ It does not matter where the bishop goes, both moves are met in the same way. }
5... g5 6. Bg3 h5 { Gaining a lot of space! } 7. h3 cxd4 8. exd4
{ In case of  8.Nxd4  e5  9.Nxc6  bxc6  our central control would be nothing short of majestic. }
8... Nh6
{ The knight heads to f5, hitting the unfortunate bishop once more. With such a space advantage on the Kingside, only Black can be better. }
