[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "2.Nf3 c5 3.Bf4?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5
{ One of the great benefits of playing the Tarrasch is that virtually any other move than 2.c4 can be met by 2...c5. Especially after 2.Nf3, this is a great shortcut, avoiding loads of sidelines.  For example, many London players may wish to play 2.Nf3 and then 3.Bf4, but now they no longer have such an option.   Objectively, White's best move is  3.c4  , but after  3...e6  we transpose back to the main body of the course. I recently was able to use this in my own practice when facing GM Tabatabaei from Iran in the 2022 Olympiad. }
3. Bf4
{ Not a very likely possibility, unless you are playing an online blitz game and your opponent has premoved  3.Bf4  . In that case, it is useful to be ready. }
3... cxd4
{ White is already in a tough situation since exchanging the c-pawn for d-pawn benefits us. }
4. Nxd4 { A logical recapture, but quite a serious mistake. } 4... f6
{ Intending to build a great center with ...e5. The white pieces are completely misplaced and serve as easy targets for an attack. Black is already quite a bit better. }
*

