1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5
{ One of the great benefits of playing the Tarrasch is that virtually any other move than 2.c4 can be met by 2...c5. Especially after 2.Nf3, this is a great shortcut, avoiding loads of sidelines.  For example, many London players may wish to play 2.Nf3 and then 3.Bf4, but now they no longer have such an option.   Objectively, White's best move is  3.c4  , but after  3...e6  we transpose back to the main body of the course. I recently was able to use this in my own practice when facing GM Tabatabaei from Iran in the 2022 Olympiad. }
3. Bf4
{ Not a very likely possibility, unless you are playing an online blitz game and your opponent has premoved  3.Bf4  . In that case, it is useful to be ready. }
3... cxd4
{ White is already in a tough situation since exchanging the c-pawn for d-pawn benefits us. }
4. c3
{ Perhaps it is best to make a dubious pawn sacrifice out of the ordeal. } 4...
dxc3 { Happily accepting the offer. } 5. Nxc3 Nf6 6. e4
{ White should continue to sacrifice pawns to disturb our development, since otherwise, they may soon find themselves without any compensation. }
6... dxe4
{ There's no reason to be scared, as besides capturing another pawn, White is also forced to exchange queens. }
7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. O-O-O+ Bd7
{ The right way of blocking the check, since  8...Ke8  9.Nb5  would suddenly be quite good for White. }
9. Ne5 Ke8
{ Certainly White has decent compensation in the form of piece activity, but due to the absence of queens, it is hard to build a serious attack. If we remain unscattered for the next couple of moves, we may soon be able to capitalize on a healthy material advantage. }
10. Nb5 { White has to keep asking questions. } 10... Na6
{ Protecting against Nc7. Now, it is no longer easy for White to create any more threats while we intend to slowly but surely bring out our pieces with ...e6 and ...Be7. Still, White's activity should be sufficient to maintain the balance. Don't forget that we no longer have the right to castle! }
