[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5
{ One of the great benefits of playing the Tarrasch is that virtually any other move than 2.c4 can be met by 2...c5. Especially after 2.Nf3, this is a great shortcut, avoiding loads of sidelines.  For example, many London players may wish to play 2.Nf3 and then 3.Bf4, but now they no longer have such an option.   Objectively, White's best move is  3.c4  , but after  3...e6  we transpose back to the main body of the course. I recently was able to use this in my own practice when facing GM Tabatabaei from Iran in the 2022 Olympiad. }
3. dxc5
{ If White does not wish to transpose to theoretical variations at all costs, this may be the best try, at least gaining a pawn for the moment. }
3... Nf6 { Natural development is best. } 4. c3
{ I recently faced this line although from the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.c3  c5  4.dxc5  , when playing Arjun Erigaisi in the Abu Dhabi open.  I did not react accurately and soon drifted into a slightly worse position. The point of the line is that White wants to try and hang on to the c5-pawn, for as long as possible.   4.e3  e6  5.b4  a5  6.c3  transposes to 2.Nf3 c5 3.e3 #2. }
4... e6 5. Be3
{ A rather awkward way of defending the pawn, but at least White does not make any structural commitments through  5.b4  yet.   5.b4  is almost certain to transpose to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  Nf6  4.dxc5  e6  5.b4  a5  6.c3  reversed Noteboom variation after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/4pn2/2Pp4/1P6/2P2N2/P3PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq b3 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a5  6.e3  . }
5... Nc6
{ In the aforementioned game I played  5...a5  , stopping b2-b4 ideas.  However, I was hit by  6.c4  , putting me under pressure. After analysing the variation afterwards, I realized that developing pieces is better than making pawn moves. }
6. b4
{ moves such as ...Ng4 were already in the air, so White must protect the pawn on c5 once more. }
6... Be7
{ Keeping all our options on the table by just continuing to develop. White has to reckon with ...a5, ...Ng4 but also the simple ...O-O. }
7. g3
{ Since the e3-bishop blocks the e2-pawn, this is the only satisfactory way for White to develop the bishop. }
7... Ng4
{ It is time to ask White some tough questions. Where would the bishop like to go? }
8. Bd2
{ The most fighting choice.   In case of the forcing  8.Bd4  e5!  9.h3  exd4  10.hxg4  dxc3  11.Nxc3  Nxb4  we would have little to fear. }
8... O-O 9. Bg2 b6
{ Breaking up the white pawn chain. Although we will no longer regain the pawn, we will have wonderful compensation instead. }
10. cxb6 Qxb6 11. O-O a5
{ Continuing to chip away at the white pawn structure. At the same time, White's development looks rather awkward, with especially the bishop on d2 needing to protect the pawns, but being in the way of the b1-knight's development. Although the computer as usual gives an evaluation of 0.00, it seems that Black's position is easier to play. }
