4... e6 5. Qc2
{ This was played in a duel between two Indian superstars, Gukesh-Erigaisi. White is hoping to discourage us from playing  5...Bxc5  since it appears to run into  6.cxd5  with a discovered attack.   5.cxd5  Bxc5  6.Qc2  transposes to the variation at hand. }
5... Bxc5
{ It turns out we can in fact capture this pawn, with the help of some tactics. }
6. cxd5 Qb6
{ Protecting both our bishop and creating a counterthreat to the f2-pawn. } 7.
e3 exd5
{ A reasonably typical IQP position has been reached. After making our standard moves of ...O-O and ...Nc6, we can try to play for ...d4, with a comfortable game ahead. }
