1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5
{ One of the great benefits of playing the Tarrasch is that virtually any other move than 2.c4 can be met by 2...c5. Especially after 2.Nf3, this is a great shortcut, avoiding loads of sidelines.  For example, many London players may wish to play 2.Nf3 and then 3.Bf4, but now they no longer have such an option.   Objectively, White's best move is  3.c4  , but after  3...e6  we transpose back to the main body of the course. I recently was able to use this in my own practice when facing GM Tabatabaei from Iran in the 2022 Olympiad. }
3. dxc5
{ If White does not wish to transpose to theoretical variations at all costs, this may be the best try, at least gaining a pawn for the moment. }
3... Nf6 { Natural development is best. } 4. c4
{ It would have been more critical to make this move on the previous or second move, but then again better late than never as the saying goes.   4.e3  e6  5.b4  a5  6.c3  transposes to 2.Nf3 c5 3.e3 #2. }
4... e6 5. Be3
{ A quirky idea which has once been tried by Chinese GM Li Chao.   5.cxd5  Bxc5  6.Qc2  transposes to a position that is normally reached through the 5.Qc2 move order. }
5... Nbd7
{ There are other possibilities, but this one appears to be the most enticing of all. For now, we simply intend to capture on c5, so White better comes up with something good. }
6. Nc3
{ White tries to avoid complications but doesn't put any pressure on Black either. }
6... Bxc5 7. Bxc5 Nxc5 8. cxd5
{ Interestingly, we have transposed to an ancient game between Nikolic and Seirawan, 1989! In that game, the natural  8...exd5  was played, but the silicon machine points out we have even better. }
8... Qb6
{ Playing for activity by attacking the b2-pawn. We do not mind if White captures on e6, since in return for the pawn we will have amazing piece activity. }
9. dxe6 { Picking up the gauntlet. } 9... Bxe6 10. Qc2 O-O 11. e3 Bf5
{ A cute idea, distracting the white queen away from the defence of the b2-pawn. }
12. Qxf5
{ White has to accept the offer since other queen moves were incredibly passive. }
12... Qxb2 13. Qxc5 Qxa1+ 14. Nd1 Qxa2
{ After quite a few captures, we have reached an interesting imbalanced position, with approximate material equality - White has two pieces for a rook and one pawn.  Usually, this would be slightly in favour of the 2 pieces, but in this case, there are two mighty connected passed pawns on the Queenside, which will soon start marching down the board. Furthermore, we are significantly ahead in development. If anything, the position is easier to play for Black. }
