3. dxc5
{ If White does not wish to transpose to theoretical variations at all costs, this may be the best try, at least gaining a pawn for the moment. }
3... Nf6 { Natural development is best. } 4. c4
{ It would have been more critical to make this move on the previous or second move, but then again better late than never as the saying goes.   4.e3  e6  5.b4  a5  6.c3  transposes to 2.Nf3 c5 3.e3 #2. }
4... e6 5. Be3
{ A quirky idea which has once been tried by Chinese GM Li Chao.   5.cxd5  Bxc5  6.Qc2  transposes to a position that is normally reached through the 5.Qc2 move order. }
5... Nbd7
{ There are other possibilities, but this one appears to be the most enticing of all. For now, we simply intend to capture on c5, so White better comes up with something good. }
6. cxd5 { This is where the fun is at. } 6... Nxd5 7. Bd4 Bxc5
{ We happily offer the g7-pawn, as White will need to move the bishop for a fourth@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ time in eight moves, to capture it. }
8. Bxg7 Rg8 9. Bd4 e5
{ Another cool pawn sacrifice, which can not be accepted. } 10. Bxc5
{ White is forced to make this exchange, as our initiative after  10.Bxe5  Nxe5  11.Nxe5  Qd6  would be insanely powerful. }
10... Nxc5
{ With two powerful horses in the center of the board, and an open g-file to work with we certainly have good play here for the lost pawn. }
11. Nxe5
{ Capturing another pawn is incredibly risky, but also versus other moves our initiative would have been strong. }
11... Be6 12. Nc3 Qc7
{ A nifty move, as  13.Nxd5  is conveniently met by  13...Qxe5  . At the same time, we are ready to castle Queenside on the next turn, with fantastic play. Even objectively, the computers already prefer Black. }
