[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5
{ One of the great benefits of playing the Tarrasch is that virtually any other move than 2.c4 can be met by 2...c5. Especially after 2.Nf3, this is a great shortcut, avoiding loads of sidelines.  For example, many London players may wish to play 2.Nf3 and then 3.Bf4, but now they no longer have such an option.   Objectively, White's best move is  3.c4  , but after  3...e6  we transpose back to the main body of the course. I recently was able to use this in my own practice when facing GM Tabatabaei from Iran in the 2022 Olympiad. }
3. g3
{ I was surprised to notice that this move is not as bad as it looks. White is playing a reversed Grunfeld, and probably we have no better than to transpose to some mainstream theory. }
3... cxd4 4. Bg2
{ The most popular move is the automatic recapture  4.Nxd4  , but it is actually a grave mistake, as after  4...e5  Black is already much better with the central pawns. }
4... Nf6 5. O-O
{ By now we have reached a major theoretical position, which is akin to a reversed Grünfeld.  It is important to understand that we do not wish to play  5...Nc6  here too early, since that allows White to capture  6.Nxd4  and meet  6...e5  with  7.Nxc6  , exchanging off the knights.  Therefore, a bit of a waiting game will ensue, with White hoping to see ...Nc6, while Black wishes that White captures on d4, with our knight still standing on b8. }
5... h6
{ With the previous bit of text in mind, this move makes perfect sense, persuading White to capture on d4. }
6. b3
{ White cleverly rejects the offer and passes the ball back into our court. At the same time, the b2-square is freed up for the bishop. }
6... h5
{ Now things are getting really weird! I do think that this idea fits well in our course, unbalancing the position and getting our opponents out of their comfort zones.  It was possible to play this move immediately instead of 5...h6, but most likely, b3 is not beneficial to White as it may leave the dark squares weakened.  A glance at the database also tells us that Black has a great score with 6...h5!? - scoring six victories, three draws and no losses to date. }
7. h3
{ Besides  7.h4  , this is another way of trying to stop our h-pawn in its tracks. However, it accomplishes the exact opposite as will soon become clear. }
7... h4 8. g4 Bxg4
{ Boom! In fact, this was recently played by my good friend IM Thomas Beerdsen, who was the inspiration for this line. }
9. hxg4 h3 10. Bh1 h2+
{ Certainly White was not expecting this when playing 7.h3! } 11. Nxh2
{ The pawn must be taken, but now the h-file is opened for our rooks. } 11...
Nc6
{ A slight improvement over the aforementioned game. Although White is up a piece, their king is in dire straits and our pawn on d4 obstructs the White army severely. This means that we can continue to develop our initiative slowly but surely, while the opponent will find it hard to bring their pieces into the defence. }
*

