[White "13) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "2.Nf3 c5 3.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5
{ One of the great benefits of playing the Tarrasch is that virtually any other move than 2.c4 can be met by 2...c5. Especially after 2.Nf3, this is a great shortcut, avoiding loads of sidelines.  For example, many London players may wish to play 2.Nf3 and then 3.Bf4, but now they no longer have such an option.   Objectively, White's best move is  3.c4  , but after  3...e6  we transpose back to the main body of the course. I recently was able to use this in my own practice when facing GM Tabatabaei from Iran in the 2022 Olympiad. }
3. e3 { A typical choice for those who like to play the Colle System. } 3...
Nf6 4. dxc5 { Aiming for a reversed Noteboom variation. } 4... e6 5. b4
{ The only way of protecting the c5-pawn. } 5... a5 6. c3 axb4 7. cxb4 b6
{ This ensures that we will win the pawn since  8.cxb6  runs into  8...Bxb4+  . }
8. a4 bxc5 9. b5
{ The point of White's previous play. We have reached the Noteboom position with reversed colours. While Black is doing fine in terms of equalizing, they can not expect to play for an advantage playing a theoretical position down a tempo. }
9... c4
{ I quite like this idea, which was the choice of both Carlsen and Ding. Immediately advancing our passed pawn, and lengthening the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop. }
10. Be2 Bb4+
{ Forcing the exchange of dark-squared bishops is decent for us since we'll be able to block the white pawns on the Queenside more easily afterwards. }
11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Ne4
{ This entails a pawn sacrifice, but we'll get great compensation in return. }
13. Qd4 Qa5+ 14. Kf1
{ White must move the king since  14.Nbd2  O-O  15.O-O  e5!  is a nice tactic. White loses material in all of the lines, for example,  16.Qxd5  Nc3!  17.Qxc4  Be6  18.Qd3  Rd8  and White must lose the protection of the bishop. }
14... O-O 15. Bxc4
{ White can win a pawn with this tactic, but as mentioned we have been more than willing to give it up. After all, the white king is stuck in the center and we'll have attacking chances. }
15... Bb7 16. Bd3 Rc8
{ The rook occupies the open file and is ready to infiltrate c1. Bringing the b8-knight into the game is also very much on our agenda. In any case, White should be very careful not to land into serious danger very quickly. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "2.Nf3 c5 3.e3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5
{ One of the great benefits of playing the Tarrasch is that virtually any other move than 2.c4 can be met by 2...c5. Especially after 2.Nf3, this is a great shortcut, avoiding loads of sidelines.  For example, many London players may wish to play 2.Nf3 and then 3.Bf4, but now they no longer have such an option.   Objectively, White's best move is  3.c4  , but after  3...e6  we transpose back to the main body of the course. I recently was able to use this in my own practice when facing GM Tabatabaei from Iran in the 2022 Olympiad. }
3. e3 { A typical choice for those who like to play the Colle System. } 3...
Nf6 4. dxc5 { Aiming for a reversed Noteboom variation. } 4... e6 5. b4
{ The only way of protecting the c5-pawn. } 5... a5 6. c3 axb4 7. cxb4 b6
{ This ensures that we will win the pawn since  8.cxb6  runs into  8...Bxb4+  . }
8. Bb5+
{ This is Le Quang Liem's recommendation in his course on the London. This typical check is also common in the reversed Noteboom, where Black plays ...Bb4+. }
8... Bd7 { The check must be blocked in this way. } 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4
{ Similarly to 8.a4, White aims for the two connected passed pawns on the edge of the board.   Note that  10.c6  fails due to  10...Bxb4+  . }
10... bxc5 11. b5 g5
{ Super sexy! I simply could not refrain from recommending this move, which has already been played by a number of strong players such as Wesley So and Alexander Grischuk. The pawn will often be pushed to g4, undermining the f3-knight. }
12. Bb2
{ White can not afford to play  12.Nxg5  , since  12...Rg8  spells bad news upon their position. }
12... Bd6
{ It is important to cover the e5-square before pushing ...g4. White has a wide variety of continuations, but  Black should be doing well in all of them. }
13. Qe2
{ This has been played by Le Quang twice, so naturally, this should be the move we should investigate.   Instead,  13.Nfd2  has been tried a couple of times too, after which  13...Qc7  is very reasonable. }
13... g4 { Kicking the white knight away as per the plan. } 14. Nfd2 Qb8
{ Although  14...Qc7  is certainly possible too, I slightly prefer this square for the queen. We make sure that an eventual a4-a5&b5-b6 will not hit our queen. The game is certainly super complex, but Black is doing fairly alright.  Ideas include playing ...c5-c4 and ...Nc5, bringing the knight to d3 from where it's strong as an octopus. Even gaining further space on the Kingside with ...h5-h4 is not out of the question. Our king is surprisingly safe on e8 but can seek shelter on either e7 or f8 if needed. }
