[Black "2.Nf3 c5 3.e3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5
{ One of the great benefits of playing the Tarrasch is that virtually any other move than 2.c4 can be met by 2...c5. Especially after 2.Nf3, this is a great shortcut, avoiding loads of sidelines.  For example, many London players may wish to play 2.Nf3 and then 3.Bf4, but now they no longer have such an option.   Objectively, White's best move is  3.c4  , but after  3...e6  we transpose back to the main body of the course. I recently was able to use this in my own practice when facing GM Tabatabaei from Iran in the 2022 Olympiad. }
3. e3 { A typical choice for those who like to play the Colle System. } 3...
Nf6 4. c3 { We are now playing a reversed Slav Defence. } 4... e6
{ There are many ways of developing. I quite like the plan of playing ...Nbd7, ...b6 and ...Be7, just getting a comfortable and equal game. }
5. Bd3 Nbd7 6. Nbd2 b6
{ It is clever to develop the bishop to b7 as early as possible, dealing with any e3-e4 shenanigans. }
7. O-O Bb7 8. Qe2 { Still trying to get e3-e4 in. } 8... Ne4
{ A way of keeping things spicy, not allowing the opponent to play e3-e4 at all. We will follow up by completing our Kingside development, while it is not obvious for White to find a new plan. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Josef Benzinger - Siegbert Tarrasch, Munchen 1932"]
[Result "*"]

{ In a course on the Tarrasch Defense, one surely has to include a game of the inventor of the opening, Mr Siegbert Tarrasch himself. In those days, the theory was not very far advanced yet, but the general plans can already be seen upon looking through the games of the old masters. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8.
dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bg5 Be6
{ As we now know, this is a touch passive and the preference should be given to  9...O-O  . }
10. Nbd2
{ Upon clicking through dozens of historical games in the Tarrasch Defense, I have noticed a tendency of players back then to develop the knight this way. As we now know, the knight stands much better on c3 instead. }
10... h6 { Cashing in on the bishop pair is a good idea. } 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12.
Nb3 Bb6
{ Already Black is comfortable, with great control over the dark squares and the two bishops. }
13. Qd2 O-O 14. Rfd1 Rac8 15. a3
{ Another slow move, after which Black is firmly in the driver's seat.   15.e3  should have been preferred, intending to play either one of the knights to d4. }
15... Rfd8
{ Having been able to develop and position the pieces on excellent squares, Black already enjoys a good advantage. Notice how in this case the isolani is a strength, rather than a weakness as it obstructs White's forces and takes up a lot of space. }
16. Nbd4
{ In case of another move, Black would have started advancing the isolani. After the text, White's problems are not over, however. }
16... Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Rc4
{ Strong play by Tarrasch, as he puts serious pressure on the white position. }
18. Nf3
{ Hoping to maintain the knight with  18.e3  is no fun either, as Black is much better after the subsequent trade of bishop for a knight. After  18...Bxd4  19.exd4  Rdc8  Black has full control over the c-file and threatens ...Rc2; White is in dire straits. }
18... g5
{ Tarrasch proves he is well up to the task of continuing the initiative. Often in the Tarrasch Defense, there are tactics using the slightly weak f2-point. Noticing this vulnerable point, Tarrasch sets to exploit this and threatens to play ...g4 next. }
19. h3
{ Perhaps White had hoped to bring a halt to the Black attack, at least momentarily but they would have been wrong. }
19... g4
{ Not slowing down in the slightest, as the rook is suddenly being transferred over to the g-file. }
20. hxg4 Rxg4 { ...Rxg3 is now a serious threat that has to be reckoned with. }
21. Kf1
{ After this move, it's more or less game over.   21.e3  would have been the only way to continue struggling on, as at least the bishop on b6 is slightly diminished in its activity. }
21... d4
{ I know I have been giving a lot of exclamation marks, but they are well deserved.  The text is once again a demonstration of the deep understanding Tarrasch had of his own opening. The d-pawn is being used as a force, rather than being considered a weakness. Sooner or later, the d-pawn will advance one more square, ripping open the protection in front of White's king. }
22. Bh3
{ The final mistake, but in bad positions, good moves are hard to come by. }
22... Re4
{ Perhaps, only here Benzinger noticed that his planned  23.Bxe6  would run into the devastating  23...d3  .  Actually, ...d3 will come next regardless of White's move. }
23. Bg2
{ The alternative would be just as losing.   23.Bxe6  d3!  This sexy move demolishes White's position as there are too many threats to handle. }
23... d3 { Of course! } 24. exd3 Rxd3
{ Using the fact that  25.Qxd3  runs into  25...Bc4  . } 25. Qc2 Rxf3 26. Qxe4
Rxf2+ 27. Ke1 Qxb2 { Mate will follow from various directions. A great game. }
*

