[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Tigran Petrosian - Boris Spassky, Moscow 1969"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Bg5 cxd4
{ Although this is not my recommendation in the course, I have decided to devote no less than three model games to this old main line. Although this move is nowadays considered slightly dubious and better ways have been found, the types of positions reached will be similar to the positions you will encounter in many slightly different variations.  Actually, it was not until the Karpov-Kasparov, 1984 Match that this move really started decreasing in popularity. As is widely known, Spassky managed to eventually win his World Championship Match against Petrosian, only to lose it later to Fischer in 1972.  What is less well known, is that Spassky started the match rather poorly, and it was in this crucial game four that the match turned, as he defeated the Petrosian with the black pieces no less. }
10. Nxd4 h6 11. Be3 Bg4
{ Spassky had employed this particular variation already in game two of the match.   In game 18, he switched to  11...Re8  instead, which is the other main line. Actually, upon doing the analytical work for this course, I spent quite some time attempting to revolutionize this particular variation. In the end, I was not fully satisfied, but I believe it is certainly not unplayable either. }
12. Nb3
{ Petrosian sticks to his guns.   Nowadays this move is regardless as rather harmless and  12.h3  and @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp2bpp1/2n2n1p/3p4/3N2b1/2N1B1P1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qa4  are considered more testing. }
12... Be6
{ It is logical to protect the d5-pawn, but modern computers have no such intentions and offer a variety of moves, simply ignoring White's threats.   12...Qc8  is one of the engine-approved moves, clearing the d8-square for the rook, as well as hinting at ...Bh3.  13.Nxd5  Nxd5  14.Qxd5   14.Bxd5  Rd8  already loses material for White.  14...Bxe2  Black is doing absolutely fine. }
13. Rc1 Re8
{ It may have been an improvement to play  13...Qd7  , already creating the idea of ...Bh3. }
14. Re1
{ After this soft choice Black achieves a comfortable game.   The rather strange return of the knight with  14.Nd4  would have brought Black into an inferior position. I have never particularly enjoyed positions where White is allowed to play Nxe6, but at the same time, there is no real way of avoiding them either. }
14... Qd7
{ Now everything is back to being in order, since  15.Nd4  is conveniently met by  15...Bh3  . }
15. Bc5
{ Often White will have a choice of whether to play Bc5 or Nc5, it is never easy to choose which one to opt for.  From a positional viewpoint, it is logically advantageous to exchange pieces for White, especially our dark-squared bishops, things are rather more complicated. The reason being that in doing so, White will lose essential control over the d4-square, allowing us to quite often thrust our pawn forward.  Besides, our so-called remaining bad bishop on e6 is not so bad at all since it will often be able to bring itself out to h3, or poke the White position with ...Bg4 as will be seen in this game. }
15... Rac8
{ While the f8-rook often develops itself to e8, it is never completely clear what to do with a8-rook since both d8 and c8 are decent squares. This is no exception, as both ...Rad8 as well as the text are perfectly playable. }
16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. e3
{ Already worried about an eventual ...d5-d4, White decided to take measures rather earlier than later. However, even such an apparently safe move as e2-e3 weakens the White Kingside just a tad more since the f3-square is now less well-defended. Spassky will set about to exploit this.   As often,  17.Nxd5  is not dangerous whatsoever.  17...Nxd5  18.Bxd5  Rcd8  19.e4  Nb4  Black will regain the pawn with a fine position. }
17... Red8 18. Qe2 Bg4
{ Moves like these are very important to incorporate into your system, as they are likely to annoy the opponent. White does not wish to allow the active bishop to remain on g4, however, removing it comes at the price of weakening their position. }
19. f3
{ Petrosian evidently does not wish to tolerate the bishop on g4, but now the e3-pawn is permanently weak. }
19... Bf5 20. Rcd1 Ne5
{ Slowly but surely Black is improving his pieces. The knight is well-centralized and may even look for the c4-square later. The game is still balanced objectively, but already it feels as if Black's position is slightly easier to handle and White must be careful. }
21. Nd4 Bg6 22. Bh3 Rc4
{ Spassky decided to go on a bit of a holiday with his rook. Although computers don't necessarily approve of it, it must have confused Petrosian as he was not able to deal with it in a good way.   More solid may have been  22...Rc7  , leaving the c4-square free for the knight to occupy. }
23. g4
{ So far, Petrosian is up to the occasion as he finds an excellent idea, creating the threat of f4 followed by f5, locking up the g6-bishop. }
23... Rb4
{ The rook makes a funny impression on b4, but it was necessary to move it in order to avoid tactical ideas along the lines of f3-f4 and an eventual Nxd5, leaving the rook unprotected. Clearly, Spassky must have been in an adventurous mood to play in this manner. }
24. b3
{ Petrosian decides to consolidate his position before undertaking any more action.   The direct  24.f4  was possible as well, but would only have ensued in further complications:  24...Nc6   All the time I was speaking about the c4-square, but in this particular case it is better for the knight to retreat since  24...Nc4  25.b3  is quite awkward to meet.  25.f5  Bh7  A super complex position has arisen, where the Black position is completely locked up, but White has been advancing on the Kingside like there's no tomorrow, creating quite some weak points in the process. The position is probably dynamically balanced. }
24... Nc6
{ With the c4-square being off-limits, Spassky wisely pre-empts f3-f4 by White and returns the knight back home. the f3+g4 combination may later become targets for attack if White is not careful. }
25. Qd2 Rb6
{ When I said the rook is going on a holiday I was not joking, this is certainly quite an absurd place for the rook. Magically, however, Spassky manages to bring it back along the sixth rank in just a couple of moves. }
26. Nce2
{ This is a real step in the wrong direction, clearly being too passive.   26.Na4  is a tempting alternative, since 26...Nxd4 does not work.  26...Ra6  However, completely sidetracking the rook seems to be quite playable for Black!   26...Nxd4  27.exd4  Re6  28.g5  being the clever point, as White wins material here.  27.Bf1  Nxd4  28.exd4  Re6  The subtle difference is that g4-g5 no longer wins the exchange with White's bishop being on f1.   The sophisticated  26.Bg2  may have been White's best. Actually, the bishop on h3 was not doing altogether much, and now the path is opened for White's h-pawn to advance. }
26... Bh7 { Profylaxis against an eventual Nf4. } 27. Bg2
{ A solid choice by Petrosian, bringing the bishop back home.   Some older books recommended  27.Nf4  instead, but after  27...g5  , forcing the knight back, Black has quite a good position. }
27... Re8 28. Ng3 Nxd4 29. exd4
{ After this the advantage really starts to shift in Black's favour, as the f4- and h4-squares are permanently weak.   29.Qxd4  would have retained the balance. }
29... Re6 { I told you this rook was going to magically rejoin the game! } 30.
Rxe6 { Only for one move though, as White immediately exchanges it. } 30...
Qxe6 31. Rc1
{ Perhaps  31.Kf2  would have been more solid, intending to offer the exchange of more rooks through 32.Re1. }
31... Bg6
{ A subtle idea by Spassky. He notices that the ideal square for the knight would be e6, targeting the d4-pawn as well as taking control over the f4-square. By vacating the h7-square, he starts a slow but effective plan of transferring the knight to greener pastures. }
32. Bf1 Nh7 { Here we go! } 33. Qf4
{ It would have been wise for White to improve their knight as well with  33.Ne2  , looking for the f4-square. }
33... Nf8
{ As per the plan, but this allows White a sudden way to bail out.   33...Qe7  would have been the most accurate, vacating the e6-square as the knight can now manoeuvre to its desired outpost via either f8 or g5. }
34. Rc5
{ Missing his chance.   34.Qe5!  would have been a highly clever way of solving White's problems. Namely, exchanging the queens would solve any White issues of king safety.  34...Qxe5  35.dxe5  Rxe5  36.f4  followed by f5 would be disastrous for Black. }
34... Bb1
{ Perhaps with his last move, Petrosian was hoping to pin Black's queen down to e6, therefore preventing the knight from arriving there. As it turns out, however, the g6-square is just as juicy for the knight. The text therefore not only attacks the a2-pawn but moreover vacates the g6-square. }
35. a4 Ng6 36. Qd2
{ White soon collapses now.   The only way to stay in the game was  36.Qc1  , creating threats to the bishop. }
36... Qf6 37. Kf2 Nf4
{ The knight has been installed, and many threats are starting to appear. The main problem for White is that there are no prospects, and all they can do is try to prevent the threats as they come. }
38. a5
{ White collapses immediately, but the situation was already extremely tough. }
38... Bd3 { A cute tactic, cutting White's protection of the d4-pawn. } 39. Nf5
{ 39.Bxd3  Qxd4+  is game over. } 39... Qg5
{ A final accurate move by Spassky, creating a dual threat of ...Bxf5, and the far stronger ...Nh3+ which prove too many to deal with.   39...Bxf5  40.Qxf4  would not have been as clear. }
40. Ne3 Qh4+ 41. Kg1 Bxf1
{ Petrosian resigned since his position collapses in every variation. A superb win by Spassky!   41...Bxf1  42.Nxf1   42.Kxf1  Qh3+  43.Kg1  Qxf3-+  42...Re2  43.Qxf4  Qf2+  44.Kh1  Qg2 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Tigran Petrosian - Boris Spassky, Moscow 1969"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Bg5 cxd4 10. Nxd4 h6 11. Be3 Re8
{ Deviating from game 4 of the match, which saw  11...Bg4  instead.  This is the main line, as it vacates the f8-square for the bishops, and hints at the typical exchange sacrifice on e3 later on. }
12. Rc1
{ The most popular move, but also the most testing one in my opinion.   Karpov gave preference to  12.Qb3  instead. }
12... Bf8 13. Nb3
{ Although this puts direct pressure on the d5-pawn, retreating from the center does not seem that critical.   Rather, the subtle  13.a3  which has been employed by Anatoly Karpov and Boris Gelfand among others, appears to be quite a headache for Black restricting the counterplay to a minimum. }
13... Be6 { The d-pawn needs to be protected. } 14. Nb5
{ Petrosian aims to bring the knight around to d4, but as I have stated often throughout the course, the isolani needn't be blockaded but attacked instead. Whenever we have the feeling our opponent is trying to blockade our pawn we can count this as a minor victory.   Instead of the text,  14.Qd2  , intending 15.Rfd1, would have been more venomous. }
14... Bg4
{ Spassky embarks upon a seemingly strange plan, as he will move the bishop four times in a short period. However, all the moves have a point, as White is forced to weaken their position by chasing the bishop around. }
15. h3
{ Sometimes this is a useful move, sometimes it is not. In this case, I think it's the latter as the potential exchange sacrifice on e3 will only become stronger now that the g3-pawn is slightly vulnerable. }
15... Bf5 16. N5d4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Bd7
{ The bishop moves one last time, and perhaps White feels as though they must have accomplished something. Upon a closer look, it becomes rather more apparent that White lacks a good plan since there's no good way to attack the d5-pawn.  Black can slowly set about improving the position and preparing an eventual sacrifice on e3. }
18. Qb3 Qa5
{ Spassky plays excellently. He indirectly defends against Qxb7, by covering the a6-square thus being able to trap White's queen after  19.Qxb7  Reb8  . }
19. a3 Bd6
{ The bishop was nicely tucked away on f8, but it is time to bring it back into action, hitting the g3-pawn, something which may be relevant later on. }
20. Qd3 Qd8
{ Absolutely fantastic play by Spassky. With the b7-pawn no longer being attacked, the queen returns to d8, to reposition itself on e7, threatening ...Bxg3. }
21. Rfd1 Qe7 22. Bd2 { The threat of ...Bxg3 must be dealt with. } 22... Ne4
{ Centralizing the knight, Black's play flows smoothly, mainly because the d5-pawn is not easily attacked. Imagine the knight on d4 being on c3, and things would be much different. }
23. Be1 { 23.Qb3  Rad8  24.Qxb7  Bxg3!  25.fxg3  Nxd2 } 23... Be5
{ 23...Rad8  24.Qb3  Qf6  25.Qxb7 } 24. Qb3
{ A tricky idea, since White attacks both d5 and b7, and Black needs to react accurately. }
24... Bxd4
{ A minor mistake, since although Black will be very solid after this trade, it does in essence give up any hopes of winning the game.   24...Rad8!  is the engine's recommendation, and as it turns out all the tactics work beautifully for Black.  25.Qxb7?   25.Qxd5  Ba4  26.Qxe4  Bxd1  27.Rxd1  Qf6  White loses material, since ...Bxd4 can not be prevented.  25...Bxd4  26.Rxd4  Nxg3!  A stunning blow! Note how this tactic would not have been possible with the White pawn still on h2.  27.fxg3  Qe3+  White loses at least one of the rooks. }
25. Rxd4 Bc6
{ Although White is slightly better here, I think this position is still an excellent demonstration of how the Tarrasch can be extremely solid at times. In fact, in numerous variations throughout the course, we see the White bishop pair not being useful, since the knight on e4 does a great job restricting them. This is a nice example of that being used in a practical game. }
26. h4 Qe5 27. Qe3
{ A mistake, based on a tactical oversight.   With  27.Qd1  White would have retained a small positional advantage. }
27... Qf6
{ As it turns out, there is no convenient way of meeting the treat of ...Nxg3. }
28. Bxe4
{ Bailing out to a slightly worse position.   Note that  28.Qd3  would have run into  28...Bb5!  . }
28... Rxe4 29. Rxe4 dxe4
{ Although Black is slightly better here due to the save king, Iron Tigran defended well and Spassky never really got an attack going. }
30. Bc3 Qf5 31. Rd1 Re8
{ Using a small tactic that  32.Qxa7  is unplayable due to  32...e3  , crushing! }
32. Rd6 f6
{ A typical idea of rendering the c3-bishop useless as it's not looking at a brick wall of pawns. }
33. Rd4 a6 34. Kh2 Qg4 35. a4 Kf7 36. Kg1 Re5
{ Spassky slowly tries to bring his pieces near White's king, but unfortunately, the material is too limited to make any serious headway. }
37. Rd6 Rf5 38. b3 Qh3 39. Be1 Qg4 40. Bc3 Qh3 41. Bd4 h5
{ 41...Rf3  I quickly wondered about this cute tactic, but here too, White manages to bail out into a draw.  42.exf3  exf3  43.Qe6+!  Qxe6  44.Rxe6  Kxe6  45.a5= }
42. Bc3 Kg8 43. Rd8+ Kh7 44. Rd6 Qg4
{ Black's only real idea is ...Rf3, but Petrosian has been dealing with it accurately, so Spassky retreats the queen.   In this specific moment,  44....Rf3  would be a terrible blunder due to  45.exf3  exf3  46.Qd3+  followed by Qf1. }
45. a5 Qg6 46. b4 Qf7 47. Bd4 Qc4 48. Bc5 Re5 49. Bd4 Rf5 50. Bc5 Qc2 51. Qd2
Qb3 52. Qd1 Qb2 53. Qd2 Qa1+ 54. Qd1 Qe5 55. Qd4 Qe8 56. Qc4 Bb5 57. Qe6
{ After a series of moves of going around in circles, Petrosian finally manages to exchange the queens. }
57... Qxe6 58. Rxe6 Rd5 59. Rd6
{ And the rooks as well, leading to an elementary draw.   Note that Spassky had set up the last trick, since  59.Rxe4  loses White the game after  59...Rd1+  60.Kh2  Bc6!   Never lose focus, or you might lose the game! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Anatoly Karpov - Garry Kasparov, Moscow 1984"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ No course on the Tarrasch Defense would be complete without this legendary game, perhaps the most famous of all. Kasparov had rigorously prepared his favourite Tarrasch for his World Championship Match in 1984 versus Karpov, but it did not bring him the results he desired as he lost both games employing it. }
1... d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3 Nf6
{ Playing ...Nf6 before ...Nc6 is important. This idea has only recently become known and is quickly gaining in popularity, avoiding dull and tedious endgames and spicing stuff up. }
6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Bg5 cxd4
{ The third and the last game, where we take a look at this old main line. Back in those days, this was almost an automatic move. In a way, it was after this game, that the Tarrasch started losing its popularity for a long time, with the stigma being that Black will have to defend slightly worse endgames and there is no longer room for entertaining play.   Only later,  9...c4  came to the forefront, the move I recommend in this course. Leading to vastly different positions which are not only easier to play, but also simply better. }
10. Nxd4 h6 11. Be3 Re8 12. Qb3
{ 12.Rc1  is probably the toughest test on Black's position objectively speaking, and the one after which I struggled to find lines amounting to the fun and dynamic play Black so desires to achieve through this opening. The d5-pawn is unfortunately a tad too weak to be compensated with the active piece play here.  With the text move, Karpov intends to quickly put pressure on the isolani as well as limit Black's piece play, but current engines seem to think this is not as dangerous. }
12... Na5 13. Qc2 Bg4 14. Nf5 Rc8
{ Kasparov awards this an exclamation mark in his book on his matches with Karpov, but modern engines disagree and prefer the most popular move  14...Bb4  instead, actually claiming that Black is doing fairly alright! }
15. Bd4
{ Here, Karpov improves over the 7th game in the match, where he chose  15.Nxe7  instead.  Although he won that game, it was not due to the opening. The text clears the e3-square for the knight, from where it can exert enormous pressure on the isolani. }
15... Bc5 { The most accurate reply. } 16. Bxc5 Rxc5 17. Ne3
{ A profound concept, since instead of blockading the d-pawn, White sets about to attack it with as much force as possible. }
17... Be6
{ In his book on the match, Kasparov dedicates much analysis to the alternative  17...d4  , eventually correctly concluding Black is doing alright. }
18. Rad1 Qc8
{ Forming a battery on the c-file is logical.   Stockfish recommends  18...Qe7  instead, claiming that Black is still quite close to achieving equality. }
19. Qa4 Rd8
{ In his annotations, Kasparov leaves no comment after this move. Yet, I feel it is precisely here that Black drifts into an unpleasant position.   While playing the Tarrasch, one must always be ready to shed some material in order to activate the pieces. Exactly that would have been possible here by  19...Nc4!  , removing the dim knight from the rim, and relinquishing some of the pressure on the d5-pawn.  20.Nxc4  Rxc4  21.Qxa7  Bh3!  White has won a pawn, but Black's pieces suddenly seem extremely coordinated. With the last move, Black wishes to exchange bishops, slightly weakening White's king. All in all, there is a lot of counterplay.  22.Rd4  Bxg2  23.Kxg2  b5! }
20. Rd3 a6 21. Rfd1
{ The computer points out a stunning tactic, which would have given White a winning position on the spot:  21.Ncxd5  Bxd5  22.Bxd5  Nxd5  23.Qd1!  falling back with the queen like this is definitely not easy to see, but the pin on the knight combined with the threat of b4 appears to be decisive. }
21... Nc4 22. Nxc4 Rxc4 23. Qa5 Rc5 24. Qb6 Rd7 25. Rd4 Qc7
{ I do not like offering the exchanging queens in this manner, basically ensuring Black will have to defend passively for the remainder of the game.   Instead,  25...Qc6  seems more natural since after  26.Qxc6  bxc6  Black's structure would have significantly improved. }
26. Qxc7 Rdxc7
{ We have reached the beginning of a famous endgame, which has been analysed many times over. It is precisely this type of endgame that one would like to avoid at all costs upon playing a technical wizard by the name of Anatoly Karpov. However, what is often forgotten is that Kasparov was defending this endgame very well up to a certain point, and was close to making a draw. }
27. h3 h5 { Important not to allow White to advance his pawns. } 28. a3 g6 29.
e3 Kg7 30. Kh2
{ Despite being slightly better it is not entirely obvious how White should improve their position. In his book, Kasparov recommends the plan of playing f2-f3 and Kg1-f2 instead, which does seem reasonable. }
30... Rc4
{ The eventual exchange of rooks will be advantageous to the defending side. }
31. Bf3 b5 32. Kg2 R7c5 33. Rxc4 Rxc4
{ Strategically speaking, it would be desirable to play  33...dxc4  instead, restoring the pawn structure, but after  34.Rd6  the white rook would be too active.   Instead,  33...bxc4  was an interesting alternative since Black may be able to use the semi-open b-file for activity. }
34. Rd4 Kf8
{ Bringing the king closer to the center is almost always a good idea in endgames. }
35. Be2 Rxd4 36. exd4
{ After the exchange of another pair of rooks, the position is almost entirely symmetrical. Yet, White retains a symbolic advantage since the d5-pawn is placed on a light square and is therefore easier attacked than the d4-pawn. }
36... Ke7
{ Kasparov correctly points out that  36...Ne4  might have solved all his woes in one go. }
37. Na2 Bc8 38. Nb4 Kd6 39. f3 Ng8
{ An interesting idea would have been to play  39...Ne8  , intending to transfer the knight to e6 via either c7 or g7.   Kasparov analyses  39...h4  , concluding that this would have solved all his problems immediately.  40.gxh4  Nh5  41.Kf2!?  It seems that White can still put some pressure.  41...Nf4  42.Bf1⩲ }
40. h4 Nh6 41. Kf2 Nf5
{ The knight looks beautiful on f5, but it is a touch vulnerable to either g3-g4 or an attack by the bishop. Therefore, e6 may have been a preferable square for the knight. }
42. Nc2 f6
{ The first inaccuracy, weakening his pawn-chain on the Kingside unprovoked.   Simply keeping the status quo with  42...Bd7  might have given Black the draw without too many problems. }
43. Bd3
{ Suddenly Black is faced with some tough questions since the Kingside formation is being put under pressure. }
43... g5
{ A tough decision, after which White is allowed to exchange to a good knight versus bad bishop endgame.  Interestingly, even engines are not entirely sure what's the best way to defend this endgame as Stockfish approves of the text, while Lc0 prefers to retreat the knight to e7. In either case, the defense has become much harder. }
44. Bxf5 Bxf5 45. Ne3
{ If you have ever opened a book on good knights versus bad bishops, this endgame will no doubt have been included. Actually, this endgame has been analysed by so many people throughout the years that I feel my analysis will prove a little superfluous. Therefore, I will keep it rather brief. }
45... Bb1 46. b4 gxh4
{ Although I knew about this famous mistake, I was still shocked to see my Stockfish eval instantly jump from +0,15 to +8!   Although the defense would be by no means easy,  46...Bg6  would have kept the game objectively drawn. }
47. Ng2
{ A now legendary response, which was missed by Kasparov and his team in their home analysis @@StartBracket@@yes, games were adjourned back in those days!@@EndBracket@@. By temporarily giving up a pawn, White can infiltrate the black camp, whereas there's absolutely nothing that Black can do about it. Notice how all the pawns on the Queenside are placed on dark squares, making the bishop something akin to a ghost bishop, not being able to do anything. }
47... hxg3+ 48. Kxg3 Ke6 49. Nf4+ Kf5 50. Nxh5 Ke6 51. Nf4+ Kd6 52. Kg4 Bc2 53.
Kh5
{ According to Stockfish, the cleanest way is to make a triangle with the king starting with  53.Kh4  , effectively putting Black into zugzwang after  53...Bd1  54.Kg3  Bc2  55.Kg4  Black has to give way somehow since any bishop move along the b1-h7 diagonal will allow 56.Kh5, when Black is unable to attack f3. }
53... Bd1 54. Kg6 Ke7 55. Nxd5+
{ This pawn should never have been taken! The loss of this pawn actually benefits Black enormously as it is now possible to activate the king in cases.   55.Nh5  would still have given White a slow but steady route to a win. }
55... Ke6 56. Nc7+ Kd7
{ In his book, Kasparov writes that he was already reconciled to a loss, yet  56...Kd6  would have given Black a rather elementary draw since White is unable to keep his extra pawns. Surprisingly, even after the text, Black is still able to make a draw, but his task has gotten much more difficult:   56...Kd6  57.Ne8+  White's best try.   57.Nxa6  Bxf3  58.Kxf6  Kd5  59.Nc7+  Kxd4  60.Nxb5+  Kc4  .  White is up two pawns to none, but the distant king on f6 makes all the difference, and Black simply captures all White's pawns.  57...Ke7  58.Nxf6  Bxf3  59.Kf5  Kd6  Despite being up a pawn, White can not improve his position, since moving the knight from f6 will immediately be answered by ...Kd5, activating the king. }
57. Nxa6 Bxf3 58. Kxf6 Kd6 59. Kf5 Kd5 60. Kf4 Bh1 61. Ke3
{ One would expect that being up two clean pawns, this should be easily winning for White. Yet, the position is still within the realms of a draw. This reminds me of the famous quote 'The worst bishop is still better than the best knight'. }
61... Kc4 62. Nc5 Bc6 63. Nd3 Bg2 64. Ne5+ Kc3 65. Ng6 Kc4 66. Ne7 Bb7
{ Only this is the decisive mistake.   The only move was  66...Bh1  , keeping the bishop on the other side of the board. The reason for this becomes clear after White's next move. }
67. Nf5 Bg2
{ To make a draw, Black needed to be able to play  67...Kd5  and meet  68.Kd3  with  68...Be4+. However, in the current position, the king, unfortunately, obstructs the bishop. Now it is also clear why the bishop should have been on h1 instead.   In his book, Kasparov writes that he should have chosen  67...Kd5  regardless as the best defense, but one can imagine however that Kasparov had already resigned himself to a defeat, as the endgame indeed does seem rather hopeless now. }
68. Nd6+ Kb3 69. Nxb5 Ka4 70. Nd6
{ Black resigned, since after  70...Kxa3  the b-pawn simply promotes. A legendary game, which shows how you can drift into a slightly passive position if one does not utilize opportunities to dynamic play early on in the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal - Paul Keres, Bled/Zagreb/Belgrade 1959"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 c5 3. c4 e6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3
O-O 9. Bg5 Be6
{ As it turns out, besides  9...cxd4  and @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2n2n2/2pp2B1/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 8 9@@EndFEN@@  9...c4  , there's even a third move. This one is the least good of the three as it is rather passive and already commits the bishop to e6. In other variations, it is typical that the bishop goes to g4 instead, for example. }
10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Na4
{ The simple, yet strong  11.Rc1  would have given White a rather significant advantage instead. }
11... Bb6
{ A highly creative concept by Keres, as he not only gives up the bishop but allows the doubling of his pawns as well. Although not entirely correct, one has to give marks to Keres for playing in such an imaginative way.   The usual  11...Be7  would have been better, but then again, this game may not have made it to the Model Games section in that case. }
12. Nxb6 axb6
{ So Black's pawn structure is ruined, and he has a bad bishop on e6. Yet, as we will see, the game will turn around in just a few moves. Keres his concept is based on the activity of pieces @@StartBracket@@note the rook on a8!@@EndBracket@@, as well as quickly exchanging light-squared bishops with ...Qd7 and ...Bh3. If White does not deal with this accurately, they may quickly find themselves to be in trouble. }
13. Nd4 h6 14. Bf4
{ Already a slight misstep. The bishop would stand better on e3, targeting the b6-pawn.   Actually, the best would have been to play  14.Nxe6!  . Although this improves Black's pawn structure, this exchange prevents the plan carried out by Keres in the game, and the two bishops by White will reign supreme in the long run. }
14... Qd7 15. a3
{ Once again, it would have been better to play  15.Nxe6  , but Tal, not realizing the importance of this makes a slow move, ensuring that the a-pawn is defended. In doing so, he allows Keres to carry out his master plan to full completion. }
15... Bh3
{ The key idea, as Black will be able to enjoy great control over the light squares after the exchange of bishops. Moreover, the bishop on f4 and knight on d4 are no longer strong pieces and will easily be attacked by the black army as will become apparent over the next few moves. }
16. Qd3 Rfe8 17. Rfe1 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Re4
{ Due to the absence of light-squared bishops the rook can occupy this fantastic square, immediately forcing White's knight back. }
19. Nf3 Rae8
{ In the space of just a couple of moves, Keres has been able to fully coordinate his army, which is now exercising great pressure upon the White position. }
20. Bd2 { When Tal starts retreating his pieces, you know something is off! }
20... d4
{ An opportunity to push the d-pawn should always be taken. By pushing forward, the d5-square is being cleared for either the black queen or knight to occupy. }
21. e3
{ An attempt at exchanging some material, but in doing so the knight on f3 loses its protection, something which Keres will be able to fully exploit. }
21... Qd5
{ The perfect square for the queen, especially making the white knight and king feel not so safe on the long diagonal. }
22. exd4 Rxd4
{ 22...g5!?  I was wondering about this move, creating a devastating threat of ...g4, but it turns out that White can still save himself by a miracle  23.h3  White must force the h-pawn to h5 first.  23...h5  24.Bxg5!  This exchange sacrifice is strictly necessary.  24...Rxe1  25.Rxe1  Rxe1  26.Bxf6  Ne5  A great idea, utilizing both the pin on the knight as well as on the pawn. Unfortunately, it still does not bring the full point home after  27.Bxe5  Rxe5  Black is much better, but White is not dead yet. }
23. Rxe8+ Nxe8 24. Qe2 Nd6
{ Despite trading some pieces, White remains in a tough spot, with the knight being pinned and the black pieces being extremely active. Note how especially the light squares in White's camp are extremely weak, something that Keres most likely foresaw when he played 11...Bb6 all the way back. }
25. Be3
{ Already an inhuman amount of accuracy was needed to keep White in the game. The text is quite logical, but as we will see White can no longer keep everything together now. }
25... Rd3 26. Kg1 Nc4
{ Once the knights start jumping, you know it's bad for White. All sorts of threats start to appear such as ...Nxb2, or ...N6e5, going after White's king. The engines already give an advantage of a magnitude of approximately -5! }
27. Ne1 Rb3 28. Rc1 Nxe3
{ Exchanging the powerful knight for the dumb bishop, but Black does win a pawn while retaining all his positional plusses. }
29. fxe3 Qe5 30. Ng2 Rxb2
{ As they would write in the old Soviet books, 'the rest is a matter of technique'. It takes Keres some time to convert his advantage into a full point, but Tal never really gets a chance to get back in it. }
31. Qd3 Qe6 32. Nf4 Rb3
{ A clever tactic by Keres, forcing the exchange of a set of major pieces. }
33. Rc3 { 33.Nxe6  Rxd3  is equally hopeless as another pawn falls. } 33...
Rxc3 34. Qxc3 Qe4
{ Once again, the black queen centralizes itself beautifully in the center of the board, from where it can do maximum damage. As is well known, the queen+knight combination can be a dangerous attacking duo, and Keres will soon start attacking the white monarch. }
35. Qb3 b5 36. Qxb5
{ Allowing Black a passed pawn after an eventual ...b4 would not offer any hope either. }
36... Qxe3+ 37. Kf1 Qf3+ 38. Kg1 Qe3+ 39. Kf1 g5
{ Before engaging his own knight into the fray, Keres first forces the enemy knight to retreat. }
40. Ne2 Ne5
{ Excellent judgement, as Black can afford to give back his extra pawn in order to create serious mating threats. }
41. Qxb7 Nd3 42. Qc8+ Kg7 43. Qf5
{ The direct mating threat on f2 has been parried, but Keres will now attack from another angle. }
43... Qd2 44. Nd4 Qe1+ 45. Kg2 Qe3
{ Keres is being extremely accurate, as this attack on the knight forces White to defend in rather awkward ways. }
46. Qd5
{ Moving the knight elsewhere would allow ...Qe2+. After this, however, Black starts chasing the white king all over the board, picking up a couple of pawns in the process. }
46... Qf2+ 47. Kh3 Qf1+ 48. Kg4 Nf2+ 49. Kf5 Qd3+ 50. Ke5 Ng4+ 51. Kd6 Qxa3+
{ After capturing White's only remaining hope, the game is basically over. Tal plays on for a while, but with the king being chased around the board while being down material, the game is over. }
52. Kc7 Qe7+ 53. Kc8 Ne3 { It's important not to blunder the queen to Nf5+. }
54. Qb5 Qe4 55. Qb2 Kg6 56. Qb6+ f6 57. Ne6 Nc4 58. Qa6 Ne5 59. Nc7 Qc2 60. Qd6
Qxh2 { Slowly but surely all White's pawns start disappearing. } 61. Nd5 Qf2
62. Kb7 Qxg3
{ The most practical decision, as the g- and h-pawns will slowly but surely walk themselves to promotion. }
63. Qxf6+ Kh5 64. Qe6 Ng4 65. Ne7 Qf3+ 66. Kc8 Kh4 67. Nf5+ Kh3 68. Kd8 h5
{ Black's king is the safest I have ever seen! } 69. Qg6 Ne5 70. Qe6 Ng4 71.
Qg6 Ne5 72. Qe6 Qd3+ 73. Nd4+ Ng4 74. Qd5 Nf2 75. Kc8 h4 76. Qe5 Qe4 77. Qf6
Qf4 78. Nf5 Ne4 79. Qe6 Qg4 { Finally, Tal decided, enough is enough. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Arjun Erigaisi - Rauf Mamedov, Warsaw 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ Arjun Erigaisi has quickly established himself as one of the most promising youngsters in the world, whereas Rauf Mamedov is a big expert on the Tarrasch Defence, having employed it many times. }
1... d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3
O-O 9. Bg5 c4
{ Having looked at several historic games featuring  9...cxd4  , and even @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2n2n2/2pp2B1/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 7 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be6  , we definitely must include a game in the variation that I am recommending. }
10. Ne5 Be6 11. f4
{ Arjun, true to his style, chooses the most aggressive approach. } 11... Ng4
12. Bxe7
{ As can be found in the theoretical chapters, this promises Black a good game.   Instead,  12.Nxg4  is the critical variation. }
12... Nxe7 13. Qd2 Nxe5
{ Although in some variations it is typical to give White the central mass in order to play on the Queenside, here it was unnecessary.   13...Nh6  would have been a cute idea since White's powerful central knight will soon be dislodged after ....f6. }
14. fxe5 Rb8
{ Mamedov starts his Queenside play, and despite not having the best version, it still remains a strong @@StartBracket@@and the only available@@EndBracket@@ plan. }
15. a4
{ It is useful for White to include this, since eventually the a-file shall be opened, meaning that the a1-rook will be activated. }
15... a6 16. e4
{ Certainly White has to use his central pawn mass to his advantage, and Arjun does exactly that. }
16... b5 17. axb5 axb5
{ Black is simply continuing his simple plan of advancing the pawn mass. Although White may be slightly better, it appears that the position is harder to play for them, as it is not exactly clear what to aim for. }
18. exd5
{ Releasing the tension in the center seems to help Black more than White.   Activating the rook along the a-file with  18.Ra6  would have been an interesting alternative. The threat of Rd6 needs to be taken seriously.  18...dxe4  19.Nxe4  b4!  All that matters is to push those Queenside pawns! There is already a serious idea of playing ...c3 bxc3 b3, creating a dangerous passed pawn. Stockfish 15 claims White is a bit better, but in a practical game, anything can happen. }
18... Nxd5 19. Ne4
{ Once again,  19.Ra6  with the idea of Rd6 was worthy of consideration. Arjun instead centralizes his knight, perhaps looking for an attack, but for the moment it is still quite far away. }
19... b4 { Pushing those pawns down the board! } 20. Rac1 Rc8 21. Rf2 Qa5
{ Generally speaking, I'd be wary of removing the queen from the Kingside, but here everything seems to work out well for Black. The idea of playing ...c3 is becoming virtually unstoppable and White better come up with some counterplay real fast. }
22. Ng5 { The right spirit, targetting the h7-pawn. } 22... c3 23. Qd3 g6 24.
b3
{ A terrible error, ensuring that the c3-pawn will live forever.   By this point, it was high time to pull the emergency brake and exchange some pieces:  24.Nxe6  fxe6  25.Bxd5  A rather ugly solution, but already better options were scarce.  25...Qxd5  26.Rxf8+  Rxf8  27.bxc3  Rf3  28.Qd2  b3!  Not letting the opponent off the hook so fast.  29.c4  It does seem that this gives enough play to maintain the balance, as White's passed pawns also start pushing. }
24... Qa3 25. Rb1 Qa7
{ A practical decision by Mamedov, bringing the queen back just in case.   The computer points out  25...Bf5  as winning, but it requires nerves of steel. The key point is that  26.Rxf5  runs into  26...c2!  when the c-pawn promotes. }
26. Rc1
{ It is hard to judge the Arjun, especially considering this is a rapid game. After this move, there is no getting back, however.   The last chance once against consisted of exchanging on e6:  26.Nxe6  fxe6  27.Rxf8+  Rxf8  28.Bxd5  exd5  .  I have to say that this position looks absolutely horrendous, but magically White can get some counterplay going after  29.e6  . The e-pawn can be protected with Re1, and White keeps on fighting. }
26... Qa3 27. Rb1 Qa7 28. Rc1 Rfd8
{ Having repeated moves a couple of times, Mamedov brings his rook on the semi-open d-file. The d-pawn is the juicy target. At the same time, White would love to get some kind of attack going, but his pieces are too tied up to taking care of the c-pawn that there simply is no way. }
29. g4
{ Creating the idea of bringing the queen over to h3, but this is dealt with rather effectively. }
29... Qe7
{ Forcing the knight from its attacking outpost deprives White of any illusions of starting an attack. }
30. Ne4 Bxg4 31. Qg3 Be6 32. Ng5 c2
{ Just before the game is over, Mamedov makes a hasty decision, allowing Arjun one more chance of struggling. There was no need to push the c-pawn from its eternal safety on c3.   32...Nc7  This surprising, yet strong retreat would have brought the game to a swift conclusion as the d-pawn will soon fall.  33.Qh4  h5  Parrying the mating threat, while ideas such as ...Qd7 or ...Nb5 will be decisive next move. }
33. Ne4
{ 33.Nxe6  fxe6  34.Rcxc2  Rxc2  35.Rxc2  Eliminating the c-pawn was strictly necessary, still after  35...Nc3  Black is much better, with the dominating knight and the weak d4-pawn. }
33... Qa7
{ Now it's back to being completely winning for Black, as his forces penetrate the position. }
34. Nc5 Nc3 35. Qe3 Nd1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Igor Bondarevsky - Paul Keres, Soviet Union 1951"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8.
dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nbd2
{ A variation that is usually played by those who are familiar with the pseudo-wisdom of blocking isolated pawns. Instead, as I have stated many times in the course, isolated pawns should be attacked instead. Now Black already has the upper hand as early as move nine! }
9... O-O 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Nbd4 Re8 12. b3 Nxd4
{ In the course I recommend  12...Ne4  , which may be a touch more accurate.  After the move played in the game, Black retains a comfortable position, though. }
13. Nxd4 Bg4
{ The lack of pressure on the isolated pawn allows Black extremely smooth and good development. Already there is an idea of ...Bxd4 followed by ...Bxe2, winning a pawn. }
14. Re1
{ This can't be good, however. The f2-pawn will be exceptionally weak and be exposed to various tactics.   It was better to play  14.Bb2  , ignoring the idea of ...Bxd4 since it will give White two bishops in return. }
14... Ne4 { No need to worry about f3, since there's the ...Nc3 resource. } 15.
Bb2 Qg5
{ All of Black's pieces occupy brilliant squares. You won't see a better Tarrasch than this! }
16. Qd3 h5
{ A typical plan, which apparently has not been popularized by AlphaZero but by Paul Keres instead! The h-pawn rushes down the board, and will soon be a strong unit in the attack. Note that f3 is still unplayable due to ...Nc5. }
17. e3 h4 { No stopping this pawn. } 18. f3
{ Finally White opts for this but leaves his Kingside chronically weakened in the process. Truth be told, already the position was terrible. }
18... Nc5 19. Qd2 Bh5 20. g4 Bg6
{ White has managed to defend against the first wave of attack, but the second one is coming right away. First up is the threat of ...Nd3, which has to be dealt with. }
21. Bf1 h3
{ Always nice to see the h-pawn make it to h3 unscathed. It will prove to be a prominent force in the attack. }
22. Rac1 Rad8
{ Keres slowly builds up the attack.   22...f5  The engine already suggests direct means of breaking open White's Kingside.  23.Bxh3  fxg4  24.Bxg4  Nd3  is a nice sample line, when White will at least lose the exchange if not more. }
23. b4 Nd7
{ Allowing White off the hook, and missing a pretty piece sacrifice as well.   Of course,  23...Ne4!  was screaming to be played!  24.Qe2  Perhaps Keres was more worried about White not accepting the offer, but now the knight can reroute itself to the amazing c4-square.   24.fxe4  Qxg4+  25.Kf2  Rd6  followed by ...Rf6, with a swift checkmate.  24...Nd6  followed by ...Nc4, with disastrous effects. }
24. Bxh3 Ne5
{ This certainly looks highly dangerous well, with ...Nc4/d3 in the air. Bodnarevsky finds a way to keep everything together for the moment. }
25. f4 { The knight must be eliminated. } 25... Qh4 26. fxe5 Qxh3 27. Qg2 Qh6
28. Qg3
{ Somehow White has managed to restore some coordination in his camp, as everything is defended and he is up a pawn after all. Yet, the black position remains easier to play as the two bishops remain a powerful force. }
28... Be4 29. g5
{ 29.Nf5  might have been better since Black is practically forced to give up on his light-squared bishop.  29...Bxf5  Allowing Nd6 is completely unfeasible.  30.gxf5  d4  Black has enough activity for a draw, but no more. }
29... Qg6 { Now, at least Black manages to retain his bishop pair. } 30. Ne2
Rc8 { Contesting the c-file is a good idea. } 31. Bd4 Rc4
{ After squandering his advantage a couple of moves ago, Keres is back to playing strong chess. Capturing the rook will give Black a strong passed pawn, but leaving it be is not pleasant either. }
32. Rxc4
{ The computer recommends the cold-blooded  32.a3  instead, but the text is far more human since at least the situation clarifies a bit after the trade of rooks. }
32... dxc4 33. Qf4 Bd3
{ Black is back to being quite a bit better since despite being down a pawn, all of White's pawns are easy targets and they are bound to fall sooner or later. }
34. Nc3 Rd8
{ I like this move, but the computer has even better ideas in mind:  34...f6!  . Noticing this move is not easy at all, but once noticed its strength becomes clear. White has no way of keeping everything together and is bound to lose some material.  35.exf6  Bxd4  36.Qxd4  Qxg5+  37.Kh1  Re6!  Another powerful engine move, continuing the attack. White is in a world of trouble. }
35. Kf2 Bxd4 { Cashing in. } 36. exd4 Qb6 37. Qe3 Rxd4 38. Nb5
{ So far Bodnarevsky has been doing a good job defending a tough position, but now he collapses.   38.e6!  was necessary, probably giving White enough counterplay to salvage a draw. }
38... Rf4+
{ In this endgame, the black bishop combined with the passed c-pawn proves too much to handle for White. }
39. Kg3 Qxe3+ 40. Rxe3 Rf1 41. e6 fxe6 42. Rxe6 a6 43. Nd4
{ Now the c-pawn marches on, but either way there was no way of maintaining a blockade as  43.Nc3  would have been met by  43...Rc1  . }
43... c3 44. Re8+ Kh7 45. Rc8 c2
{ Using the fact that  46.Nxc2  loses due to  46...Rc1  . } 46. Nb3
{ Stopping the pawn one square before queening, but it won't matter. } 46...
Kg6 47. h4 Bf5 48. Rc7 Rh1 49. Kg2 Be4+ { Keres spots a direct win. } 50. Kf2
Bc6 51. Ke3 c1=Q+ 52. Nxc1 Rxc1 53. a4 Rb1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bent Larsen - Garry Kasparov, Niksic International 1983"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. b3
{ A reasonable choice, often played by players who don't wish to enter the heavy theory battles ensuing after either  9.dxc5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bg5  . }
9... Ne4
{ Kasparov shows excellent understanding, as this idea is typical in lines where White plays b2-b3. }
10. Bb2 Bf6
{ The ...Ne4+...Bf6 combination is very strong, and not easy to deal with for White. }
11. Na4 Re8
{ In the theory chapter, I recommend the slightly different  11...cxd4  . Kasparov's choice is by no means bad either. }
12. Rc1 b6
{ An ambitious approach by the 13th World Champion, as he tries to keep the central tension to a maximum. }
13. dxc5
{ Larsen continues along the critical path, imposing hanging pawns on Black, actually a structure that is not seen as frequently in the Tarrasch Defence. }
13... Bxb2 14. Nxb2 bxc5 15. Na4
{ This was the point - the knight returns to a4 and attacks the c5-pawn. Black now must come up with inventive ways of seeking counterplay, since it's not feasible to try and hang on to the pawns. }
15... Ba6 { The only reasonable way. } 16. Re1
{ The e2-pawn must be protected.   16.Nxc5  Nxc5  17.Rxc5  Bxe2  ends badly for White. }
16... c4 17. Nh4
{ Here, Larsen goes astray. One knight on the rim is alright, but two is one too many.   17.bxc4  In order to fight for an advantage White must carry on along this route.  17...Bxc4  18.Nd2!  Nxd2  19.Qxd2  Rc8  After a couple of trades, a typical Tarrasch-Esque position has been reached once again.  Although structurally White is better, Black's pieces, most notably the bishop on c4 are well positioned. A complicated battle lies ahead. Actually, this specific position has been reached twice before in correspondence games, both ending in draws. }
17... Qa5
{ An excellent find by Kasparov, as the queen stands excellently here, and moreover, the d8-square is being cleared for the a8-rook to occupy. }
18. Nf5 g6
{ The simple  18...Rad8  would have been better, as the knight on f5 is actually not threatening anything. }
19. Nd4 Rac8 20. h4
{ After this White is officially in a world of hurt.   There was no longer any time to waste, and White needed to hurry to cause some disharmony in the black camp:  20.Bh3!  would have been just the way to do so, as Black has to create a small weakness in order to deal with the threat of Bxc8.  20...f5  The only way in order not to lose material, but the Black king on g8 no longer feels as secure after this.   20...Rc7  21.Nxc6  Rxc6  22.Bd7  would be winning for White.  21.Nxc6  Rxc6  22.Bg2  It is hard to evaluate this position since although Black is super active, everything appears rather vulnerable. As usual, the engine calmly claims 0.00s! 😃 }
20... Ne5
{ Now, everything is working in perfect harmony together for Black. The knight is ready to jump to g4, the c-pawn can be pushed any time and White lacks any tricks. }
21. Bh3 Rc7 22. Nc2
{ A sign of a desperate man, as falling back with the knight can not be good. }
22... cxb3
{ One of the several wins that Black has at its disposal.   The engine also suggests rather rough ways such as  22...Nd3  , completely crushing White. }
23. axb3 Bc8
{ Not giving anything away, but slightly complicating the task.   23...d4!  This stunning blow would have completely torn White's position to pieces, as the tactics in the subsequent variations show. It is precisely this type of play that we look for when playing the Tarrasch Defense!  24.Nxd4  Nxg3!  The crux of the combination! The e-file is being cleared.  25.fxg3   25.Rxc7  does not help White's cause either.  25...Qxc7  26.fxg3  Ng4!  Another bombshell! Suddenly g3 is being attacked, and White can not defend it. Once again, White is hopeless.  25...Rxc1  26.Qxc1  Nd3!  That's why the e-file had to be cleared - game over. }
24. Bg2 Ng4
{ This looks rather crushing as well, with the knights on e4 and g4 being two of the most menacing knights one can imagine. }
25. Rf1 Bd7
{ Despite retaining an enormous advantage, this lets White slightly off the hook.   25...Ba6!  This rather surprising retreat of the bishop would have been the killer blow, as the e2-pawn is subject to many tactics.  26.Nd4  seems like the natural human choice, but after the calm  26...Rec8  27.Rxc7  Qxc7  White is still helpless to the great number of threats such as ...Nxg3, or ....Nxf2 in some sort of order. }
26. Ra1 Bxa4
{ Having missed the direct wins, Kasparov decides to transition the game into more technical territory where he still retains a pleasant advantage. However, the prospect of quickly winning the game is no longer there. }
27. Rxa4 Qc3 28. Bxe4 dxe4 29. e3
{ After this, the material will liquidate some more.   It was also possible to play  29.Na3  instead, bringing the knight back into the game via either b5 or c4. }
29... Qxb3 30. Rxe4
{ This was Larsen's idea, forcing a short tactical skirmish, finally leading to an endgame. }
30... Rxe4 31. Qd8+ Kg7 32. Qxc7 Rc4 33. Nd4 Rxc7 34. Nxb3
{ It's nothing short of a miracle, but white is still alive. Yet, even after all those adventures, he retains an unpleasant position as the outside passed a-pawn remains a source of worry. }
34... Rc2 35. Nd4 Ra2
{ If White were able to activate the rook, a draw would not be far away, but as it is, his rook is being forced to keep protecting the f2-pawn passively. }
36. e4 { Slowly preparing to untangle through f3. } 36... Rd2 37. Nc6 a6 38. e5
Re2 39. Ra1 Rxf2 40. Rxa6
{ Generally speaking, a 3v3 endgame should make for an easy draw, but here matters are not so simple as White's pawns are all separated and the king is cut on the first rank. }
40... Rc2 41. h5
{ This a smart idea by Larsen, as the defending side typically desires to exchange as many pawns as possible. }
41... Kh6 42. hxg6 hxg6 43. Ra4 Kg5 44. Nd4
{ Although objectively there is nothing wrong with this, it does sharpen the play as White in essence gambits one of his pawns.   It would perhaps have been more practical to keep the status quo with  44.Ra6  , asking Black to show his plan. }
44... Rc3 45. e6
{ This was Larsen's plan since although he loses the g3-pawn, he hopes that the far advanced e6-pawn will prove sufficient for a draw. }
45... Rxg3+ 46. Kh1
{ Although this objectively draws the game, it seems rather strange to me to allow the king to be cut off.   The alternative of  46.Kf1  seems more practical to me. }
46... f5 47. e7 Re3 48. Nc6 f4 49. Ra5+
{ It is a bit of a mystery to me why Larsen decided to force the Black king forward, yet even this does not spoil anything objectively.   The cute  49.Ra3  would have been far simpler though, forcing Black's rook off the third rank. }
49... Kh4 50. Ra8 Nf6 51. Kg2
{ Finally, Larsen cracks under the enormous pressure of having defended a tough position for hours on end.   It was not too late to still save the game with the study-like  51.Kh2  . It is essential to keep the black king out, while not allowing Black to advance the f-pawn with check. This is the only way of doing so.  51...f3   51...Re2+  52.Kg1  Kg3  53.Ra3+  f3  54.Rxf3+  Kxf3  55.Nd4+  Ke3  56.Nxe2  Kxe2  57.Kg2  this being a draw, is another of the key points.  52.e8=Q!  Another tough move, giving up the only asset in White's position. As it turns out, it is essential to distract the Black pieces, even if just for a moment.  52...Nxe8   52...Rxe8  53.Rxe8  Nxe8  54.Ne5=  53.Ra4+  Kg5  54.Kg3  Activating the king at last, with a draw in sight. }
51... f3+
{ Now it's all over, as the Black army forms a mating net around the white king. }
52. Kf1 Kg3 53. Nd4 Ng4 54. Nxf3 Rxf3+ 55. Kg1 Nh2 56. Rf8 Rc3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ding Liren - Nihal Sarin, chess.com 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This recent rapid game was a serious test of the course, since it followed my given main line all the way through. }
1... d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e3 c4 8. Be2
Nbd7 9. O-O Bb4 10. Ne5 O-O 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Bf3
{ So far we have been following the main variation of the 5.Bg5 variation.   Only here, Nihal slightly deviates from  13...Kh8  as is given in the course. }
13... Kg7 14. a4
{ A rather unorthodox move, as this enables the bishop on b4 to not be challenged. On the other hand, White does stop any plan of quickly advancing on the Queenside and renders this more important. }
14... b6
{ The direct  14...a6  would be a grave positional error due to  15.a5!  . Therefore Black has to include this move first. }
15. Ne2 Bd6
{ Nihal is clearly very familiar with the intricacies of the position as he plays another very accurate move. White would have loved to bring the knight closer to the Kingside, but now after either Ng3 or Nf4 Black will happily capture the knight. }
16. Nc3 Bb4 { Asking White if they want a draw. } 17. Qc2
{ Ding, of course declines the silent draw offer. } 17... Rac8
{ Slightly improving the rook.   There was nothing wrong with  17...Bf5  either, but as will become clear, Nihal desires to push his pawn to f5 instead.  18.e4?!  may seem slightly worrying, but in fact, it only backfires after  18...Bg6  when the White center is under a great deal of pressure. }
18. Rfd1 f5
{ With the last couple of moves White clearly had been preparing the thrust e3-e4. With the text, Nihal effectively stops this idea. Although the computer does not entirely approve of this move, I quite like it as after this it is no longer as clear what White should aim for now. }
19. g3 a6 { Black, on the other hand, has a straightforward plan! } 20. Ne2
{ You know chess is tough when the engine recommends  20.Ra2  as its first line! }
20... Bd6 { We have seen this little dance before. } 21. b3
{ Ding decides to open some avenues on the Queenside himself before the Black pawn storm gets too strong. A decent plan, but it does give Black a passed pawn which might well become very strong very soon. }
21... b5
{ Following the plan set in motion ages ago.   Actually, there was another idea but that would have been incredibly hard to spot in a rapid game:  21...f4!  An amazing idea offered by the silicon machine, clearing the f5-square for the bishop.  22.gxf4  Other captures are worse.  22...Bf5  23.Qb2  c3!  Another striking pawn sacrifice! The point is to lure all White's pieces away from the Kingside.  24.Nxc3  Bb4  The following complications are Stockfish-level difficult, but I shall still show them for their beauty.  25.Rdc1  Rxc3!  26.Rxc3  Be4!  27.Bxe4  dxe4  White is up an exchange and two pawns, but the king is about to be given a whirlwind of checks. Actually, the game should rather quickly end in a perpetual check.  28.Kh1  Qh3  29.Rg1+  Kh8  30.Rcc1  Qf3+  31.Rg2  Ba3!  A final stunning blow, luring the queen away from the long diagonal.  32.Qxa3  Rg8  33.Rcg1  Rxg2  34.Rxg2  Qd1+  35.Rg1  Qf3+  A beauty of a variation. }
22. axb5 axb5 23. bxc4 Rxc4
{ The right recapture.   After  23...bxc4  24.Nc3  the c-pawn would easily be blockaded. The b-pawn, however, is much harder to stop. }
24. Qb3 Rfc8 25. Ra5 Rb4 26. Qa2 Ra4
{ Fantastic play by Nihal, who correctly judges that giving up the d-pawn is well worth it to manufacture the outside passed a-pawn. }
27. Rxa4 bxa4 28. Bxd5 a3
{ That's one strong pawn over there! Moreover, as is well known a queen is not a great blockader of a passed pawn, and this is no exception. }
29. Bxe6 Qxe6 30. d5 Qe4 31. Nd4
{ One mistake is all it takes, as it's immediately game over.   It was not too late to salvage the game with some swift counterplay:  31.Qa1+!  was necessary, when Black is being faced with a difficult choice.  31...Kg8   31...f6  the other attempt, but here too, White manages to find adequate counterplay.  32.Nf4!  The knight ventures to either e6 or h5, with enough threats to compensate for the dangerous a-pawn.  32.Qf6  a2  This seems very tempting, but it brings no more than a draw.  33.Qxd6  Qb1  34.Rxb1  axb1=Q+  35.Kg2  Qe4+  36.f3  Qxe3  37.Nf4  . There is no mate, and White has a fortress. }
31... Rb8
{ Ding must have missed this subtle move. Suddenly the rook is threatening to come all the way down the board to b2, with devastating effect. }
32. Nb3 { A sad move to make, but the only way to stop ...Rb2. } 32... Qc4
{ With White being completely uncoordinated Nihal convincingly brings the full point home. }
33. Qa1+ Kg6
{ No fear! White is unable to create a single threat and the position collapses as the Black forces infiltrate. }
34. Na5 Qe2 35. Re1 Qxe1+ { Finishing in style. } 36. Qxe1 a2 *

