[Black "Sasa Martinovic - Rustam Kasimdzhanov, Bundesliga 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Bg5 Be6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8.
e4
{ I noticed that Rustam Kasimdzjanov had been picking up the Tarrasch recently with some good results. }
8... Nd7
{ I do not mention this idea in the course, but Kasimzhanov had done his homework as this is the second choice of the computer besides  8...dxe4  . Actually, I did know about this move but was not entirely satisfied.  As with many contemporary ideas, they only work well for one game, and then are left to be never seen again. This might be one of those, as it clearly confused Martinovic and brought a shock effect on him. }
9. Nxd5
{ Not the most critical, most likely  9.Bb5  is a more serious test, after which I was not fully happy with Black's prospects. Capturing a pawn does seem very logical, though. }
9... Bxd5 10. exd5 O-O-O
{ As can be seen in the theoretical chapters, castling Queenside is not uncommon at all in these variations. White is up a pawn momentarily, but the d5-pawn will soon be recaptured, giving Black full equality. }
11. Be2 Kb8 12. O-O Nb6
{ Going after the d5-pawn, which will be captured next move. Already, it seems as if the Black position might be a tad easier to play since his pieces will be more active than White's. }
13. dxc5
{ Allowing Black to develop the bishop with tempo is rather strange.   13.Rc1  Rxd5  14.Qc2  seems more accurate, using the fact that Black can not take on d4 due to the back-rank checkmate idea.  14...cxd4??  15.Qc7+  Ka8  16.Qc8+  Nxc8  17.Rxc8 }
13... Bxc5 14. Qc2 Rxd5 15. Rad1
{ White can not have been happy about the opening outcome, so perhaps already he is trying to steer the game into dryer territory. Kazimdzhanov on the other hand does his best to keep the game complicated. }
15... Rc8
{ A clever way of bringing the rook into the game with tempo, as ...Bxf2 is now threatened. }
16. Qb1
{ The queen already has to retreat to slightly passive squares.   16.Qxh7  Qxb2  can only be beneficial to Black. }
16... g6
{ Taking Qxh7 out of the equation once and for all, and also putting the pawns on light-squares - the colour of White's bishop. A typical strategy in opposite-coloured positions, as it will restrict the opponent's bishop as much as possible. }
17. Nd2 Bb4 18. Ne4
{ Although the knight appears to be standing well in the center of the board, it will soon be kicked away.   18.Nb3  placing the knight here instead of e4 looks a little strange at first, but a closer look reveals that things are quite alright here for White. The bishop will go to f3, and the knight does a good job taking away the c5-square for Black's bishop. Had Martinovic chosen to play this way, he would have been completely fine. }
18... Rxd1 19. Rxd1 Qe5
{ Centralizing the queen and getting ready to kick White's knight away from its central outpost. Already, Black is starting to get a slightly better position. }
20. a3 f5
{ Not strictly necessary, as the simple  20...Be7  would have been entirely playable as well.  Kasimdzjanov wishes to complicate and unbalance the game as much as possible, though and with this move, he manages to do exactly that. }
21. axb4 fxe4
{ After a somewhat unusual trade of pieces, the position has become much sharper. In the long run, White's bishop may prove stronger than the black knight, but on the other hand, there are some weak pawns on the Queenside that are prone to attack. Moreover, Black's centralized queen hampers White's piece activity. }
22. Bg4
{ A first real step in the wrong direction as it allows the Black rook to infiltrate. Perhaps, Martinovic was hoping to create some sort of an attack, but as we will see Black has everything under control.   22.g3  should have been preferred, creating some air for the white king just in case, and waiting for Black to show his cards.  22...Nd5  Perhaps Martinovic was worried about the knight jumping to the center, but after  23.b5  White keeps a good degree of control over the position, whereas the queen can rejoin the game via a2. }
22... Rc4 23. b3 Rxb4 24. Rd8+
{ What can be more natural than this check, forcing the Black king away from its secure hiding place. However, this may well prove to be the final mistake, as the White forces will lack the coordination to create an attack.   The sophisticated engine suggestion  24.Qc1!  would have allowed White to remain well in the game, as besides the direct threat of mate in 1, the queen can be activated to e3 or even h6.  24...a6  25.Rd8+  Ka7  26.Qe3  .    Although being down a pawn, White has sufficient compensation with the active pieces. }
24... Kc7 25. Rf8 Nd5 26. Rf7+ Kb6
{ Black is completely centralized, and although the king has been chased to b6, it is surprisingly safe there. If White were able to engage the queen in the attack, things may be different but as it is there is no way of doing so and Black is simply winning. }
27. Bc8 Ne7 { Covering against the threat of Rxb7+. } 28. Bh3 e3
{ Now it's Black's turn to start an attack of his own, and take some more pawns as well! }
29. fxe3 Qxe3+ 30. Kh1 Rxb3
{ Black is up two full pawns, and it is hard to envision a scenario of White creating even a hint of a threat. }
31. Qd1 Rc3 32. Qd8+ Kc5
{ No fear whatsoever by Kasimdzhanov, as he marches the king forward some more! }
33. Qa5+ b5 34. Qxa7+ Kb4
{ An amazing display of steel nerves. White has been able to recapture a pawn but has run out of checks. Meanwhile, the mating threats on the back rank force White to exchange queens and enter a losing endgame. }
35. Qxe3 Rxe3 36. Kg1 Kc3
{ There's no need to care about the h7-pawn being under attack as the b-pawn is ready to be promoted. }
37. Bd7 b4 38. Ba4 h6
{ Preserving the h-pawn at last.   38...b3  would be a grave error, as it allows White to transition into an endgame that may be drawable  39.Bxb3  Kxb3  40.Rxh7  . Due to the limited material, this is most likely a draw. Therefore, Black does need to keep the h-pawn. }
39. Kf2 Re5 40. Rf3+ Kd2
{ Black's king really is the star of this game! It is something of a pity that it does not quite do a touchdown and reach the first rank. }
41. Rb3 Nd5 42. Bc6
{ This almost seems to save White, as there is a threat of Bxd5 and Rxb4, but Black has everything under control. }
42... Nf4 { This cute tactic ensures that Black remains comfortably winning. }
43. Kf3 { 43.Rxb4  Nd3+  is the point. } 43... Nd3
{ White resigned, as besides being down a pawn, his forces are entirely dominated and the b-pawn is unstoppable. }
*

